42
00:02:39,839 --> 00:02:40,680
[SPEAKER_21]: Yeah, thank you very much.

43
00:02:41,981 --> 00:02:46,865
[SPEAKER_21]: So yeah, there's a bunch of things that were done, I guess, and ongoing things too.

44
00:02:48,206 --> 00:02:51,668
[SPEAKER_21]: You know, obviously the big stuff that people are going to notice is going to be done on the capital budgets.

45
00:02:51,688 --> 00:02:53,390
[SPEAKER_21]: We're not here to talk about that right now, but.

46
00:02:53,850 --> 00:02:59,073
[SPEAKER_21]: I think most of the notably to think about it is there wasn't anybody position for a long time.

47
00:02:59,093 --> 00:03:01,414
[SPEAKER_21]: We're relying on an outsourced vendor to do a lot of the work.

48
00:03:01,874 --> 00:03:05,095
[SPEAKER_21]: We had a consultant come in, Jim Silver, obviously you all know him.

49
00:03:05,115 --> 00:03:09,437
[SPEAKER_21]: He's done a great job, I think, stabilizing things and keeping the business running.

50
00:03:10,098 --> 00:03:12,639
[SPEAKER_21]: And I've kind of taken over from there all day three.

51
00:03:13,679 --> 00:03:20,803
[SPEAKER_21]: But yeah, I think, you know, a lot of the foundational stuff like inventories and knowing what we have, what we don't have are things under maintenance.

52
00:03:21,623 --> 00:03:35,209
[SPEAKER_21]: We're ongoing with that and then putting in policy procedures around, you know, cybersecurity awareness training, you know, how do we handle data, you know, and archive data and data sensitivity and privacy and things like that.

53
00:03:36,369 --> 00:03:43,232
[SPEAKER_21]: So we'll continue on with those sorts of things and we'll continue to see where the gaps are, what we need to upgrade and what we need to do.

54
00:03:44,052 --> 00:03:47,474
[SPEAKER_21]: I think the budget itself has gone up a little bit.

55
00:03:47,874 --> 00:03:49,755
[SPEAKER_21]: This is just what we'd call, you know,

56
00:03:50,735 --> 00:03:54,658
[SPEAKER_21]: to run the business budget in the private sector, but it's just keeping the lights on essentially.

57
00:03:55,418 --> 00:04:06,705
[SPEAKER_21]: I think the increase in expense is that there's a lot of software that needs some upgrades here and there, just sort of desktop things, you know, maintenance costs go up year over year, things like that.

58
00:04:06,805 --> 00:04:12,669
[SPEAKER_21]: So, but I'll open up the questions to any of you have and poke holes in my theorems.

59
00:04:13,109 --> 00:04:13,910
[SPEAKER_15]: Questions from the council.

60
00:04:17,023 --> 00:04:17,624
[SPEAKER_15]: Councilor Carvilla.

61
00:04:18,364 --> 00:04:21,107
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, Madam President, and welcome.

62
00:04:21,187 --> 00:04:33,519
[SPEAKER_20]: I know you've only been here a couple of days, so it's going to be kind of hard to figure out where you're at, but I think one of the big questions that we've all asked is about how protected are we from what you've seen.

63
00:04:35,601 --> 00:04:41,083
[SPEAKER_21]: Yeah, I think it's a great question, because I think it's a lot of concern.

64
00:04:41,103 --> 00:04:44,984
[SPEAKER_21]: You know, I think what happened in the Lowell Law Ritz, they were locked down for a number of days.

65
00:04:45,804 --> 00:04:47,204
[SPEAKER_21]: It's becoming more and more common.

66
00:04:47,705 --> 00:04:51,886
[SPEAKER_21]: I come from a background of being an analyst and working in cybersecurity to some degree.

67
00:04:53,086 --> 00:04:54,627
[SPEAKER_21]: So ransomware is the main attack point.

68
00:04:54,667 --> 00:04:55,387
[SPEAKER_21]: They try to get people.

69
00:04:56,287 --> 00:05:01,548
[SPEAKER_21]: One of the interesting things about it is that it's not necessarily they're getting into your system and stealing your stuff.

70
00:05:01,908 --> 00:05:03,269
[SPEAKER_21]: It's social engineering.

71
00:05:03,489 --> 00:05:07,230
[SPEAKER_21]: So it's calling someone up and saying, hey, I work directly for the mayor.

72
00:05:07,330 --> 00:05:08,670
[SPEAKER_21]: You know, she's trying to get into an account.

73
00:05:08,710 --> 00:05:09,991
[SPEAKER_21]: Can you reset her password for me?

74
00:05:10,031 --> 00:05:12,111
[SPEAKER_21]: Let me know what it is, type of thing.

75
00:05:12,211 --> 00:05:17,432
[SPEAKER_21]: So we need to be better, I think, about communicating and get that to people like this is how they're going to get your kind of thing.

76
00:05:17,973 --> 00:05:23,014
[SPEAKER_21]: As far as the system itself, I think the level of

77
00:05:23,654 --> 00:05:31,200
[SPEAKER_21]: So the security we have around the servers and the application of that is what you'd expect to see to some degree.

78
00:05:31,681 --> 00:05:36,624
[SPEAKER_21]: As we upgrade things like the network going into next year, we can do a lot more things around that for sure.

79
00:05:36,644 --> 00:05:40,287
[SPEAKER_21]: A lot more monitoring, see where things are, the traffic's going, things like that.

80
00:05:42,566 --> 00:05:51,350
[SPEAKER_21]: Like nothing's 100% foolproof as my first day in IT, the security told me, you know, firewalls don't keep people out, they tell you when someone got in.

81
00:05:52,290 --> 00:05:57,692
[SPEAKER_21]: But I think we're as good as we can be right now, but we can always try to do better and modernize at the time.

82
00:05:57,852 --> 00:06:03,495
[SPEAKER_20]: Have you been able to take stock of some of the hardware that the different departments have that probably need?

83
00:06:03,815 --> 00:06:05,515
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, I see some of the old stuff.

84
00:06:05,675 --> 00:06:06,436
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, sure.

85
00:06:06,456 --> 00:06:09,057
[SPEAKER_20]: Have you had a chance to make some type of assessment yet?

86
00:06:09,532 --> 00:06:12,213
[SPEAKER_21]: I mean, I've certainly taken mental notes as I've gone through.

87
00:06:12,233 --> 00:06:13,993
[SPEAKER_21]: I haven't gone through a full inventory yet.

88
00:06:14,053 --> 00:06:16,134
[SPEAKER_21]: I definitely want to get that done sooner rather than later.

89
00:06:16,154 --> 00:06:26,197
[SPEAKER_21]: And then when we start figuring out the capital plans for next year, obviously we'll start at the bottom and work our way up, you know, as far as what's the oldest and most vulnerable type of thing.

90
00:06:26,677 --> 00:06:27,797
[SPEAKER_21]: I think that's part of the problem.

91
00:06:27,837 --> 00:06:29,618
[SPEAKER_21]: This building is a lot of equipment is really old.

92
00:06:30,118 --> 00:06:32,481
[SPEAKER_21]: So you can you can see I'm, you know, I'm up on the third floor.

93
00:06:32,982 --> 00:06:39,469
[SPEAKER_21]: And, you know, that's probably the worst part of the network and I actually feel that so I definitely want to make that a priority for sure.

94
00:06:39,489 --> 00:06:43,514
[SPEAKER_21]: Thank you.

95
00:06:43,554 --> 00:06:43,915
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah.

96
00:06:44,475 --> 00:06:44,896
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

97
00:06:45,216 --> 00:06:47,239
[SPEAKER_27]: Welcome to Medford and welcome to the city council.

98
00:06:47,259 --> 00:06:47,559
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

99
00:06:49,202 --> 00:06:52,025
[SPEAKER_27]: I was curious, since you're a relative outsider.

100
00:06:53,046 --> 00:06:58,552
[SPEAKER_27]: What are your impressions of our needs in city in the city of Medford in City Hall.

101
00:06:59,292 --> 00:07:02,676
[SPEAKER_27]: When it comes to it when it comes to the software and the hardware.

102
00:07:03,256 --> 00:07:08,442
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm not thinking about, you know, dollar amounts that might be attached to anything but in terms of need.

103
00:07:09,216 --> 00:07:11,678
[SPEAKER_21]: Sure, that's a good question.

104
00:07:11,998 --> 00:07:21,266
[SPEAKER_21]: Um, so just to be clear I lived in Medford for 18 years, I only escaped across the line like a half a mile into summer school about five years ago and that was just because my rent went up.

105
00:07:22,567 --> 00:07:29,112
[SPEAKER_21]: But, uh, and that was one of the reasons why you know when I was in Medford and living in Medford and interacting City Hall.

106
00:07:30,586 --> 00:07:33,569
[SPEAKER_21]: I found it a little frustrating that I had to do everything manually.

107
00:07:33,709 --> 00:07:37,792
[SPEAKER_21]: I get a piece of paper, fill it out, walk it down to City Hall and do whatever.

108
00:07:38,573 --> 00:07:39,694
[SPEAKER_21]: And it was fine for me.

109
00:07:39,854 --> 00:07:42,816
[SPEAKER_21]: I work in tech, so I can just tell my boss I'm gonna take off for a couple hours, do whatever.

110
00:07:42,876 --> 00:07:44,558
[SPEAKER_21]: But for most people, they just can't do that.

111
00:07:45,278 --> 00:07:48,861
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm like, why are we leveraging technology to make things easier?

112
00:07:49,982 --> 00:07:56,588
[SPEAKER_21]: You think of customers, internal customers, the people that work here, and external constituents, how they interact with City Hall.

113
00:07:58,609 --> 00:08:01,293
[SPEAKER_21]: I think there's a lot of things we can do to modernize, to make things easier.

114
00:08:01,513 --> 00:08:05,518
[SPEAKER_21]: I see people doing their work, people doing a lot of repeated processes.

115
00:08:05,539 --> 00:08:06,500
[SPEAKER_21]: I don't like that.

116
00:08:06,640 --> 00:08:08,102
[SPEAKER_21]: I've never liked that as an IT person.

117
00:08:08,122 --> 00:08:09,504
[SPEAKER_21]: I'd say, well, that should be automated.

118
00:08:09,544 --> 00:08:11,407
[SPEAKER_21]: You have to do it over and over the same way again.

119
00:08:11,947 --> 00:08:14,651
[SPEAKER_21]: Well, we have to do it this way because the system doesn't let us automate it.

120
00:08:14,711 --> 00:08:15,212
[SPEAKER_21]: or what have you.

121
00:08:15,232 --> 00:08:17,053
[SPEAKER_21]: So there's a lot of opportunities for things like that.

122
00:08:17,994 --> 00:08:20,557
[SPEAKER_21]: Obviously, you can't boil the ocean, you know, everything costs money.

123
00:08:20,577 --> 00:08:26,682
[SPEAKER_21]: So you kind of have to prioritize what's the best bang for your buck when spending money, what's the ROI, as we'd say.

124
00:08:27,903 --> 00:08:31,106
[SPEAKER_21]: So yeah, but there are things for sure that we could certainly help people with.

125
00:08:31,527 --> 00:08:40,035
[SPEAKER_21]: But again, it all comes back to what I was saying earlier about the foundational work, let's get the network bandwidth going the way it should be so people can be more effective without having delays and slowdowns.

126
00:08:40,395 --> 00:08:44,338
[SPEAKER_21]: There's certain things that are going to have to happen first before other projects can move forward.

127
00:08:44,498 --> 00:08:45,919
[SPEAKER_21]: So it's going to have to happen serially.

128
00:08:46,919 --> 00:08:52,163
[SPEAKER_21]: But once we put together that list, I think we can move pretty quickly on a lot of things.

129
00:08:55,085 --> 00:09:02,049
[SPEAKER_27]: I don't know if you've gotten a chance to review the goals, the stated goals, since I assume you weren't here helping to develop them.

130
00:09:02,069 --> 00:09:06,512
[SPEAKER_27]: But you mentioned that the budget that we have is basically keeping lights on.

131
00:09:07,594 --> 00:09:13,779
[SPEAKER_27]: does the budget that we have in front of us allow you to accomplish at least some of these goals that are, that have been set?

132
00:09:13,899 --> 00:09:15,320
[SPEAKER_21]: So there's two sections of the budget.

133
00:09:15,340 --> 00:09:18,743
[SPEAKER_21]: We have what we call, you know, sort of the BAU business as usual.

134
00:09:18,803 --> 00:09:25,329
[SPEAKER_21]: This is like, you know, someone's computer dies on a second floor and I have to swap it out or I want to upgrade some of the machines.

135
00:09:25,409 --> 00:09:31,253
[SPEAKER_21]: I want to pay for licenses, maybe expand licensing because someone, you know, wants to use the same program or you have to do hires.

136
00:09:32,374 --> 00:09:33,595
[SPEAKER_21]: The capital expenditures,

137
00:09:34,556 --> 00:09:36,498
[SPEAKER_21]: That's a whole different barrel over there.

138
00:09:36,678 --> 00:09:43,146
[SPEAKER_21]: That's the really big ticket items, but the ones that bring you up to where, you know, now we can start.

139
00:09:43,166 --> 00:09:49,173
[SPEAKER_21]: For instance, finance department, they've been talking about like, you know, we really should get on a more modern financial package.

140
00:09:50,463 --> 00:10:01,853
[SPEAKER_21]: Most of those things now are cloud-based, which are great for a lot of things, disaster recovery, reporting, the whole nine yards, but they require a lot more bandwidth to go out and in.

141
00:10:01,893 --> 00:10:07,698
[SPEAKER_21]: And so he's gonna be dependent on me finishing my part before he can even think about doing his part kind of thing.

142
00:10:08,979 --> 00:10:13,643
[SPEAKER_21]: So yeah, so the capital projects are definitely the more cool kind of technology stuff.

143
00:10:13,984 --> 00:10:15,225
[SPEAKER_21]: This budget here is just the,

144
00:10:15,765 --> 00:10:19,187
[SPEAKER_21]: you know, keyboards, mice, and, you know, desktop software, that kind of stuff.

145
00:10:19,267 --> 00:10:21,969
[SPEAKER_21]: But it's still important stuff people have to work under the child to know.

146
00:10:22,630 --> 00:10:22,890
[SPEAKER_21]: Thanks.

147
00:10:23,150 --> 00:10:24,371
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

148
00:10:25,311 --> 00:10:27,233
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, thanks.

149
00:10:27,673 --> 00:10:28,053
[SPEAKER_03]: Welcome.

150
00:10:28,333 --> 00:10:29,414
[SPEAKER_03]: Good to have you here.

151
00:10:29,934 --> 00:10:33,417
[SPEAKER_03]: Really getting in front of the gauntlet on day three.

152
00:10:35,818 --> 00:10:36,939
[SPEAKER_03]: Just a couple questions.

153
00:10:37,699 --> 00:10:44,904
[SPEAKER_03]: One on what you were talking about, kind of how a lot of our processes are still paper processes, and that also really

154
00:10:45,830 --> 00:10:48,994
[SPEAKER_03]: limits the ability to share data kind of with the public about what's happening.

155
00:10:52,253 --> 00:11:03,102
[SPEAKER_03]: what can we do to at least try to implement like more of an open data policy for the city and what resources would you need so that your department can make basic city statistics and information more accessible to the public?

156
00:11:03,723 --> 00:11:06,625
[SPEAKER_03]: As far as what's an example?

157
00:11:07,846 --> 00:11:11,269
[SPEAKER_03]: Like, you know, how many building permits were issued this year?

158
00:11:11,329 --> 00:11:13,591
[SPEAKER_03]: Or, you know, I know we have that data in the building department, right?

159
00:11:13,631 --> 00:11:17,435
[SPEAKER_03]: But I'm kind of thinking envisioning something like something

160
00:11:17,955 --> 00:11:25,959
[SPEAKER_03]: I mean, I know we're not going to have the resources to do this right away but something kind of like summer stat in Somerville where you have a bunch of city statistics and information available in a single place.

161
00:11:26,459 --> 00:11:37,024
[SPEAKER_03]: And I guess kind of a tangential part of that question is, is your role as an IT director also working on kind of public information the city website, that kind of thing.

162
00:11:37,717 --> 00:11:39,498
[SPEAKER_21]: I think that's handled the communications department.

163
00:11:40,818 --> 00:11:42,699
[SPEAKER_21]: Certainly, we haven't had any discussions about that.

164
00:11:43,460 --> 00:11:45,140
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm open to what makes sense anywhere.

165
00:11:45,941 --> 00:11:49,843
[SPEAKER_21]: But as far as data aggregation, data reporting, I'm all for it.

166
00:11:50,943 --> 00:11:54,545
[SPEAKER_21]: The problem you get yourself into is years and years of legacy systems.

167
00:11:55,065 --> 00:11:56,666
[SPEAKER_21]: and being able to aggregate that data.

168
00:11:57,926 --> 00:11:59,247
[SPEAKER_21]: So you have two methods.

169
00:11:59,287 --> 00:12:03,809
[SPEAKER_21]: You either find some way to bring it, unify it on one umbrella, which is a huge capital expense.

170
00:12:05,049 --> 00:12:11,512
[SPEAKER_21]: You hire a bunch of people just to do, you know, actuarial work, you know, data aggregation and crunching data scientists type people.

171
00:12:13,412 --> 00:12:15,313
[SPEAKER_21]: Or you have to look at the silos of data.

172
00:12:15,333 --> 00:12:16,594
[SPEAKER_21]: What are the most important ones?

173
00:12:16,654 --> 00:12:18,515
[SPEAKER_21]: What can't they report on now easily?

174
00:12:18,675 --> 00:12:23,176
[SPEAKER_21]: I think a report should just be one button because the report was written and you can run it as many times as you want.

175
00:12:24,897 --> 00:12:31,720
[SPEAKER_21]: Can we get them what we need in software-wise upgrade or to a new model package to get that data out?

176
00:12:31,780 --> 00:12:34,582
[SPEAKER_21]: But I'm all about, you know, data doesn't lie, right?

177
00:12:34,802 --> 00:12:36,102
[SPEAKER_21]: You know, you can make assumptions.

178
00:12:36,823 --> 00:12:41,085
[SPEAKER_21]: People can say whatever they want, but if the data back up any assertion, then you win the argument.

179
00:12:41,545 --> 00:12:42,945
[SPEAKER_21]: And it's also good just for people to see.

180
00:12:42,985 --> 00:12:45,686
[SPEAKER_21]: Like you said, let's see how many permits are going.

181
00:12:45,706 --> 00:12:50,087
[SPEAKER_21]: Our permitting office actually issues a high number of permits in a relatively short amount of time.

182
00:12:50,387 --> 00:12:53,048
[SPEAKER_21]: They're a high-functioning group, that kind of stuff.

183
00:12:54,048 --> 00:12:54,868
[SPEAKER_21]: I'm all for that.

184
00:12:54,908 --> 00:12:55,468
[SPEAKER_21]: I think it's great.

185
00:12:55,548 --> 00:13:11,312
[SPEAKER_21]: But when you're dealing with 20-, 30-year-old computer systems, it can be pretty tough to do that, unless you have staff that just are in report-writing roles, which nobody really has the appetite nowadays to really fund that anymore, unfortunately.

186
00:13:12,233 --> 00:13:15,395
[SPEAKER_21]: But back in the old days, we used to have just report writers that did that sort of stuff.

187
00:13:16,595 --> 00:13:17,536
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

188
00:13:18,156 --> 00:13:26,862
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, the interesting thing is, you know, I was talking to Jim Silva, who was, you know, working on this before you came on board.

189
00:13:27,182 --> 00:13:31,185
[SPEAKER_03]: And he was talking about how we kind of have different IT universes for the city.

190
00:13:31,265 --> 00:13:36,849
[SPEAKER_03]: You know, some people, you know, City Hall is in one section, the police stations in another, libraries in another.

191
00:13:37,469 --> 00:13:38,630
[SPEAKER_03]: Schools are in a whole other world.

192
00:13:39,397 --> 00:13:42,820
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, you know, each of those entities releases reports, right?

193
00:13:43,380 --> 00:13:46,042
[SPEAKER_03]: But it's sometimes they live in one place or another.

194
00:13:46,083 --> 00:13:58,372
[SPEAKER_03]: I guess my question is, um, what, you know, either do you have any plans or intentions to try to bring together these different IT environments under a single infrastructure?

195
00:13:58,813 --> 00:13:59,393
[SPEAKER_03]: And if

196
00:14:02,683 --> 00:14:07,730
[SPEAKER_03]: if yes, or how big of an investment would that take, or what can you do with your existing resources?

197
00:14:08,391 --> 00:14:18,686
[SPEAKER_21]: The most effective model that we use, or used to use, out in the private sector is called the shared services model, where everybody, IT is just one department of services everywhere.

198
00:14:19,727 --> 00:14:21,729
[SPEAKER_21]: And it's just the easiest way to do things.

199
00:14:21,749 --> 00:14:28,272
[SPEAKER_21]: So you don't end up with five redundant different systems, because five different departments bought the same time and attendance system.

200
00:14:28,633 --> 00:14:31,775
[SPEAKER_21]: I worked for a company that had 300 different time and attendance systems.

201
00:14:32,175 --> 00:14:34,376
[SPEAKER_21]: We consolidated it down to one.

202
00:14:34,416 --> 00:14:35,477
[SPEAKER_21]: We picked one and went with it.

203
00:14:36,017 --> 00:14:37,278
[SPEAKER_21]: And it saves you money.

204
00:14:37,418 --> 00:14:43,101
[SPEAKER_21]: And it makes, like you said, reporting a lot easier across the whole aggregate business, whether you're a corporation or government.

205
00:14:44,482 --> 00:14:57,191
[SPEAKER_21]: I would like to see that eventually, but we have, I think we have a ways to go before we can get there just because we are in those different universes where the police department is in library are probably up here and a lot of the other apartments are somewhere down here.

206
00:14:57,211 --> 00:15:01,874
[SPEAKER_21]: We have to bring everyone back up to that level before we can think about that.

207
00:15:02,375 --> 00:15:06,057
[SPEAKER_21]: But I'm always there to assist or advise or what have you.

208
00:15:06,658 --> 00:15:08,439
[SPEAKER_03]: Would you say that there's funding in

209
00:15:09,482 --> 00:15:11,924
[SPEAKER_03]: your capital budget to make some progress on that?

210
00:15:12,144 --> 00:15:14,245
[SPEAKER_21]: I haven't even gone through the capital budget in detail yet.

211
00:15:14,626 --> 00:15:16,047
[SPEAKER_03]: Gotcha, nope, totally understood.

212
00:15:17,007 --> 00:15:19,609
[SPEAKER_03]: If when you do, feel free to send me an email.

213
00:15:19,649 --> 00:15:19,949
[SPEAKER_03]: Thanks.

214
00:15:20,950 --> 00:15:21,951
[SPEAKER_03]: All good, thanks, Madam President.

215
00:15:22,771 --> 00:15:24,252
[SPEAKER_15]: Any questions from councilors on Zoom?

216
00:15:27,314 --> 00:15:27,655
[SPEAKER_02]: No, ma'am.

217
00:15:29,096 --> 00:15:29,576
[SPEAKER_15]: Councilor Knight.

218
00:15:31,938 --> 00:15:32,498
[SPEAKER_02]: No questions.

219
00:15:33,819 --> 00:15:34,259
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

220
00:15:35,020 --> 00:15:36,040
[SPEAKER_15]: I just have one.

221
00:15:36,060 --> 00:15:37,802
[SPEAKER_15]: So prior to you,

222
00:15:38,841 --> 00:15:43,346
[SPEAKER_15]: Maybe a little ways prior to that to the department, you said 2 people looking at a staffing level.

223
00:15:43,386 --> 00:15:45,368
[SPEAKER_15]: I know we've been here for a week.

224
00:15:45,568 --> 00:15:52,196
[SPEAKER_15]: I mean, is there for a city of our size and the age of our systems is there a preferred staffing level?

225
00:15:52,216 --> 00:15:54,038
[SPEAKER_15]: I know you'll make do with what you have, but.

226
00:15:54,625 --> 00:15:57,568
[SPEAKER_21]: Yes, staffing levels is an interesting subject.

227
00:15:57,649 --> 00:15:59,911
[SPEAKER_21]: It's also religious war in some companies.

228
00:16:00,812 --> 00:16:04,516
[SPEAKER_21]: There's no golden rule for it because everybody has a different set of systems.

229
00:16:04,556 --> 00:16:05,958
[SPEAKER_21]: Some are more high maintenance than others.

230
00:16:06,399 --> 00:16:07,400
[SPEAKER_21]: What I want to say is this.

231
00:16:08,161 --> 00:16:10,523
[SPEAKER_21]: If you can outsource stuff,

232
00:16:12,145 --> 00:16:16,708
[SPEAKER_21]: That's repetitive and low-hanging fruit, sort of lower-level work.

233
00:16:17,549 --> 00:16:20,991
[SPEAKER_21]: You should always look to do that because it's going to save you a heck of a lot of money in the long run.

234
00:16:21,512 --> 00:16:27,016
[SPEAKER_21]: If you look at some of the municipalities around here that are even smaller in effort, they have five or six people in the IT staff.

235
00:16:27,556 --> 00:16:33,040
[SPEAKER_21]: They're just going around doing whatever, fixing people's print drivers and really mundane tasks.

236
00:16:34,081 --> 00:16:36,042
[SPEAKER_21]: But when you look at the amount they're spending on staff,

237
00:16:37,324 --> 00:16:41,770
[SPEAKER_21]: They could do it a heck of a lot cheaper by what we chose to do here.

238
00:16:41,790 --> 00:16:46,797
[SPEAKER_21]: We have Toss that does the help desk stuff, and it works great, and they're a really good company.

239
00:16:47,659 --> 00:16:48,981
[SPEAKER_21]: We save a lot of money by doing that.

240
00:16:49,001 --> 00:16:51,504
[SPEAKER_21]: If we had to staff up three or four people, the problem you get is

241
00:16:52,777 --> 00:16:56,479
[SPEAKER_21]: municipalities aren't going to pay as much as corporate America are going to.

242
00:16:57,080 --> 00:16:58,060
[SPEAKER_21]: It's just a reality.

243
00:16:58,741 --> 00:17:03,483
[SPEAKER_21]: Also, trying to find people in IT qualified to do IT work is next to impossible.

244
00:17:03,924 --> 00:17:09,407
[SPEAKER_21]: I mean, even some of the bigger tech companies struggle to find qualified people to fill positions.

245
00:17:09,887 --> 00:17:13,850
[SPEAKER_21]: So being able to have this third party that has 26 or 28 people that can

246
00:17:16,511 --> 00:17:21,435
[SPEAKER_21]: at any moment, you know, handle an issue for a user or even for our servers, back end stuff.

247
00:17:21,935 --> 00:17:26,999
[SPEAKER_21]: That's pretty invaluable and considering what we're paying for, we're getting great value out of it.

248
00:17:27,179 --> 00:17:28,540
[SPEAKER_21]: I think it's a smart way to go.

249
00:17:28,580 --> 00:17:30,982
[SPEAKER_21]: I think it's eventually you'll see other towns around here.

250
00:17:31,002 --> 00:17:33,744
[SPEAKER_21]: I think it's a legacy thinking they have to have a big staff.

251
00:17:34,065 --> 00:17:35,866
[SPEAKER_21]: I think they'll eventually start looking towards this model.

252
00:17:36,386 --> 00:17:36,607
Okay.

253
00:17:37,587 --> 00:17:37,887
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

254
00:17:38,748 --> 00:17:41,510
[SPEAKER_14]: Any other questions?

255
00:17:42,631 --> 00:17:43,091
[SPEAKER_14]: Seeing none.

256
00:17:43,552 --> 00:17:44,152
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you so much.

257
00:17:44,252 --> 00:17:44,533
[SPEAKER_14]: Excellent.

258
00:17:44,573 --> 00:17:44,833
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

259
00:17:45,822 --> 00:17:48,344
[SPEAKER_15]: All right, we will go to building and code enforcement.

260
00:17:48,364 --> 00:17:48,924
[SPEAKER_15]: That is page 153.

261
00:17:48,964 --> 00:17:54,768
[SPEAKER_15]: We have Building Commissioner Forti here for us at 153.

262
00:17:55,269 --> 00:18:01,533
[SPEAKER_15]: So total expenditures for building and code enforcement is $1,885,531, an increase of $85,178, 8.51% over the prior year.

263
00:18:11,292 --> 00:18:15,135
[SPEAKER_15]: If you want to tell us any highlights or anything about the budget.

264
00:18:15,316 --> 00:18:17,257
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Madam President, counselors Thank you.

265
00:18:17,738 --> 00:18:31,209
[SPEAKER_01]: So, we're really nothing outside of the norm here this year we're not asking for any capital items, you may have seen that we've kind of improved the conditions down in our department it's become.

266
00:18:32,090 --> 00:18:33,452
[SPEAKER_01]: more cleaner and friendlier.

267
00:18:34,593 --> 00:18:43,343
[SPEAKER_01]: You'll notice that there is a large flat screen at the front counter now that allows us to help people that were having some difficulty with the computer.

268
00:18:44,184 --> 00:18:46,246
[SPEAKER_01]: I determined that that was one thing that we were lacking.

269
00:18:46,466 --> 00:18:47,948
[SPEAKER_01]: We're able to get that taken care of.

270
00:18:49,228 --> 00:18:52,229
[SPEAKER_01]: I've been in charge of the department a little over eight months now.

271
00:18:52,829 --> 00:18:59,651
[SPEAKER_01]: So a lot of what I have been able to accomplish with my staff over the past eight months has mostly been housekeeping.

272
00:19:00,612 --> 00:19:04,433
[SPEAKER_01]: I will tell you that my staff are very competent.

273
00:19:04,533 --> 00:19:05,233
[SPEAKER_01]: They're versatile.

274
00:19:06,193 --> 00:19:12,195
[SPEAKER_01]: They have been able to function without a department head, a direct department head for a few months there.

275
00:19:12,275 --> 00:19:14,076
[SPEAKER_01]: And they did a fantastic job.

276
00:19:15,836 --> 00:19:23,663
[SPEAKER_01]: I have really no predictions outside of what we're using here this year.

277
00:19:23,763 --> 00:19:27,706
[SPEAKER_01]: I would say that the biggest thing is projected revenue.

278
00:19:27,866 --> 00:19:38,295
[SPEAKER_01]: I believe that it's going to increase exponentially with a couple of things that have been initiated by me as the building commissioner.

279
00:19:39,236 --> 00:19:39,876
[SPEAKER_01]: I find that,

280
00:19:41,476 --> 00:19:59,847
[SPEAKER_01]: We were lacking in permit fees, due to underestimated building permit values, and these things aren't really a big deal when you're talking about small homeowner jobs and stuff like that but some of the commercial work that is occurring and what I'm projecting as what's coming up in the city.

281
00:20:00,788 --> 00:20:12,742
[SPEAKER_01]: I now require by code that a final cost affidavit be submitted at the end of every job prior to the issuance of a certificate of occupancy, which is the authorization under the state building code.

282
00:20:13,443 --> 00:20:14,764
[SPEAKER_01]: I've initiated that policy.

283
00:20:14,844 --> 00:20:16,747
[SPEAKER_01]: I've given people plenty of warning.

284
00:20:17,227 --> 00:20:24,733
[SPEAKER_01]: so that they know what's coming and I'm expecting that to generate a significant amount of additional revenue to the city.

285
00:20:25,393 --> 00:20:27,895
[SPEAKER_01]: I found that our permit fees were lacking this year.

286
00:20:28,015 --> 00:20:33,019
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm going to say that a good portion of that was due to the raising of the interest rates.

287
00:20:33,559 --> 00:20:37,822
[SPEAKER_01]: I feel as though a lot of people may have hesitated in doing some of the projects.

288
00:20:38,082 --> 00:20:41,365
[SPEAKER_01]: We are seeing pretty good permit counts, but there are a lot of small stuff.

289
00:20:42,386 --> 00:20:53,496
[SPEAKER_01]: But what I see on the drawing board coming up in the next five years, I think that we're going to be in a very different place as far as revenue stream from the building department.

290
00:20:54,497 --> 00:20:56,559
[SPEAKER_01]: We also have been able to.

291
00:20:57,940 --> 00:21:01,241
[SPEAKER_01]: curb the overtime bill a little bit, make it a little bit more efficient.

292
00:21:01,301 --> 00:21:11,585
[SPEAKER_01]: So when, when we're called out on a code enforcement call, um, it's fines are an automatic, um, fines are issued automatically to help pay for the overtime costs.

293
00:21:11,605 --> 00:21:15,166
[SPEAKER_01]: Not in every case, obviously, because we have emergencies that we must respond to.

294
00:21:16,126 --> 00:21:21,811
[SPEAKER_01]: But I find that my department is one of the most responsive departments here in the city.

295
00:21:22,151 --> 00:21:24,253
[SPEAKER_01]: They do a very good job of getting back to people.

296
00:21:25,034 --> 00:21:30,358
[SPEAKER_01]: I find that there are little to no complaints about how things are handled.

297
00:21:31,439 --> 00:21:34,782
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm able to sit pretty much near the counter all day and I hear what's going on.

298
00:21:36,164 --> 00:21:49,442
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm, I'm satisfied that my, my staff is doing a great job that we're, you know, I have a very versatile staff which allows a lot of flexibility in the schedule so that people have ample time off.

299
00:21:50,223 --> 00:22:07,701
[SPEAKER_01]: Um, and, and I project over the next year that, um, revenues will increase, um, that, that some of the housekeeping issues that I put into place, um, will start to really take effect and we'll, we'll be able to, um, really advance this department forward to where I think it should be, which, you know, there's always room for improvement.

300
00:22:07,741 --> 00:22:12,185
[SPEAKER_01]: We have, uh, we have goals to achieve with, uh, scanning our, um,

301
00:22:12,946 --> 00:22:15,908
[SPEAKER_01]: you know, our plan, all of our stored plans.

302
00:22:16,808 --> 00:22:21,291
[SPEAKER_01]: That's one of the big projects that needs to be tackled over the next couple of years.

303
00:22:21,471 --> 00:22:24,552
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm going to propose that in next year's budget.

304
00:22:25,113 --> 00:22:28,194
[SPEAKER_01]: But I would just tell you that our expenses are pretty much level.

305
00:22:28,915 --> 00:22:35,038
[SPEAKER_01]: And I don't expect to be needing anything because I'm no longer in charge of public buildings.

306
00:22:35,058 --> 00:22:37,179
[SPEAKER_01]: We have a facilities director for that now.

307
00:22:37,339 --> 00:22:40,421
[SPEAKER_01]: And so we've separated most of our budget from that.

308
00:22:40,481 --> 00:22:41,502
[SPEAKER_01]: I do believe that there is,

309
00:22:42,582 --> 00:23:11,053
[SPEAKER_01]: a line item here um in the budget for um let's see i thought repair the materials and supplies that's not it i'm sorry it looks like it was it looks like it was taken out okay yeah we did have a building maintenance budget in there but it's been moved to the facilities director so yeah it's on the first yeah yeah okay okay so i i really am i'm open for questions and anything i can help with

310
00:23:11,631 --> 00:23:11,891
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

