00:23:37,237 --> 00:23:37,437
[SPEAKER_20]: I know

319
00:23:38,810 --> 00:23:46,076
[SPEAKER_20]: Dennis does the best he can, but he's just one man and you've got him going different directions.

320
00:23:46,096 --> 00:23:59,847
[SPEAKER_20]: But that's really one of the things I'd like to see is code enforcement, because even if you use the guy, the person part-time, maybe two or three days a week, there's a lot of obvious,

321
00:24:01,330 --> 00:24:05,373
[SPEAKER_20]: offenses around the city that can be, you know, which would help our curb appeal.

322
00:24:06,833 --> 00:24:21,682
[SPEAKER_20]: If the code enforcement officer was out, maybe, you know, if he dedicated two days a week, something, you know, to going around and cleaning up some of the low hanging fruit, that would, I think that would help us to the, especially the look of a lot of things.

323
00:24:23,603 --> 00:24:26,185
[SPEAKER_20]: That's really my only thing that I've ever asked for.

324
00:24:26,225 --> 00:24:29,587
[SPEAKER_20]: I say, we did get it one year and then it disappeared.

325
00:24:30,427 --> 00:24:34,050
[SPEAKER_01]: We actually have two inspectors that are dedicated to code enforcement.

326
00:24:34,511 --> 00:24:39,396
[SPEAKER_01]: Again, because of their versatility, they do building inspections on occasion.

327
00:24:40,016 --> 00:24:41,818
[SPEAKER_01]: They're mostly focused on code enforcement.

328
00:24:42,378 --> 00:24:43,199
[SPEAKER_01]: They do a great job.

329
00:24:43,239 --> 00:24:44,600
[SPEAKER_01]: Sometimes they have to team up together.

330
00:24:45,201 --> 00:24:49,825
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't want them going into a property by themselves because it's a liability for the city.

331
00:24:52,087 --> 00:24:55,651
[SPEAKER_01]: But both of those code enforcement officers are also

332
00:24:56,151 --> 00:25:12,187
[SPEAKER_01]: building inspectors and if we have one specific problem in the property I know that we had talked about auto repair stations and so forth, you know, we have the ability to be able to go ahead and task, some of that and so, you know, certainly we can, you know, we can do that, you know, with, with the current staff we have.

333
00:25:15,951 --> 00:25:31,581
[SPEAKER_20]: maybe a day or two we just go around and you know I'm not saying find people but yeah hey listen this is you're out of code on this I'll give you 60 days I suddenly want to come back please take care of it yep NSA especially a sign a signs are you know the windows and signs are

334
00:25:33,005 --> 00:25:41,351
[SPEAKER_20]: They're all out of code and there's stuff everywhere, but I think if we can start cleaning up some of that stuff, that's always been my goal.

335
00:25:41,531 --> 00:25:42,151
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay, noted.

336
00:25:42,792 --> 00:25:43,772
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

337
00:25:44,172 --> 00:25:44,473
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

338
00:25:44,793 --> 00:25:45,473
[SPEAKER_15]: Vice President Behrs.

339
00:25:47,374 --> 00:25:47,735
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

340
00:25:47,755 --> 00:25:48,295
[SPEAKER_03]: Hi, Commissioner.

341
00:25:48,335 --> 00:25:49,096
[SPEAKER_03]: How are you?

342
00:25:49,376 --> 00:25:49,776
[SPEAKER_03]: Good evening.

343
00:25:53,378 --> 00:26:00,463
[SPEAKER_03]: Just a little bit off of what Councilor Carriello's question was, is the code enforcement workload manageable for the staffing level that we have right now?

344
00:26:02,308 --> 00:26:04,128
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, I find that it is.

345
00:26:04,608 --> 00:26:09,069
[SPEAKER_01]: I will say that both of my code enforcement officers are busy all day long.

346
00:26:09,469 --> 00:26:10,990
[SPEAKER_01]: There is no blank time.

347
00:26:11,030 --> 00:26:18,491
[SPEAKER_01]: They're either out in the field, cleaning up old cases, or they're in the field, you know, addressing new problems.

348
00:26:19,951 --> 00:26:25,612
[SPEAKER_01]: I would say, currently we are adequately staffed to handle the amount of calls that we get.

349
00:26:25,672 --> 00:26:28,593
[SPEAKER_01]: Now, to Councilor Caravello's point,

350
00:26:29,393 --> 00:26:31,574
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't really go around the city and police.

351
00:26:32,154 --> 00:26:39,257
[SPEAKER_01]: And the reason why is because it's always kind of been traditional that, you know, you don't go looking for trouble because it'll find you.

352
00:26:39,277 --> 00:26:47,280
[SPEAKER_01]: And I know that that sounds dismissive, but it's not because what we don't want to do is be accused of selective enforcement.

353
00:26:48,240 --> 00:26:51,621
[SPEAKER_01]: And, you know, cities have gotten into trouble for that particular reason.

354
00:26:51,661 --> 00:26:53,722
[SPEAKER_01]: And so because we're complaint driven,

355
00:26:54,502 --> 00:26:57,504
[SPEAKER_01]: It keeps us a little bit more focused on the things that are important.

356
00:26:57,864 --> 00:27:04,929
[SPEAKER_01]: It's not that a building inspector wouldn't stop if he doesn't see a building permit card in the window or he sees something unsafe or something unsightly.

357
