[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

658
00:49:17,140 --> 00:49:19,142
[SPEAKER_03]: It's bad in the water on the water side.

659
00:49:19,902 --> 00:49:33,692
[SPEAKER_03]: Something I mentioned to you many times and will mention to Bob and Nina as well is, I think it'd be great if we could separate out the trash line from the highway budget because I think it makes the highway budget look a lot bigger than it is.

660
00:49:33,792 --> 00:49:39,697
[SPEAKER_03]: The trash is 7.9 million of the 10 million this year, and that's all just the contract that we pay out.

661
00:49:41,338 --> 00:49:44,720
[SPEAKER_03]: That's just what I think would be a really helpful way to display information in the budget.

662
00:49:49,782 --> 00:49:58,067
[SPEAKER_03]: On snow and ice removal, I think last season was the first season with the new ordinance in place.

663
00:49:58,327 --> 00:49:58,888
[SPEAKER_03]: How did it go?

664
00:50:00,351 --> 00:50:02,353
[SPEAKER_03]: with the sidewalk snow removal ordinance?

665
00:50:02,633 --> 00:50:04,975
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, with the updated snow and ice.

666
00:50:05,636 --> 00:50:16,445
[SPEAKER_26]: If I gauge it based off of complaints and requests to clear sidewalks, I think I've been doing this for a year and a half or so, and two winter seasons.

667
00:50:17,446 --> 00:50:25,653
[SPEAKER_26]: I think the understanding from the community is a little bit higher that second snow season about what they're responsible for.

668
00:50:26,053 --> 00:50:30,816
[SPEAKER_26]: But to Constant Caraviello's point, we didn't have a lot of shoveling events.

669
00:50:31,196 --> 00:50:32,256
[SPEAKER_26]: We had a lot of ice events.

670
00:50:33,177 --> 00:50:40,721
[SPEAKER_26]: And a lot of people don't, those don't land on people's radar, but they land on my radar because we spend a lot of money on salt and they're actually a tough, ice storms are tougher.

671
00:50:40,741 --> 00:50:41,761
[SPEAKER_26]: And Stevie could tell you about it.

672
00:50:41,781 --> 00:50:46,043
[SPEAKER_26]: Sometimes there's a, ice storms are just as tough, if not tougher than, you know, snow.

673
00:50:46,103 --> 00:50:54,508
[SPEAKER_26]: Sometimes I think snow, from what I hear, I don't plow, but snow is easier to deal with than snow plus melting, plus sleep, plus rain, et cetera.

674
00:50:56,383 --> 00:50:56,683
[SPEAKER_03]: Got it.

675
00:50:58,144 --> 00:50:59,184
[SPEAKER_03]: Just a couple more questions.

676
00:50:59,384 --> 00:51:04,286
[SPEAKER_03]: On parks, something that we hear a lot is just requests for restroom facilities.

677
00:51:04,346 --> 00:51:09,268
[SPEAKER_03]: I know that's a pretty significant expense, and I don't think any of our parks have restroom facilities.

678
00:51:12,069 --> 00:51:22,913
[SPEAKER_03]: When you were discussing some of the new park construction projects with the grants that the Planning and Development Sustainability Office has been bringing in in partnership with you, has that idea ever come up to bring restroom facilities into our parks?

679
00:51:25,516 --> 00:51:31,665
[SPEAKER_26]: It is, I would talk to Alicia on a little bit more about this as well.

680
00:51:31,825 --> 00:51:40,477
[SPEAKER_26]: You know I advise on these things, but I don't necessarily have, you know, have the planning hat on when these projects are being assembled and developed.

681
00:51:43,923 --> 00:51:52,986
[SPEAKER_26]: The recent projects I've seen have areas, I believe, at least one of them anyway, with dedicated areas so program can bring in portable toilets.

682
00:51:53,527 --> 00:51:56,048
[SPEAKER_26]: That's typically what happens is program brings in portable toilets.

683
00:51:57,088 --> 00:52:04,391
[SPEAKER_26]: Now, bathroom buildings, that's obviously a significant capital expense to bring in a new building.

684
00:52:04,931 --> 00:52:07,292
[SPEAKER_26]: It's not just the initial expense, it's the ongoing maintenance of that.

685
00:52:08,592 --> 00:52:25,343
[SPEAKER_26]: The DPW has played a role in the caretaking of Wright's Pond, for example, the building up there, and that bathroom seems to see significant vandalism, for example, which obviously that's a cost that falls on the city.

686
00:52:26,784 --> 00:52:28,485
[SPEAKER_26]: Would I like to see bathrooms at our parks?

687
00:52:28,925 --> 00:52:33,007
[SPEAKER_26]: Probably not if the DPW is going to be the entity managing them.

688
00:52:34,565 --> 00:52:37,749
[SPEAKER_26]: Because I don't think we're ready for that, that burden, so to speak, at the moment.

689
00:52:38,150 --> 00:52:42,035
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, it also means sewerage and utility design and all that.

690
00:52:42,436 --> 00:52:48,063
[SPEAKER_26]: So it's significant, complicated, and it would need its own initiative.

691
00:52:48,804 --> 00:52:51,067
[SPEAKER_03]: That goes kind of right to my next question, which is

692
00:52:53,334 --> 00:53:06,638
[SPEAKER_03]: and feel free to answer it, answer whichever version of this question is easier for you to answer, but do you feel like you have enough staff to do the work that the city needs DPW to do and or what would you do with additional staff that you don't have now?

693
00:53:07,758 --> 00:53:08,298
[SPEAKER_26]: That's a good question.

694
00:53:08,318 --> 00:53:13,960
[SPEAKER_26]: I think to accomplish the goals that I have, I'm a practical person when it comes down to it.

695
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:23,082
[SPEAKER_26]: So to accomplish the goals that I have with the DPW and knowing what we have to work with, I'm confident that we can satisfy those goals.

696
00:53:23,742 --> 00:53:26,963
[SPEAKER_26]: Now, the second part of your question, what would I do with more?

697
00:53:26,983 --> 00:53:31,044
[SPEAKER_26]: I don't spend too much time thinking about that.

698
00:53:32,304 --> 00:53:39,448
[SPEAKER_26]: But if there was more, I would figure out ways to spend more and have bigger, broader goals.

699
00:53:39,708 --> 00:53:43,090
[SPEAKER_03]: I guess the other way to frame it is, what are we not doing that you would like to be doing?

700
00:53:44,851 --> 00:53:46,192
[SPEAKER_26]: What are we not doing that I'd like to be doing?

701
00:53:46,252 --> 00:53:48,553
[SPEAKER_26]: I think we're touching upon everything.

702
00:53:48,573 --> 00:53:49,534
[SPEAKER_26]: I think we're doing everything.

703
00:53:49,574 --> 00:53:54,357
[SPEAKER_26]: The RDBW is big, and we do a lot of things.

704
00:53:57,756 --> 00:54:00,858
[SPEAKER_26]: The things that I can think about are more capital expenditures.

705
00:54:01,979 --> 00:54:04,161
[SPEAKER_26]: And we've touched upon here, our asset management.

706
00:54:04,681 --> 00:54:12,987
[SPEAKER_26]: Since I've been with the city, we've done an analysis, some sort of evaluation on all of our largest assets.

707
00:54:13,847 --> 00:54:22,734
[SPEAKER_26]: And as the time goes by here, we do have to think hard collectively as a city on what we do with our aging city.

708
00:54:23,094 --> 00:54:25,315
[SPEAKER_26]: So I think that's the best way to answer your question.

709
00:54:25,596 --> 00:54:27,017
[SPEAKER_26]: Those are the things that I think about.

710
00:54:27,657 --> 00:54:34,603
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, our infrastructure is getting to be, you know, the big boom in this city was 1900 to 1940, right?

711
00:54:34,643 --> 00:54:38,406
[SPEAKER_03]: So our infrastructure is getting to be 80 to 120 years old.

712
00:54:38,666 --> 00:54:39,066
[SPEAKER_26]: You got it.

713
00:54:39,266 --> 00:54:41,008
[SPEAKER_26]: And I think, you know, people see it.

714
00:54:41,508 --> 00:54:42,949
[SPEAKER_26]: You know, there's no question about it.

715
00:54:42,969 --> 00:54:43,610
[SPEAKER_26]: It's no secret.

716
00:54:43,890 --> 00:54:44,630
[SPEAKER_26]: The city is old.

717
00:54:44,710 --> 00:54:45,171
[SPEAKER_26]: It was built.

718
00:54:45,331 --> 00:54:47,132
[SPEAKER_26]: A lot of it was built in the 20s and 30s.

719
00:54:48,854 --> 00:54:51,156
[SPEAKER_26]: And that was quite some time ago.

720
00:54:51,236 --> 00:54:57,762
[SPEAKER_26]: So when you do it that way, then of course, all that infrastructure comes to age at around the same time.

721
00:54:58,002 --> 00:55:01,726
[SPEAKER_26]: And it's not like days, we're talking years, if not decades.

722
00:55:02,727 --> 00:55:06,871
[SPEAKER_25]: But like a water pipe, when you put it in the ground, you can expect 100, 120 years out of it.

723
00:55:06,891 --> 00:55:07,531
[SPEAKER_25]: So we're getting there.

724
00:55:10,334 --> 00:55:16,757
[SPEAKER_26]: So anyway, I think that's a challenge that this city faces that's beyond the scope of an operating budget.

725
00:55:17,178 --> 00:55:31,045
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, I really appreciate your focus on the asset management and the assessment of our needs for that, because I think streets, sidewalks, and buildings, that's going to be a lot on our end.

726
00:55:31,205 --> 00:55:34,346
[SPEAKER_03]: Obviously, water, sewer, a lot of the enterprise fund, but big needs there as well.

727
00:55:36,167 --> 00:55:36,868
[SPEAKER_03]: And we need to be

728
00:55:38,550 --> 00:55:44,529
[SPEAKER_03]: I think you've said it before in prior meetings, you know, if we're just doing the bare minimum to keep an old system together.

729
00:55:45,735 --> 00:55:48,717
[SPEAKER_03]: you increase the chance of catastrophic failure, right?

730
00:55:48,897 --> 00:55:50,058
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, exactly.

731
00:55:50,078 --> 00:55:51,318
[SPEAKER_26]: And that's just how the science works.

732
00:55:51,859 --> 00:55:57,322
[SPEAKER_26]: And that's how we do those evaluations, criticality, probability, risk assessment, really.

733
00:55:58,763 --> 00:56:06,508
[SPEAKER_26]: Just to give you a real easy example, is the water main feeding hospitals and schools, or is it feeding a four house subdivision?

734
00:56:06,528 --> 00:56:12,331
[SPEAKER_26]: So obviously one's going to have a higher criticality than another one.

735
00:56:13,992 --> 00:56:16,594
[SPEAKER_26]: just to give you an idea, and that's just one very simple scenario.

736
00:56:16,654 --> 00:56:24,659
[SPEAKER_26]: But it works with every asset, because if you think of pedestrian sidewalks, for example, some of our pedestrian sidewalks see a lot more feet hitting them than others.

737
00:56:25,520 --> 00:56:31,683
[SPEAKER_26]: So the public dollars, when we're assessing where they should go, we need to take that into consideration.

738
00:56:32,224 --> 00:56:36,446
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, I think it speaks to some of the work that we did with the previous commissioner on a sidewalk

739
00:56:38,167 --> 00:56:40,527
[SPEAKER_03]: priority sidewalk clearing program that the city could run.

740
00:56:41,288 --> 00:56:48,269
[SPEAKER_03]: So maybe that list of sidewalks is similar to the main focus needs of where we have a lot of foot traffic.

741
00:56:48,629 --> 00:57:01,871
[SPEAKER_26]: One of the things that I believe I shared with you, and if not me, Owen probably has, is the data from our asset management work on pavement and sidewalks and a heat map, which basically shows foot traffic densities.

742
00:57:02,411 --> 00:57:03,652
[SPEAKER_26]: So the way

743
00:57:05,492 --> 00:57:15,677
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm trying to slowly transition, and I've had support for this, slowly transition how operations and investment happens based off of data.

744
00:57:15,897 --> 00:57:26,361
[SPEAKER_26]: Because these assets are so big, we need to be thinking about them strategically and with data supporting where we put those public funds.

745
00:57:26,841 --> 00:57:27,822
[SPEAKER_26]: So I will continue to do that.

746
00:57:29,197 --> 00:57:29,377
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

747
00:57:29,417 --> 00:57:30,539
[SPEAKER_03]: I have one more question for you.

748
00:57:30,580 --> 00:57:36,130
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm asking it to police, fire, DPW and schools as the big, big four departments.

749
00:57:36,150 --> 00:57:39,396
[SPEAKER_03]: So I don't know if Chief Buckley warned you already, he said he wasn't going to.

750
00:57:41,060 --> 00:57:55,992
[SPEAKER_03]: It's not a big deal, but I think it's an important question that I'm finding a lot of value in, which is basically, are there any metrics, a metric or metrics that you use either on a daily or, you know, like kind of the daily and an annual basis to measure success?

751
00:57:56,112 --> 00:58:09,283
[SPEAKER_03]: Like if, you know, what is something, a statistic or a metric that you see that says, this was a good day for DPW or something at the end of the year, a metric or a set of metrics that you see that you say, this was a good year, we made a lot of progress as a department?

752
00:58:10,425 --> 00:58:15,746
[SPEAKER_26]: I think each division of DPW has their own metrics when it comes to that.

753
00:58:16,266 --> 00:58:25,808
[SPEAKER_26]: One of the things that I use on the day-to-day is how many tickets are coming in, how many complaints are coming in, how many issues are arising.

754
00:58:25,948 --> 00:58:26,888
[SPEAKER_26]: For example, parks.

755
00:58:27,368 --> 00:58:32,829
[SPEAKER_26]: So if we're getting a lot of complaints about ball fields, what's happening?

756
00:58:33,109 --> 00:58:33,609
[SPEAKER_26]: Something's wrong.

757
00:58:33,790 --> 00:58:35,710
[SPEAKER_26]: If we're not getting a lot of complaints about ball fields,

758
00:58:36,490 --> 00:58:37,732
[SPEAKER_26]: you know, we're probably in good shape.

759
00:58:37,772 --> 00:58:39,374
[SPEAKER_26]: I probably don't need to drive by and go look at it.

760
00:58:39,914 --> 00:58:42,137
[SPEAKER_26]: So that's kind of like the day by day, year to year.

761
00:58:44,530 --> 00:58:48,531
[SPEAKER_26]: You know, I've been at this for about a year and a half, so I want to take a rain check on that one.

762
00:58:49,551 --> 00:58:59,333
[SPEAKER_26]: But one of the things that I am doing is trying to develop metrics that are easily quantifiable, almost monthly.

763
00:59:00,314 --> 00:59:04,835
[SPEAKER_26]: You know, I gave some examples in the report, like tons of asphalt that we placed, for example.

764
00:59:05,255 --> 00:59:07,295
[SPEAKER_26]: I think it was like 275 tons last year.

765
00:59:07,956 --> 00:59:10,296
[SPEAKER_26]: Now, that number means more to some people than others.

766
00:59:10,876 --> 00:59:13,537
[SPEAKER_26]: But, you know, if, for example,

767
00:59:14,637 --> 00:59:17,539
[SPEAKER_26]: I keep in touch with all the division heads on a regular.

768
00:59:18,560 --> 00:59:30,369
[SPEAKER_26]: But if I were to see a report, and I'm not to pick on highway, I know it's here, but if I got a report and the city said, oh, this month we didn't zero tons of asphalt, then that's obviously a red flag.

769
00:59:30,389 --> 00:59:31,189
[SPEAKER_26]: But that doesn't happen.

770
00:59:32,510 --> 00:59:34,652
[SPEAKER_26]: So I know that's a small example.

771
00:59:35,292 --> 00:59:40,375
[SPEAKER_26]: But it is one of the things from an annual perspective and a monthly perspective month to month.

772
00:59:40,916 --> 00:59:46,479
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm still working on as the commissioner trying to figure out what those best metrics are to tell to tell the story.

773
00:59:46,499 --> 00:59:47,319
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah.

774
00:59:47,460 --> 00:59:48,100
[SPEAKER_26]: So great.

775
00:59:48,400 --> 00:59:48,840
[SPEAKER_26]: More to come.

776
00:59:49,361 --> 00:59:49,621
[SPEAKER_03]: Cool.

777
00:59:49,681 --> 00:59:49,921
[SPEAKER_03]: No.

778
00:59:50,021 --> 00:59:51,122
[SPEAKER_03]: And I appreciate the answer.

779
00:59:51,142 --> 00:59:56,005
[SPEAKER_03]: I would have taken what the chief Buckley's answer was, which I'll have to think about and get back to you.

780
00:59:56,125 --> 00:59:57,566
[SPEAKER_03]: So I appreciate the examples.

781
00:59:57,646 --> 00:59:59,347
[SPEAKER_25]: But well, I was thinking about it with you.

782
01:00:03,247 --> 01:00:03,827
[SPEAKER_03]: That's all I have.

783
01:00:03,847 --> 01:00:06,369
[SPEAKER_03]: I have some questions for facilities, but I'll stop there for Tim.

784
01:00:06,869 --> 01:00:07,170
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

785
01:00:07,510 --> 01:00:07,990
[SPEAKER_15]: Councillor Sagan.

786
01:00:08,250 --> 01:00:08,611
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

787
01:00:09,771 --> 01:00:13,454
[SPEAKER_27]: The questions about streets have been covered by other Councillors.

788
01:00:14,875 --> 01:00:17,036
[SPEAKER_27]: I think I wanted to ask about trees.

789
01:00:18,677 --> 01:00:22,480
[SPEAKER_27]: I know we have people here for that as well.

790
01:00:23,661 --> 01:00:30,145
[SPEAKER_27]: Do we have an idea of what the timeline is like to finish an urban forestry plan?

791
01:00:31,397 --> 01:00:34,900
[SPEAKER_26]: A timeline, it should be less than a year once we execute it, I would believe.

792
01:00:35,881 --> 01:00:54,435
[SPEAKER_26]: Now, I'm not an expert, and you can stop me at any time if you can, but what I found out just in the last probably six months, four months, there are a number of opportunities out there, both partnering with folks like the Mystic River Watershed Association or Trees Medford,

793
01:00:56,056 --> 01:00:59,079
[SPEAKER_26]: or just doing it on our own.

794
01:00:59,179 --> 01:01:04,423
[SPEAKER_26]: Grant opportunities from the MVP program, for example, is where we just applied for one.

795
01:01:05,384 --> 01:01:08,006
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm noticing that there are opportunities for trees.

796
01:01:08,627 --> 01:01:15,633
[SPEAKER_26]: And one of the things that I identified, and I had some help identifying it, is that we don't have a forestry management plan currently.

797
01:01:16,273 --> 01:01:17,613
[SPEAKER_26]: So we're piecing it together.

798
01:01:17,633 --> 01:01:23,295
[SPEAKER_26]: We didn't win one grant that we applied for, but we're trying again through MVP.

799
01:01:24,175 --> 01:01:35,939
[SPEAKER_26]: And we're also partnering with Mississippi River Watershed Association on a bigger federal grant, all in the interest of seeing if we can get an inventory of our trees completed, a full one.

800
01:01:37,920 --> 01:01:44,483
[SPEAKER_26]: the workflow to support that inventory, because once you do it, it starts aging the moment you get it.

801
01:01:44,963 --> 01:01:48,244
[SPEAKER_26]: So you get an inventory, trees start dying, we're planning new ones.

802
01:01:48,725 --> 01:01:54,427
[SPEAKER_26]: So having a process in place through GIS, ideally, where we're updating that inventory.

803
01:01:55,208 --> 01:01:59,890
[SPEAKER_26]: And then the next piece of that is having an urban forestry management plan,

804
01:02:00,470 --> 01:02:11,037
[SPEAKER_25]: where we know what species, how we should focus on that, where we're lacking, where are the hot spots, all of these things.

805
01:02:13,159 --> 01:02:14,339
[SPEAKER_26]: That's needed in the city.

806
01:02:14,379 --> 01:02:15,300
[SPEAKER_26]: We don't have it.

807
01:02:16,041 --> 01:02:18,923
[SPEAKER_26]: We're doing what we can with what we have, for sure.

808
01:02:19,563 --> 01:02:26,327
[SPEAKER_26]: But with climate change and discussions about resiliency, it's becoming more important, I think.

809
01:02:27,368 --> 01:02:32,591
[SPEAKER_26]: The folks that are issuing the grants know this too, which is why I think we're seeing some availability there.

810
01:02:33,252 --> 01:02:36,754
[SPEAKER_26]: So hopefully we are successful and I can continue the pursuit.

811
01:02:37,234 --> 01:02:44,038
[SPEAKER_27]: And I know you guys put out on that tree strategy that we got a press release for maybe a little bit more than a month ago.

812
01:02:46,319 --> 01:02:51,903
[SPEAKER_27]: On average, you guys, I think for the last two years have been planting about 200 new trees a year on average.

813
01:02:53,500 --> 01:02:56,362
[SPEAKER_27]: Is this budget basically going to keep us at 200?

814
01:02:56,443 --> 01:03:01,186
[SPEAKER_27]: Are there any cuts or increases to that plan for the upcoming year?

815
01:03:01,206 --> 01:03:05,309
[SPEAKER_27]: I didn't see any cuts.

816
01:03:06,290 --> 01:03:07,370
[SPEAKER_11]: Thanks Councilor.

817
01:03:07,390 --> 01:03:15,096
[SPEAKER_11]: We do have other funding sources coming in through ARPA and some other CPA money.

818
01:03:15,516 --> 01:03:16,577
[SPEAKER_11]: So we hope to increase it.

819
01:03:16,637 --> 01:03:17,418
[SPEAKER_11]: The goal is to

820
01:03:19,244 --> 01:03:23,226
[SPEAKER_11]: increase the number of trees planted this year, and we feel confident that we can do that.

821
01:03:23,606 --> 01:03:24,026
[SPEAKER_27]: Excellent.

822
01:03:25,567 --> 01:03:37,332
[SPEAKER_27]: Do you, would you have an idea of how many trees were planting net, you know, considering the trees that are being cut down for old age, for different reasons?

823
01:03:38,073 --> 01:03:41,354
[SPEAKER_27]: Do we have an idea as a city of how many, what that net number is?

824
01:03:42,815 --> 01:03:46,597
[SPEAKER_11]: Do you mean number of trees removed versus number of trees planted?

825
01:03:46,637 --> 01:03:46,837
[SPEAKER_11]: Yes.

826
01:03:47,953 --> 01:03:57,520
[SPEAKER_11]: This year, I believe we have probably six or 700 trees removed, which is not offset by the 200.

827
01:03:58,521 --> 01:03:59,782
[SPEAKER_27]: I see.

828
01:04:00,563 --> 01:04:01,223
[SPEAKER_27]: Okay.

829
01:04:02,544 --> 01:04:03,485
[SPEAKER_27]: That's important to know.

830
01:04:04,926 --> 01:04:06,107
[SPEAKER_27]: One last question about trees.

831
01:04:08,496 --> 01:04:15,022
[SPEAKER_27]: Well, one last question about trees is, I see that there's an inventory of types of trees are you planting.

832
01:04:15,663 --> 01:04:18,726
[SPEAKER_27]: What ages are the trees that we're planting?

833
01:04:18,766 --> 01:04:21,349
[SPEAKER_27]: Are we planting slightly older trees?

834
01:04:21,389 --> 01:04:22,670
[SPEAKER_27]: Are we planting saplings?

835
01:04:23,431 --> 01:04:25,313
[SPEAKER_27]: Or is it a wide variety?

836
01:04:25,353 --> 01:04:25,973
[SPEAKER_11]: Great question.

837
01:04:26,674 --> 01:04:32,740
[SPEAKER_11]: By contract, the tree plantings need to be two and a half to three inch caliber, which is the diameter of a small trunk.

838
01:04:33,305 --> 01:04:42,670
[SPEAKER_11]: And those are the best choices for planting new trees, because if you plant larger trees, they go through greater transplant shock, but they take much longer time to recover.

839
01:04:43,010 --> 01:04:51,915
[SPEAKER_11]: So if you plant a young, healthy tree, they begin to grow right away, where a larger tree has to put all the energy into recovery.

840
01:04:52,616 --> 01:04:57,779
[SPEAKER_11]: So it's the best practices to use that size tree.

841
01:04:58,581 --> 01:04:58,962
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

842
01:04:58,982 --> 01:05:11,564
[SPEAKER_27]: Yeah, um, I, you know, trees are something that we're starting to hear more and more from residents, especially as climate change is becoming a more ever present problem, and, um,

843
01:05:12,938 --> 01:05:20,886
[SPEAKER_27]: I would personally love to see you know when the finances are more flexible, us investing more in how much we're planting and the great work that you're doing.

844
01:05:22,827 --> 01:05:30,054
[SPEAKER_27]: I do want to commend you guys for for doing such a great job with paying attention to where we're planting trees.

845
01:05:31,775 --> 01:05:52,723
[SPEAKER_27]: looking at the map and looking at where trees have been planted in recent years, there seems to be, even though we don't have that master plan in place, there seems to be much more, a lot of thought put into heat islands, into different neighborhoods, into environmental justice communities, and I think our residents should know that you guys are keeping all of that in mind.

846
01:05:53,944 --> 01:05:54,304
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

847
01:05:55,450 --> 01:05:57,191
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, back to Councilor Carvillo.

848
01:05:57,212 --> 01:05:57,492
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

849
01:05:57,512 --> 01:06:01,095
[SPEAKER_20]: Tim, I got a couple of questions on personnel.

850
01:06:01,155 --> 01:06:11,864
[SPEAKER_20]: So I'm looking down here and I see for foreman on page number two, minus 63,000, did we lose a foreman?

851
01:06:13,005 --> 01:06:16,888
[SPEAKER_20]: No, we haven't lost a foreman.

852
01:06:18,169 --> 01:06:19,150
[SPEAKER_20]: On your personnel summary.

853
01:06:21,672 --> 01:06:21,972
[SPEAKER_11]: Yes.

854
01:06:23,698 --> 01:06:25,099
[SPEAKER_20]: I got page 187, I don't know.

855
01:06:25,139 --> 01:06:27,440
[SPEAKER_26]: I did notice, so the foremans are scattered throughout.

856
01:06:27,740 --> 01:06:32,482
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, I see like there's this 63,000, we're off, did we lose a foreman?

857
01:06:32,502 --> 01:06:32,542
[SPEAKER_20]: No.

858
01:06:32,602 --> 01:06:33,003
[SPEAKER_20]: Why is the change?

859
01:06:33,123 --> 01:06:37,765
[SPEAKER_20]: It says four in the FY23 and then three in the FY24 proposed under foreman.

860
01:06:37,785 --> 01:06:40,486
[SPEAKER_20]: No, we're not removing any foreman.

861
01:06:52,210 --> 01:06:53,731
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't know why.

862
01:06:54,031 --> 01:06:54,731
[SPEAKER_20]: Why is it off?

863
01:06:55,311 --> 01:06:56,512
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't know.

864
01:06:56,532 --> 01:06:56,512
63,000.

865
01:06:57,492 --> 01:06:58,712
[SPEAKER_16]: I do not know.

866
01:07:01,033 --> 01:07:05,335
[SPEAKER_20]: I do know that we're not losing any points.

867
01:07:05,535 --> 01:07:07,476
[SPEAKER_26]: Okay.

868
01:07:07,576 --> 01:07:09,196
[SPEAKER_26]: No, we're not down tree climber.

869
01:07:09,796 --> 01:07:14,098
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, so I see, you know, and you got like a tree climber.

870
01:07:15,794 --> 01:07:43,228
[SPEAKER_26]: uh we're short did we lose did we lose one there no we changed a job we changed a job from tree climber to uh something else so we've actually increased the staffing of forestry by two over the last year if you recall um last budget hearing my strategy for forestry um i got creative with our budget and i was able to uh not not double but got another crew in forestry this year uh so

871
01:07:44,036 --> 01:07:45,478
[SPEAKER_26]: definitely not reduction.

872
01:07:53,862 --> 01:07:56,604
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, the foreman looks like maybe potentially a mistake.

873
01:07:57,725 --> 01:07:58,105
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay.

874
01:07:58,185 --> 01:07:59,746
[SPEAKER_20]: And what about the tree climber?

875
01:07:59,766 --> 01:08:00,206
[SPEAKER_20]: Did we lose?

876
01:08:00,286 --> 01:08:04,229
[SPEAKER_20]: I know you hired one, but did we lose one?

877
01:08:05,269 --> 01:08:21,060
[SPEAKER_26]: In the last year's budget, we had two tree climbers proposed and one of the job descriptions was changed from a tree climber to a maintenance craftsman, I believe, because we felt that we didn't need two, we needed one tree climber with basically a helper.

878
01:08:23,083 --> 01:08:25,324
[SPEAKER_26]: And that's what that explains the reduction in treatment.

879
01:08:27,384 --> 01:08:32,526
[SPEAKER_20]: And in the engineering department, there's a negative $60,000 there.

880
01:08:33,966 --> 01:08:36,547
[SPEAKER_20]: What is, did we lose someone in that department?

881
01:08:37,087 --> 01:08:37,527
[SPEAKER_20]: No.

882
01:08:38,227 --> 01:08:39,848
[SPEAKER_20]: Why is there a negative 60,000 there?

883
01:08:40,608 --> 01:08:41,028
[SPEAKER_20]: I do not know.

884
01:08:45,226 --> 01:08:50,890
[SPEAKER_20]: So let me say, so the 60, 63, 54, and 60.

885
01:08:52,372 --> 01:08:55,594
[SPEAKER_20]: Are those all supposed to be positives?

886
01:08:56,635 --> 01:08:57,716
[SPEAKER_26]: I get the explanation.

887
01:08:57,776 --> 01:09:02,640
[SPEAKER_26]: So that was, we have one engineer, the position's not going away, but it was,

888
01:09:04,037 --> 01:09:07,761
[SPEAKER_26]: funding from the general fund, but it was supposed to be funding from the casino fund.

889
01:09:08,241 --> 01:09:11,364
[SPEAKER_26]: So I think that's a correction from last year's budget.

890
01:09:11,565 --> 01:09:12,325
[SPEAKER_26]: I believe that's what that is.

891
01:09:12,566 --> 01:09:12,846
[SPEAKER_26]: Okay.

892
01:09:13,607 --> 01:09:15,689
[SPEAKER_20]: And is that in the engineering departments?

893
01:09:16,249 --> 01:09:17,030
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, that's an engineering.

894
01:09:17,070 --> 01:09:17,250
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay.

895
01:09:17,911 --> 01:09:19,673
[SPEAKER_20]: And last question is,

896
01:09:20,852 --> 01:09:24,294
[SPEAKER_20]: We've allocated money for sidewalks the last two years.

897
01:09:24,334 --> 01:09:26,195
[SPEAKER_20]: Where are we on the sidewalks?

898
01:09:26,855 --> 01:09:29,497
[SPEAKER_20]: Have we spent all that $2 million in the last two years?

899
01:09:29,877 --> 01:09:43,304
[SPEAKER_26]: Just about, I think we got about, I wanna say we have about 300,000 left to go on the million dollars we opened up, let's see.

900
01:09:43,524 --> 01:09:44,845
[SPEAKER_26]: It's the first million and second million.

901
01:09:46,410 --> 01:09:46,830
[SPEAKER_26]: Second million.

902
01:09:47,411 --> 01:09:54,134
[SPEAKER_26]: And then, yeah, then we have another one for 1.5 that we recently got that's next in queue.

903
01:09:54,874 --> 01:10:00,617
[SPEAKER_26]: But the one before that, I wanna say like 70% done or something like that.

904
01:10:00,857 --> 01:10:04,238
[SPEAKER_26]: So we should be finished with the vast bulk of it by the end of the construction season.

905
01:10:04,478 --> 01:10:10,721
[SPEAKER_20]: There may be a little bit left over that we would wrap into- And where does that put us in terms of staying on top of our sidewalks?

906
01:10:10,781 --> 01:10:12,442
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, do we make a dent in anything?

907
01:10:15,060 --> 01:10:16,922
[SPEAKER_26]: We definitely made a dent.

908
01:10:17,382 --> 01:10:26,611
[SPEAKER_26]: The focus has been repair lists and driven by complaints and requests for sidewalk repairs.

909
01:10:28,032 --> 01:10:28,493
[SPEAKER_26]: We are

910
01:10:29,917 --> 01:10:35,240
[SPEAKER_26]: Moving towards looking at getting more efficient use of that money.

911
01:10:36,020 --> 01:10:49,007
[SPEAKER_26]: So the next million dollars I think it's in with minus the equipment, it's probably going to be about $1.2 million out that particular bond that we're going to be looking very hard at our heat map that I was talking about.

912
01:10:49,587 --> 01:10:56,050
[SPEAKER_26]: where we can have less mobilization, so more production style work, which we get a more efficient use of our dollar.

913
01:10:57,351 --> 01:10:59,912
[SPEAKER_26]: So there's gonna be a little bit of a different strategy to make a bigger dent.

914
01:11:00,832 --> 01:11:02,673
[SPEAKER_26]: So that's the goal.

915
01:11:02,733 --> 01:11:17,800
[SPEAKER_26]: It may end up, and I'll just say it, I mean, it may end up being, if you live in a cul-de-sac and you have a heaped sidewalk panel, that may not receive as much priority as a block on a main drag, like high street or something like that, that sees thousands of feet,

916
01:11:18,841 --> 01:11:19,141
[SPEAKER_26]: a week.

917
01:11:19,622 --> 01:11:22,547
[SPEAKER_26]: So we're changing the strategy a little bit.

918
01:11:23,368 --> 01:11:27,135
[SPEAKER_26]: But I hope it's going to be so we increase the debt.

919
01:11:27,956 --> 01:11:31,121
[SPEAKER_20]: So are we still looking into putting on a side?

920
01:11:32,554 --> 01:11:34,795
[SPEAKER_20]: sidewalk division or sidewalk group.

921
01:11:35,375 --> 01:11:46,841
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes, still doing good and you said it was going to take some time but we have we made some progress from an equipment standpoint and a sort of a planning standpoint.

922
01:11:46,881 --> 01:11:47,201
[SPEAKER_26]: Yes.

923
01:11:47,361 --> 01:11:50,863
[SPEAKER_20]: So, for example, next year we might have crew in place.

924
01:11:51,623 --> 01:11:51,823
[SPEAKER_20]: Well,

925
01:11:54,134 --> 01:12:06,783
[SPEAKER_26]: I can ask Stevie to talk about how he breaks down his crews each day, but we do have crews going out doing sidewalk work, and we also have in-house, and we also have crews going out on contract work.

926
01:12:07,204 --> 01:12:11,687
[SPEAKER_26]: So we're tackling it both ways, and that's the way it has to be done.

927
01:12:13,388 --> 01:12:26,483
[SPEAKER_26]: you know, using the in-house crews to focus on spot repairs and things where it doesn't make sense to mobilize a contractor to do, for example.

928
01:12:27,964 --> 01:12:34,492
[SPEAKER_26]: And one of the pieces of progress that I have made is getting more equipment

929
01:12:35,461 --> 01:12:37,342
[SPEAKER_26]: to better do that in-house work.

930
01:12:37,722 --> 01:12:45,727
[SPEAKER_26]: So for example, transitioning from hand placed asphalt and compaction to spreader placed asphalt and compaction.

931
01:12:46,188 --> 01:12:47,648
[SPEAKER_26]: That's gonna end up with a better product.

932
01:12:47,668 --> 01:12:50,310
[SPEAKER_26]: We'll be able to do more with the man hours that we have.

933
01:12:50,890 --> 01:12:53,832
[SPEAKER_26]: Another example is a sidewalk planer machine.

934
01:12:54,032 --> 01:12:55,173
[SPEAKER_26]: I talked a little bit about that.

935
01:12:55,733 --> 01:13:00,896
[SPEAKER_26]: A lot of the sidewalk complaints that come in are because the sidewalk is heaved an inch, two inches.

936
01:13:01,937 --> 01:13:05,280
[SPEAKER_26]: Typical practice now would be, well let's remove the panel and put a new one.

937
01:13:05,841 --> 01:13:12,507
[SPEAKER_26]: If we have a sidewalk planer, we can plane off the trip hazard in an hour or whatever, and move on to the next one.

938
01:13:12,808 --> 01:13:19,474
[SPEAKER_26]: So those are the kinds of improvements I can make now, and I'm working with Stevie our highway foreman to implement those changes.

939
01:13:20,655 --> 01:13:27,697
[SPEAKER_26]: To have a dedicated crew to sidewalk is not a good use of our current crew staffing time.

940
01:13:28,397 --> 01:13:32,358
[SPEAKER_26]: So it's more of, you know, Steve, you can probably speak to DT.

941
01:13:32,978 --> 01:13:41,181
[SPEAKER_20]: I understand your short crew and to have a dedicated crew would be detrimental to the DPW.

942
01:13:41,201 --> 01:13:42,581
[SPEAKER_20]: It's going to be incremental.

943
01:13:42,721 --> 01:13:43,321
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

944
01:13:43,401 --> 01:13:49,283
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, are we looking at having a dedicated sidewalk crew going forward?

945
01:13:49,961 --> 01:13:51,283
[SPEAKER_20]: I'd like one.

946
01:13:51,323 --> 01:13:54,869
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, we could put that crew to use with contract work.

947
01:13:54,929 --> 01:13:59,136
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, they could do sidewalks all year, and then you use them in the winter for other stuff.

948
01:13:59,197 --> 01:14:01,841
[SPEAKER_20]: One last question is, where were you on our stumps?

949
01:14:03,815 --> 01:14:07,198
[SPEAKER_26]: Well, we have, uh, we've been doing a lot of movables, obviously through contract work.

950
01:14:07,618 --> 01:14:13,522
[SPEAKER_26]: And I think the, the, the last round that we currently have funding is in procurement right now.

951
01:14:13,562 --> 01:14:16,785
[SPEAKER_26]: So that should start up soon and be done by the end of the construction season.

952
01:14:16,825 --> 01:14:18,306
[SPEAKER_26]: So that would be another 50 or 60 stumps.

953
01:14:19,106 --> 01:14:25,811
[SPEAKER_26]: Um, but we have, I don't know the exact number, but we still have a significant backlog of stumps, so it will take some time for sure.

954
01:14:26,131 --> 01:14:29,374
[SPEAKER_26]: But, uh, the only other thing I can say in that, that regard is, um,

955
01:14:29,854 --> 01:14:39,179
[SPEAKER_26]: From an operational standpoint, I'm trying to transition us to treating backlog like backlog and treating new work as new work.

956
01:14:39,239 --> 01:14:44,621
[SPEAKER_26]: So in other words, not increasing our backlog by adding, if we take down a tree, adding that stump to the backlog.

957
01:14:44,921 --> 01:14:46,462
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm trying to separate backlog.

958
01:14:46,842 --> 01:14:54,166
[SPEAKER_26]: So we're taking down a tree and then queuing up the stump for removal and then contracting out the backlog so we can wipe it away.

959
01:14:54,606 --> 01:14:56,427
[SPEAKER_26]: That's going to take a lot of time.

960
01:14:57,867 --> 01:15:05,971
[SPEAKER_26]: year over year, you're going to probably hear me say things like, well, we did another bunch of contract work and we did a bunch of in-house crew, in-house crew work.

961
01:15:07,032 --> 01:15:12,194
[SPEAKER_26]: But the backlog's so large, we just got to keep doing that every single year until we catch up with ourselves, basically.

962
01:15:12,734 --> 01:15:13,014
[SPEAKER_26]: So.

963
01:15:14,115 --> 01:15:14,595
[SPEAKER_26]: That's it for me.

964
01:15:14,615 --> 01:15:14,915
[SPEAKER_26]: Thank you.

965
01:15:15,215 --> 01:15:15,616
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you.

966
01:15:16,116 --> 01:15:16,636
[SPEAKER_14]: Councillor Knight.

967
01:15:20,598 --> 01:15:21,999
[SPEAKER_02]: Madam President, thank you very much.

968
01:15:22,059 --> 01:15:23,279
[SPEAKER_02]: And Tim, thank you for being here.

969
01:15:24,080 --> 01:15:24,680
[SPEAKER_02]: Can you explain

970
01:15:25,510 --> 01:15:29,017
[SPEAKER_02]: any of the operational hardships that you may have faced over the past year?

971
01:15:31,602 --> 01:15:32,704
[SPEAKER_26]: Operational hardships.

972
01:15:34,563 --> 01:15:35,263
[SPEAKER_26]: That's a good question.

973
01:15:35,604 --> 01:15:43,808
[SPEAKER_26]: Some of the largest challenges that I have are with communications with so many different divisions and players.

974
01:15:44,408 --> 01:15:55,995
[SPEAKER_26]: So, um, you know, leading seven different divisions plus admin, uh, for a while there too, I was kind of doing double duty with engineering his own as own was getting his feet wet.

975
01:15:56,015 --> 01:15:56,115
[SPEAKER_26]: So,

976
01:15:56,695 --> 01:16:13,100
[SPEAKER_26]: Just clear communication is my biggest operational challenge, making sure that folks know where they should be and what meetings they're coming to, and making sure that one division is clearly communicating to another division.

977
01:16:14,700 --> 01:16:16,681
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, there's other challenges too.

978
01:16:16,701 --> 01:16:18,682
[SPEAKER_26]: Another operational challenge, I would say,

979
01:16:21,683 --> 01:16:24,125
[SPEAKER_25]: is prioritizing all the work that we have to do.

980
01:16:24,785 --> 01:16:28,628
[SPEAKER_26]: So I work with every division to try to do that schedule and prioritize work.

981
01:16:29,168 --> 01:16:31,470
[SPEAKER_26]: So those two challenges stand out to me.

982
01:16:35,532 --> 01:16:41,056
[SPEAKER_15]: Do you have any additional questions, Councilor Knight?

983
01:16:41,076 --> 01:16:50,822
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, so I think it's safe to say that over the past couple of years, you've done a great job with the staffing levels that you have right now and the personnel levels that you have.

984
01:16:51,561 --> 01:16:59,497
[SPEAKER_02]: You know, have you, these personnel levels, you know, have allowed you to provide the consistency in public services, right?

985
01:16:59,517 --> 01:17:03,705
[SPEAKER_02]: We haven't seen a degradation in what we've been able to deliver, have we?

986
01:17:05,087 --> 01:17:05,828
[SPEAKER_26]: No, I don't think so.

987
01:17:05,868 --> 01:17:13,854
[SPEAKER_26]: I think from before I was commissioner to now, I personally think there's been some improvements in our operations.

988
01:17:14,195 --> 01:17:16,056
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm hoping the division leaders think the same thing.

989
01:17:16,076 --> 01:17:21,421
[SPEAKER_26]: I don't know, we'd have to ask them but you know I'm pretty confident that some of the changes that I've made

990
01:17:22,221 --> 01:17:23,642
[SPEAKER_26]: are helping that.

991
01:17:23,902 --> 01:17:26,002
[SPEAKER_26]: I touched upon some of them.

992
01:17:26,162 --> 01:17:34,244
[SPEAKER_26]: I have a regular set of meetings now that happen like clockwork that folks know that they need to come to them.

993
01:17:34,284 --> 01:17:40,026
[SPEAKER_26]: And that really helps with the communication piece I was talking about and the collaboration piece between divisions.

994
01:17:40,546 --> 01:17:48,908
[SPEAKER_26]: So just that, just looking at that one thing, setting up regular meetings for operations and for procurement and other things.

995
01:17:50,582 --> 01:17:56,166
[SPEAKER_26]: That one thing, I believe, has been a significant improvement to how things were done in the past.

996
01:18:01,790 --> 01:18:02,390
[SPEAKER_02]: Excellent, thank you.

997
01:18:02,450 --> 01:18:05,853
[SPEAKER_02]: I think you're doing a great job with what you have and with the boots that you have on the ground.

998
01:18:06,653 --> 01:18:09,976
[SPEAKER_02]: So I appreciate you coming here and putting on, once again, another great presentation.

999
01:18:10,876 --> 01:18:11,157
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

1000
01:18:11,777 --> 01:18:12,477
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Councilor Nye.

1001
01:18:13,738 --> 01:18:16,220
[SPEAKER_15]: So I just, I have like two very specific questions.

1002
01:18:16,440 --> 01:18:18,542
[SPEAKER_15]: I did have one resident reach out about

1003
01:18:19,697 --> 01:18:24,839
[SPEAKER_15]: I want to make sure I just the intelligent speed assistance for fleet vehicles.

1004
01:18:24,979 --> 01:18:29,561
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't even know if that's something I know that speed cameras, you can't do Massachusetts.

1005
01:18:29,601 --> 01:18:37,984
[SPEAKER_15]: I don't even know if that falls under the umbrella, but it's just the intelligence be designed to keep fleet vehicles at the speed of which is posted in the area.

1006
01:18:38,324 --> 01:18:40,105
[SPEAKER_15]: And I'm not saying this based on seeing anything.

1007
01:18:40,145 --> 01:18:42,045
[SPEAKER_15]: I'm just saying a resident just asked about this.

1008
01:18:42,065 --> 01:18:43,526
[SPEAKER_15]: So I don't know if that's something on the radar.

1009
01:18:44,206 --> 01:18:45,407
[SPEAKER_25]: Could you say it one more time?

1010
01:18:45,647 --> 01:18:47,227
[SPEAKER_15]: It's intelligent speed assistance.

1011
01:18:47,307 --> 01:18:48,708
[SPEAKER_15]: So it's a it's intelligent.

1012
01:18:49,647 --> 01:18:59,015
[SPEAKER_15]: sure it's AI to help vehicles like fleet vehicles, they wouldn't have to maintain the speed or they would be able to go above the speed of the posted speed limit.

1013
01:18:59,075 --> 01:18:59,736
[SPEAKER_26]: First I'm hearing of it.

1014
01:19:00,096 --> 01:19:00,716
[SPEAKER_26]: Okay.

1015
01:19:00,857 --> 01:19:02,318
[SPEAKER_26]: So I can send it to you.

1016
01:19:03,018 --> 01:19:07,702
[SPEAKER_26]: Yeah, I mean, I look at it, I'm pretty confident that we're not out there speeding around.

1017
01:19:08,163 --> 01:19:09,404
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, and I've never seen an issue.

1018
01:19:09,424 --> 01:19:11,065
[SPEAKER_15]: It's just a resident asked about it.

1019
01:19:11,606 --> 01:19:12,206
[SPEAKER_25]: Sure, sure, sure.

1020
01:19:12,226 --> 01:19:16,430
[SPEAKER_25]: Yeah, I mean, yeah, I'm more than willing to learn and take in information.

1021
01:19:16,610 --> 01:19:16,870
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

1022
01:19:16,890 --> 01:19:22,636
[SPEAKER_15]: And again, I haven't had the chance to look to see if it's something I know we can't do speed cameras in Massachusetts because the law is currently written.

1023
01:19:22,656 --> 01:19:24,458
[SPEAKER_15]: So I don't even know if this falls under that umbrella.

1024
01:19:24,498 --> 01:19:25,419
[SPEAKER_15]: So I just want to raise that.

1025
01:19:26,280 --> 01:19:33,728
[SPEAKER_15]: And then for the trees, I was just curious, and this may be more of a question for Aggie, with the tree inventory,

1026
01:19:35,294 --> 01:19:39,437
[SPEAKER_15]: How are you able to keep up with the trees?

1027
01:19:39,477 --> 01:19:46,763
[SPEAKER_15]: So I've seen a fair amount of stumps removed around me, which is great, but those are also, they're like that last reminder that there ever was a tree there.

1028
01:19:47,404 --> 01:19:54,230
[SPEAKER_15]: And I just worry that people that never saw the tree there, it's like you can't even conceptualize the idea of there used to be this big tree on the corner providing shade.

1029
01:19:54,290 --> 01:20:03,978
[SPEAKER_15]: And I worry that as we catch up down the line, we lose the idea or we lose these spaces where there were trees and no one's putting in a request and it might not be on the radar.

1030
01:20:06,027 --> 01:20:06,949
[SPEAKER_15]: Just curious how that works.

1031
01:20:07,029 --> 01:20:13,681
[SPEAKER_15]: And I'm talking about West Mead, which is a little bit leafier than I know, like the Heat Island areas and areas that are, I understand are priority and should be priority right now.

1032
01:20:14,238 --> 01:20:25,125
[SPEAKER_26]: I will tell you one of the factors that was listed in our proposal for two grants now was having to do with the heat island effect and where there's shade and where there's not shade.

1033
01:20:25,545 --> 01:20:30,788
[SPEAKER_26]: And that becomes a variable in recommendations on where we should focus new plantings.

1034
01:20:31,388 --> 01:20:36,772
[SPEAKER_26]: So when we talk about an urban forest management plan, a key part of that plan

1035
01:20:37,392 --> 01:20:42,613
[SPEAKER_26]: is a set of recommendations that tells us where we should be focusing our public dollars for tree plantings.

1036
01:20:43,513 --> 01:20:59,976
[SPEAKER_26]: So I would think, and I'm not an expert, and Aggie, please chime in, but if you have a street where we had to remove trees because they died, then that would come up on that evaluation and say, hey, you've got to plant some more trees there.

1037
01:20:59,996 --> 01:21:00,956
[SPEAKER_26]: OK.

1038
01:21:00,976 --> 01:21:01,256
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

1039
01:21:02,436 --> 01:21:03,256
[SPEAKER_26]: Does that sound about right?

1040
01:21:03,336 --> 01:21:03,877
[SPEAKER_11]: Yes, it does.

1041
01:21:03,977 --> 01:21:04,317
[SPEAKER_11]: It does.

1042
01:21:04,337 --> 01:21:04,737
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you, Jim.

1043
01:21:04,757 --> 01:21:05,637
[SPEAKER_11]: But if I may add.

1044
01:21:07,553 --> 01:21:15,480
[SPEAKER_11]: In the last few years, we have been focusing on environmental justice areas around the city, which are also the Heat Island areas.

1045
01:21:16,420 --> 01:21:17,561
[SPEAKER_11]: And that's been very successful.

1046
01:21:17,601 --> 01:21:20,784
[SPEAKER_11]: So it's the denser, more densely populated neighborhoods.

1047
01:21:21,245 --> 01:21:26,749
[SPEAKER_11]: So South Medford has some areas we've addressed, some in the Wellington area.

1048
01:21:27,710 --> 01:21:33,215
[SPEAKER_11]: So we've been progressing on that for, this is at least the third year of having that as a specific focus.

1049
01:21:33,795 --> 01:21:35,757
[SPEAKER_11]: And there is one thing I mentioned is,

1050
01:21:36,922 --> 01:21:48,766
[SPEAKER_11]: Often when a tree is lost in a tree pit and the tree pit is empty, the trees are not replaced at the same location, usually because it's an improper place to put a tree.

1051
01:21:49,606 --> 01:21:56,329
[SPEAKER_11]: So it might be too close to an intersection or there must be utility conflicts and that sort of thing.

1052
01:21:56,369 --> 01:22:01,890
[SPEAKER_11]: So we assess each location by site to plant right trees in the right place.

1053
01:22:02,391 --> 01:22:02,551
[SPEAKER_15]: OK.

1054
01:22:02,911 --> 01:22:06,692
[SPEAKER_15]: And then how often is that heat assessment

1055
01:22:07,115 --> 01:22:09,017
[SPEAKER_15]: done to understand where the heat islands are?

1056
01:22:10,858 --> 01:22:12,660
[SPEAKER_26]: You'd have to ask Alicia if her office has done something.

1057
01:22:12,680 --> 01:22:14,801
[SPEAKER_26]: But we haven't done that in the DPW.

1058
01:22:14,881 --> 01:22:24,329
[SPEAKER_26]: This would be a, as long as we get the grant that we want, then that would be a fresh evaluation.

1059
01:22:24,349 --> 01:22:25,950
[SPEAKER_26]: I'm sure we would use data that we already had.

1060
01:22:26,231 --> 01:22:28,693
[SPEAKER_26]: I know we had a climate resiliency plan.

1061
01:22:28,713 --> 01:22:29,173
[SPEAKER_26]: We have that.

1062
01:22:29,213 --> 01:22:29,794
[SPEAKER_26]: It's published.

1063
01:22:29,834 --> 01:22:35,078
[SPEAKER_26]: So if there's data associated with that, I'm sure it would get used in a urban forestry management plan.

1064
01:22:35,783 --> 01:22:36,083
[SPEAKER_15]: Great.

1065
01:22:36,483 --> 01:22:36,884
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you both.

1066
01:22:37,844 --> 01:22:39,345
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other questions from the council?

1067
01:22:39,385 --> 01:22:40,766
[SPEAKER_15]: Any members of the public wish to speak?

1068
01:22:43,528 --> 01:22:44,048
[SPEAKER_14]: Seeing none.

1069
01:22:44,588 --> 01:22:45,129
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you so much.

1070
01:22:45,429 --> 01:22:45,709
[SPEAKER_14]: All right.

1071
01:22:45,769 --> 01:22:46,429
[SPEAKER_26]: Thank you very much.

1072
01:22:47,650 --> 01:22:52,293
[SPEAKER_15]: We were going to go to DEI, but Director Nagy had to step out to grab some food.

1073
01:22:52,833 --> 01:22:57,576
[SPEAKER_15]: So we are going to go through, we'll go to Chevalier, and after that, we will go to fire.

1074
01:22:59,701 --> 01:22:59,961
[SPEAKER_15]: Oh, sorry.

1075
01:22:59,981 --> 01:23:00,701
