1219
01:35:15,134 --> 01:35:15,654
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you for being here.

1220
01:35:45,097 --> 01:35:53,000
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, Memphis Fire Department consists of four groups.

1221
01:35:53,460 --> 01:36:01,963
[SPEAKER_00]: We have in-fire suppression, we have a Fire Prevention Bureau, Training Division, and Fire Investigation Team.

1222
01:36:03,064 --> 01:36:11,027
[SPEAKER_00]: And obviously, I have one full-time office manager and one part-time office assistant.

1223
01:36:14,969 --> 01:36:27,336
[SPEAKER_00]: So since I took over 18 months ago, I've been striving to bring the department up to today's modern standards by modernizing and the method fire department continues to provide protection to the citizens of Medford.

1224
01:36:27,936 --> 01:36:35,420
[SPEAKER_00]: We respond to numerous calls, medicals, motor vehicle accidents, fires, and we've had numerous multiple on fires recently.

1225
01:36:35,440 --> 01:36:35,500
[SPEAKER_00]: And

1226
01:36:37,421 --> 01:36:40,102
[SPEAKER_00]: all this with less resources.

1227
01:36:41,002 --> 01:36:55,487
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, the inflation and the pandemic supply chain interruptions have had a huge effect on the department's operations, and we're constantly looking for ways to stretch the dollar, increase efficiency and do more with less.

1228
01:36:56,507 --> 01:37:02,089
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, we've had a lot of turnover in the department since I took over due to retirements, promotions.

1229
01:37:03,049 --> 01:37:06,330
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, we did hire 12 new firefighters and

1230
01:37:07,377 --> 01:37:16,804
[SPEAKER_00]: This turnover is happening at a rate that is almost impossible to keep up with the current delays that are in the academy and throughout.

1231
01:37:16,944 --> 01:37:19,026
[SPEAKER_00]: It's not just Metro, it's throughout Massachusetts.

1232
01:37:23,089 --> 01:37:28,913
[SPEAKER_00]: That being said, I would like to take this opportunity to recognize the firefighters under my command.

1233
01:37:29,534 --> 01:37:35,979
[SPEAKER_00]: In the 18 months since I took over, they have done an excellent job and continue to do so on a daily basis.

1234
01:37:37,077 --> 01:37:39,097
[SPEAKER_00]: During the pandemic, we were here.

1235
01:37:40,018 --> 01:37:42,878
[SPEAKER_00]: We responded to COVID positive calls and facilities.

1236
01:37:44,638 --> 01:37:50,099
[SPEAKER_00]: In the beginning, the CD guidance wasn't, it was constantly changing.

1237
01:37:51,120 --> 01:37:53,220
[SPEAKER_00]: We made do with the tools that we had on hand.

1238
01:37:54,080 --> 01:37:58,421
[SPEAKER_00]: And firefighters did not have the option of working remotely.

1239
01:37:59,281 --> 01:38:01,722
[SPEAKER_00]: And they showed up every day.

1240
01:38:06,313 --> 01:38:10,475
[SPEAKER_00]: Most of them, including myself, um, ended up getting COVID.

1241
01:38:11,275 --> 01:38:18,617
[SPEAKER_00]: Our families got COVID and yet the department kept functioning at a high level despite all this throughout the pandemic.

1242
01:38:19,118 --> 01:38:29,821
[SPEAKER_00]: And I would like to take this opportunity to publicly thank all of the firefighters under my command, men and women for everything they did and continue to do to maintain public safety in the city.

1243
01:38:30,902 --> 01:38:31,002
[SPEAKER_00]: Um,

1244
01:38:33,111 --> 01:38:36,113
[SPEAKER_00]: We also receive support from many of the departments.

1245
01:38:36,153 --> 01:38:39,936
[SPEAKER_00]: Some of them we heard from today here in the city to help us accomplish our mission.

1246
01:38:40,236 --> 01:38:52,143
[SPEAKER_00]: I would also like to take this opportunity to thank the Medford Police Department, the DPW, all their staff, the water department, our mechanic, Brendan Saluda.

1247
01:38:52,184 --> 01:38:53,925
[SPEAKER_00]: I like, I have a special thanks go out to him.

1248
01:38:53,985 --> 01:38:58,728
[SPEAKER_00]: He keeps these trucks and the apparatus and all our other vehicles running on a daily basis.

1249
01:38:59,889 --> 01:38:59,989
And

1250
01:39:03,139 --> 01:39:04,399
[SPEAKER_00]: I hope I didn't miss anybody.

1251
01:39:05,980 --> 01:39:11,401
[SPEAKER_00]: I really don't want to have anybody feel like they were missed when I was thinking.

1252
01:39:14,221 --> 01:39:22,703
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'll just give you a brief summary on some of the things that are going on right now.

1253
01:39:22,763 --> 01:39:27,604
[SPEAKER_00]: We are in the process of, you know, working on the design

1254
01:39:28,288 --> 01:39:30,650
[SPEAKER_00]: and a feasibility study for a new headquarters.

1255
01:39:31,290 --> 01:39:34,473
[SPEAKER_00]: The feasibility study is at approximately 45% done.

1256
01:39:35,934 --> 01:39:38,095
[SPEAKER_00]: When it gets completed, we'll have a written document.

1257
01:39:38,236 --> 01:39:39,757
[SPEAKER_00]: So we'll be able to share that.

1258
01:39:41,658 --> 01:39:45,461
[SPEAKER_00]: We're very early stages of the design of the headquarters.

1259
01:39:45,481 --> 01:39:49,844
[SPEAKER_00]: We're trying to go through the program books and figure out the exact amount of square footage.

1260
01:39:50,765 --> 01:39:53,007
[SPEAKER_00]: And then once the feasibility comes in,

1261
01:39:53,983 --> 01:40:00,205
[SPEAKER_00]: and we figure out how big of a facility it's going to be, then obviously the next step will be to look at funding.

1262
01:40:01,305 --> 01:40:03,646
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's where we are with the headquarters.

1263
01:40:05,406 --> 01:40:12,528
[SPEAKER_00]: As far as like the outside stations, the satellite stations, since I've taken over, we've done numerous renovations.

1264
01:40:12,988 --> 01:40:15,049
[SPEAKER_00]: I listed them in my summary.

1265
01:40:18,728 --> 01:40:20,249
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, we continue to do that.

1266
01:40:20,409 --> 01:40:23,391
[SPEAKER_00]: And the facilities manager also has been a big help.

1267
01:40:23,432 --> 01:40:31,598
[SPEAKER_00]: So when I have something, um, I utilize his expertise to help me out with efficiency and how we should go about repairing some of this stuff.

1268
01:40:32,879 --> 01:40:40,724
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, we have two new fire pumpers that, uh, were funded and a contract signed with sea grade.

1269
01:40:40,764 --> 01:40:45,548
[SPEAKER_00]: So we are, um, my apparatus team is set to go out to the factory the end of June.

1270
01:40:46,414 --> 01:40:50,158
[SPEAKER_00]: to help design and finalize the drawings for the apparatus.

1271
01:40:51,119 --> 01:41:01,029
[SPEAKER_00]: And we also operate in the department, we have a utility vehicle that I activated that we use for numerous different things.

1272
01:41:01,629 --> 01:41:07,315
[SPEAKER_00]: If we need off-road, if we have an emergency up in the woods, we need to go off-road, we have that capability now.

1273
01:41:08,216 --> 01:41:09,177
[SPEAKER_00]: We have a boat that

1274
01:41:10,602 --> 01:41:16,188
[SPEAKER_00]: Right after I took over as chief, we activated Marine One and it's in the water in the summer.

1275
01:41:16,589 --> 01:41:19,832
[SPEAKER_00]: In the winter, we can't keep it in the water, so it comes out and it's stored at headquarters.

1276
01:41:21,955 --> 01:41:23,176
[SPEAKER_00]: We operate a brush truck.

1277
01:41:27,561 --> 01:41:30,164
[SPEAKER_00]: So, you know,

1278
01:41:31,702 --> 01:41:37,126
[SPEAKER_00]: While we wait for these new pumpers to come in, we have to continue to operate to the pot.

1279
01:41:38,147 --> 01:41:43,631
[SPEAKER_00]: And we recently lost one of our pumps, the frame prematurely failed.

1280
01:41:44,252 --> 01:41:46,754
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's the reason we're ordering these pumps.

1281
01:41:46,794 --> 01:41:50,457
[SPEAKER_00]: But during the wait, it's a long wait before those trucks come in.

1282
01:41:52,407 --> 01:42:02,318
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, I've made some changes in the budget and increased motor services so that we can actually begin to start to try and start some more parts.

1283
01:42:02,358 --> 01:42:06,942
[SPEAKER_00]: So we have the parts here when something breaks because what's happened with the supply chain interruption is

1284
01:42:07,974 --> 01:42:16,019
[SPEAKER_00]: we have a failure, for example, something needs breaks or needs an alternator, let's say, and then we call up and nothing is in stock.

1285
01:42:16,059 --> 01:42:22,203
[SPEAKER_00]: So then we end up, not only does it go down while we wait to repair it, we have to wait for the part to come in before we can repair it.

1286
01:42:22,243 --> 01:42:31,388
[SPEAKER_00]: So we're gonna make some changes and try to, at least the common parts that we use, that we know we're gonna use throughout the year, we're gonna try and stock some of those under this new budget.

1287
01:42:35,151 --> 01:42:37,232
[SPEAKER_00]: And with that, I'll take some questions.

1288
01:42:37,671 --> 01:42:39,172
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Councilor Carvalho.

1289
01:42:39,512 --> 01:42:40,273
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, Madam President.

1290
01:42:40,353 --> 01:42:40,873
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you, Chief.

1291
01:42:41,353 --> 01:42:50,579
[SPEAKER_20]: Chief, I don't think anybody realizes police, fire, and DPW, those are our frontline services.

1292
01:42:51,059 --> 01:42:58,824
[SPEAKER_20]: They work 24 hours a day, and they're really the only ones that don't, you're right, never had the opportunity to work remote.

1293
01:42:59,505 --> 01:43:06,149
[SPEAKER_20]: And I don't think anyone ever realizes how important the fire department or the police department is until you call them to come to your house.

1294
01:43:07,549 --> 01:43:08,549
[SPEAKER_20]: And you're correct.

1295
01:43:08,569 --> 01:43:10,270
[SPEAKER_20]: I've had a chance to come to my house a couple of times.

1296
01:43:11,010 --> 01:43:14,611
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's when you realize how important you are.

1297
01:43:14,631 --> 01:43:19,073
[SPEAKER_20]: I'd say 2 o'clock in the morning when you call for a policeman or fireman, they're there within a minute.

1298
01:43:19,093 --> 01:43:22,774
[SPEAKER_20]: So I thank you for what you've done there.

1299
01:43:23,214 --> 01:43:30,276
[SPEAKER_20]: Chief, in the last month, you've had a bunch of fires involving the lithium batteries.

1300
01:43:33,550 --> 01:43:35,091
[SPEAKER_20]: are we lacking equipment?

1301
01:43:35,231 --> 01:43:39,915
[SPEAKER_20]: Is there a different kind of equipment that we should have to put those type of fires out?

1302
01:43:40,355 --> 01:43:43,938
[SPEAKER_20]: And you know, you know, I know you get the cars now being charged at the houses.

1303
01:43:44,879 --> 01:43:48,982
[SPEAKER_20]: I think we're seeing an uptick and fires everywhere.

1304
01:43:50,183 --> 01:43:55,888
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, we did have recently have a couple of I would call them e bikes or e scooters.

1305
01:43:56,068 --> 01:43:56,228
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

1306
01:43:56,957 --> 01:43:58,758
[SPEAKER_00]: Uh, and they are lithium ion batteries.

1307
01:43:58,778 --> 01:43:59,419
[SPEAKER_00]: You're correct.

1308
01:43:59,479 --> 01:44:17,129
[SPEAKER_00]: And, um, part of what's happening with these fires we had in the homes were, um, when they do happen in the home, it's devastating because they burn so hot, they go into a thing called thermal runaway and it ends up, um, you know, causing significant damage.

1309
01:44:17,590 --> 01:44:20,532
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, and the, it happens very rapidly.

1310
01:44:20,572 --> 01:44:24,314
[SPEAKER_00]: So by the time we get there, even if it's two or three minutes, you've got this massive fire.

1311
01:44:24,494 --> 01:44:25,795
[SPEAKER_00]: So, um,

1312
01:44:27,021 --> 01:44:37,652
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, at that point when the fire gets that big, you know, you kind of go to defensive ops and that ends up being more devastating because, you know, you end up having more damage.

1313
01:44:37,712 --> 01:44:42,558
[SPEAKER_00]: So we did put out a press release through the Department of Fire Services.

1314
01:44:42,578 --> 01:44:44,600
[SPEAKER_00]: It went in the globe and, um,

1315
01:44:45,313 --> 01:44:58,795
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, to kind of put the word out about these lithium-ion batteries and the proper, to follow the manufacturer's recommendations on properly charging it, storing it, you know, they're all different.

1316
01:44:58,815 --> 01:45:01,596
[SPEAKER_00]: So to put something out like that, you have to stay generic.

1317
01:45:02,436 --> 01:45:08,197
[SPEAKER_00]: And then, you know, we're about to put out a second press release for the Southern Fire regarding lithium-ion.

1318
01:45:08,257 --> 01:45:11,438
[SPEAKER_00]: So yeah, we are seeing an uptick.

1319
01:45:13,225 --> 01:45:19,049
[SPEAKER_00]: You know those those those types of fires the ones are in the home we have to use water that's that's the media okay.

1320
01:45:19,869 --> 01:45:32,978
[SPEAKER_00]: We are my training divisions been kind of looking into some fire blankets that some of the other departments are using, but the you know when I looked into it right now it's kind of very early in the incipient phase with those.

1321
01:45:33,762 --> 01:45:38,263
[SPEAKER_00]: They're very expensive and there's a bunch of different ones out there.

1322
01:45:38,283 --> 01:45:42,564
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'm trying to like do a survey through the Metro chiefs to find out which ones are the best.

1323
01:45:43,544 --> 01:45:49,466
[SPEAKER_00]: Uh, but then obviously the end all, you know, answer, you have to make sure that you get the right one.

1324
01:45:49,846 --> 01:45:52,527
[SPEAKER_00]: The problem with them is too, is that they're only limited usage.

1325
01:45:52,587 --> 01:45:56,108
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you purchase one of those for say it's two to $3,000 per blanket,

1326
01:45:58,192 --> 01:46:00,152
[SPEAKER_00]: And you use it three times, it's done.

1327
01:46:00,773 --> 01:46:01,693
[SPEAKER_00]: Sometimes five times.

1328
01:46:01,733 --> 01:46:03,913
[SPEAKER_00]: It depends on the fire, how hot it is and what happens.

1329
01:46:03,933 --> 01:46:15,656
[SPEAKER_00]: So is that a new wave, could end up being the new wave, how we're going to fight these things, especially up on the highway where we have no water, or if you're in a parking garage and you just have very little access to water.

1330
01:46:16,516 --> 01:46:18,456
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'm definitely looking at it really hard.

1331
01:46:18,516 --> 01:46:24,098
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm in the middle of kind of waiting on the Metro Chiefs to see what everyone else is using to try and combat those.

1332
01:46:26,890 --> 01:46:28,931
[SPEAKER_20]: City is moving forward.

1333
01:46:28,951 --> 01:46:33,332
[SPEAKER_20]: We're looking to bring in bio and life science projects.

1334
01:46:34,653 --> 01:46:45,357
[SPEAKER_20]: Is the department have the equipment to do a bio hazard or something if there were to be an issue in one of those type of buildings?

1335
01:46:45,437 --> 01:46:47,418
[SPEAKER_00]: I think those are going to be level ones and twos.

1336
01:46:49,311 --> 01:46:56,804
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, I don't, if I don't think there's, I'd have to look into that to get back to you on what, if there is any specialized equipment that we would need.

1337
01:46:56,824 --> 01:46:57,866
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

1338
01:46:58,930 --> 01:47:01,531
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, they're not coming tomorrow, but they will be here in a few years.

1339
01:47:01,571 --> 01:47:03,812
[SPEAKER_20]: And I want to make sure that the department is able to handle it.

1340
01:47:03,832 --> 01:47:08,753
[SPEAKER_00]: I think that's one of the reasons we kept it to level one and two is it's less of an impact than threes or fours.

1341
01:47:08,813 --> 01:47:12,994
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, like you get up to those level labs and it's a completely different ballgame.

1342
01:47:13,074 --> 01:47:18,896
[SPEAKER_00]: So, um, I mean, there are some issues with the gases they use and how they're going to store them.

1343
01:47:18,976 --> 01:47:23,558
[SPEAKER_00]: And you know, that'll all be done through fire prevention, make sure we keep an eye on that.

1344
01:47:23,638 --> 01:47:24,258
[SPEAKER_00]: But, um,

1345
01:47:25,322 --> 01:47:29,344
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm not aware of right now of anything special that we need for those, but I will look into that.

1346
01:47:29,464 --> 01:47:31,606
[SPEAKER_20]: I know they're coming down the line and they're not here yet.

1347
01:47:31,706 --> 01:47:33,587
[SPEAKER_20]: Understood.

1348
01:47:33,827 --> 01:47:40,371
[SPEAKER_20]: So as I'm looking here in your personnel chart, I see a decrease in firefighters of $143,958.

1349
01:47:40,411 --> 01:47:45,294
[SPEAKER_20]: What do we attribute that to?

1350
01:47:45,734 --> 01:47:52,938
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, I did speak to the chief of staff about this, and that may be an error, I'm looking into that.

1351
01:47:54,634 --> 01:47:56,094
[SPEAKER_00]: it's possible that that's a mistake.

1352
01:47:57,015 --> 01:48:09,539
[SPEAKER_00]: But until I didn't communicate that to them until tonight, I thought that was what it was, but we're gonna get back to you and find out if it's a mistake or not.

1353
01:48:09,639 --> 01:48:17,201
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, Madam President, I mean, we seem to be getting a lot of mistakes in this year, and not just the department.

1354
01:48:17,241 --> 01:48:20,322
[SPEAKER_20]: We've picked up with a few others at different departments.

1355
01:48:21,182 --> 01:48:22,003
[SPEAKER_20]: I think,

1356
01:48:23,342 --> 01:48:28,504
[SPEAKER_20]: Maybe before we vote on this budget, all these mistakes should be rectified.

1357
01:48:28,524 --> 01:48:29,725
[SPEAKER_15]: Absolutely.

1358
01:48:30,265 --> 01:48:30,565
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

1359
01:48:31,285 --> 01:48:32,486
[SPEAKER_20]: That's it for me, the chief at the moment.

1360
01:48:32,506 --> 01:48:34,507
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay.

1361
01:48:38,309 --> 01:48:40,449
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other questions from counselors?

