[SPEAKER_03]: We think that's yeah, that's also in the personnel chart.

1366
01:48:52,347 --> 01:48:53,588
[SPEAKER_03]: So we think that may not be true.

1367
01:48:53,608 --> 01:48:55,810
[SPEAKER_03]: It's not true.

1368
01:48:55,831 --> 01:48:56,771
[SPEAKER_00]: Well, we're looking into it.

1369
01:48:57,092 --> 01:48:57,352
[SPEAKER_03]: Okay.

1370
01:48:57,592 --> 01:48:58,333
[SPEAKER_15]: Yeah, I do know.

1371
01:48:58,353 --> 01:48:59,814
[SPEAKER_15]: I think it was last.

1372
01:49:00,715 --> 01:49:02,397
[SPEAKER_15]: Does that I mean, I'm not trying to guess for this.

1373
01:49:02,978 --> 01:49:04,179
[SPEAKER_15]: I'll just ask this question different ways.

1374
01:49:04,199 --> 01:49:05,200
[SPEAKER_15]: So it's not connected to that.

1375
01:49:05,961 --> 01:49:10,365
[SPEAKER_15]: Do you have positions you're not able to fill because of the delay from the firefighter Academy?

1376
01:49:12,477 --> 01:49:19,239
[SPEAKER_00]: Absolutely, yeah, I'd love to, what I did when I did this budget, prepared for the budget, I did sort of a little staffing analysis.

1377
01:49:20,179 --> 01:49:23,580
[SPEAKER_00]: And what's happened is it kind of, it's a dynamic thing.

1378
01:49:23,600 --> 01:49:28,362
[SPEAKER_00]: So when you, we had people retire that really weren't slated to retire and they just left.

1379
01:49:29,162 --> 01:49:36,444
[SPEAKER_00]: So, and then a side effect of making promotions, which is fiscally responsible by the way, cause you're sealing the overtime void.

1380
01:49:37,024 --> 01:49:39,345
[SPEAKER_00]: I ended up making a bunch of promotions, like seven of them.

1381
01:49:40,045 --> 01:49:47,746
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you add up those with a couple of people that left suddenly, we had one recently just at the end of May that just left.

1382
01:49:48,426 --> 01:49:49,787
[SPEAKER_00]: So there's three there.

1383
01:49:49,807 --> 01:49:55,768
[SPEAKER_00]: There's two that are gonna age out, one in August, one in November.

1384
01:49:56,368 --> 01:49:57,888
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you add the number up, it's 10.

1385
01:49:58,188 --> 01:50:00,269
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'd like to talk to the mayor.

1386
01:50:00,529 --> 01:50:03,049
[SPEAKER_00]: I haven't done that yet, but I'm gonna sit down with the mayor.

1387
01:50:03,069 --> 01:50:07,430
[SPEAKER_00]: And once I get the authorization to do that, that all takes time.

1388
01:50:08,010 --> 01:50:08,590
[SPEAKER_00]: It takes money.

1389
01:50:09,524 --> 01:50:11,205
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, I have to have that discussion with her.

1390
01:50:11,225 --> 01:50:18,367
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, but you know, what's happened is the academy, I called up there, there's three different academies, the quickest I could get them in.

1391
01:50:18,847 --> 01:50:29,191
[SPEAKER_00]: Once I prepare and go through all the background checks and medical screening site testing, all of that, once that takes usually three, three or four months that I can then petition.

1392
01:50:29,271 --> 01:50:32,472
[SPEAKER_00]: Once I have the mayor's decision and names and social security numbers,

1393
01:50:33,225 --> 01:50:36,949
[SPEAKER_00]: we can give them conditional letters of employment and we petition the academy.

1394
01:50:37,569 --> 01:50:39,591
[SPEAKER_00]: They're telling me right now that's nine months from there.

1395
01:50:39,631 --> 01:50:41,793
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you go three and nine, that's a year.

1396
01:50:42,474 --> 01:50:51,963
[SPEAKER_00]: And then if you take the 12 weeks it takes to train them, that's 15, 16 months before we're gonna see them on the fire ground.

1397
01:50:52,764 --> 01:50:55,727
[SPEAKER_00]: So the quicker we get them,

1398
01:50:56,798 --> 01:51:10,180
[SPEAKER_00]: know, certified and decision made, then if something else comes up in the next nine months, say Boston runs an academy or Brookline or some other department where we can try to get them in there, we could get them a little bit sooner.

1399
01:51:10,921 --> 01:51:11,102
[SPEAKER_00]: But

1400
01:51:12,160 --> 01:51:16,663
[SPEAKER_00]: Um, in the absence of that, you're talking before we're going to see them will be in fiscal 25.

1401
01:51:16,763 --> 01:51:16,903
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay.

1402
01:51:18,144 --> 01:51:19,885
[SPEAKER_00]: So, and that's what I know.

1403
01:51:20,285 --> 01:51:33,533
[SPEAKER_00]: There's always, uh, what I found out in the last 18 months, the unknown where all of a sudden somebody's, you know, I did a little, uh, another little analysis and there's seven firefighters that are over 32 years.

1404
01:51:34,414 --> 01:51:35,234
[SPEAKER_00]: Some of them got 40 years.

1405
01:51:37,086 --> 01:51:41,607
[SPEAKER_00]: Some of them have 36 years and one has 37 and another one 33.

1406
01:51:42,027 --> 01:51:46,028
[SPEAKER_00]: So they have the age, they have the time, but they're hanging around, right?

1407
01:51:46,128 --> 01:51:49,829
[SPEAKER_00]: So, but they could just in any moment make a decision, hey, I'm done.

1408
01:51:50,509 --> 01:51:52,250
[SPEAKER_00]: And you know, they're ready to go.

1409
01:51:52,350 --> 01:51:54,510
[SPEAKER_00]: So, but they're not, they're hanging around.

1410
01:51:54,590 --> 01:51:59,391
[SPEAKER_00]: So I can't count those when I do my analysis, cause they could stay.

1411
01:52:00,571 --> 01:52:02,692
[SPEAKER_00]: There is one in that group that's gonna age out

1412
01:52:03,585 --> 01:52:05,786
[SPEAKER_00]: in early fiscal 25.

1413
01:52:06,227 --> 01:52:13,271
[SPEAKER_00]: So there's at least one more that I know in, you know, because once we turn 65, we have to leave, that's the deal, right?

1414
01:52:14,011 --> 01:52:17,553
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's what I know as of right now.

1415
01:52:17,773 --> 01:52:24,597
[SPEAKER_00]: And what's happening is it's exceeding, the rate they're leaving at is exceeding my ability to replace them.

1416
01:52:25,758 --> 01:52:29,580
[SPEAKER_00]: Even if I call right now today, because it takes so long to do that process.

1417
01:52:30,600 --> 01:52:32,941
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's the best explanation I have for that.

1418
01:52:33,221 --> 01:52:42,883
[SPEAKER_15]: So just confirming outside of this, whatever is going on with this too, that we don't know, you do have within this budget, to your understanding, money for those 10 positions?

1419
01:52:44,183 --> 01:52:45,583
[SPEAKER_00]: Right now, I do.

1420
01:52:47,003 --> 01:52:55,785
[SPEAKER_00]: Even if this is correct and it's 78, I do have the money there to fill those positions in this budget.

1421
01:52:56,305 --> 01:52:58,526
[SPEAKER_00]: And there'll still be some left over

1422
01:52:59,417 --> 01:53:01,099
[SPEAKER_00]: That'll be what we call vacant positions.

1423
01:53:01,119 --> 01:53:12,689
[SPEAKER_00]: We talked about that last budget season that we have to maintain, because what's going to happen, the side effect of all this, if we don't get them quick enough, then the overtime goes up and then I exceed the overtime budget.

1424
01:53:12,729 --> 01:53:15,531
[SPEAKER_00]: So that money's there to kind of protect me when I go over.

1425
01:53:15,551 --> 01:53:16,112
[SPEAKER_15]: Okay.

1426
01:53:16,692 --> 01:53:20,613
[SPEAKER_15]: And as I understand, police are having an issue getting qualified candidates.

1427
01:53:21,593 --> 01:53:24,674
[SPEAKER_15]: Is FIRE having the same issue, or it's just simply the delay of the academy?

1428
01:53:25,414 --> 01:53:27,275
[SPEAKER_00]: It's more or less the delay in the academy.

1429
01:53:27,295 --> 01:53:33,196
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, I have to have the conversation with the mayor, and she has to give me the authorization to begin.

1430
01:53:33,216 --> 01:53:36,377
[SPEAKER_00]: Once that happens, like I said, that time clock will start.

1431
01:53:40,440 --> 01:53:47,804
[SPEAKER_00]: I'll begin all, you know, usually we start with the background checks, then we go make a decision from there, how many make it through that.

1432
01:53:47,884 --> 01:53:57,029
[SPEAKER_00]: Cause that's the other issue that's happening is not, we've had sort of a, when we call for the list, sometimes we don't get as many on the list that we need to hire.

1433
01:53:57,089 --> 01:54:02,851
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you're going to hire say 10, for example, you might need to look at 30 because that's the civil service rules.

1434
01:54:03,632 --> 01:54:07,254
[SPEAKER_00]: So you might go through that list and you don't end up with 10, you can end up,

1435
01:54:08,500 --> 01:54:09,001
[SPEAKER_00]: with less.

1436
01:54:09,461 --> 01:54:10,482
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's the fear.

1437
01:54:10,522 --> 01:54:14,647
[SPEAKER_00]: And then, um, uh, you know, the list could run out.

1438
01:54:15,669 --> 01:54:20,294
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, I, I don't think this one will, but you know, they give the test every, every year.

1439
01:54:20,394 --> 01:54:24,199
[SPEAKER_00]: So, um, you know, there was some discussion

1440
01:54:24,824 --> 01:54:33,527
[SPEAKER_00]: and in the chief's association about maybe creating a reserve list so that like you have these people on the list and when those openings open up the academy, you can jump on.

1441
01:54:34,287 --> 01:54:39,629
[SPEAKER_00]: And then every time these people retire, you could say, okay, uh, we're going to hire, you know what I mean?

1442
01:54:39,669 --> 01:54:45,731
[SPEAKER_00]: If you have a certified list to pull from, but, um, Medford's never traditionally done that in the fire department.

1443
01:54:45,751 --> 01:54:47,372
[SPEAKER_00]: So that would be a change.

1444
01:54:47,912 --> 01:54:48,152
[SPEAKER_00]: Um,

1445
01:54:49,545 --> 01:54:59,593
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, my advice to the may is going to be start immediately, get the process started, get them all, um, you know, pull the list from civil service, get, get started on the background checks.

1446
01:54:59,613 --> 01:55:05,197
[SPEAKER_00]: The quicker we get that done, the faster I can petition the academy and get that clock started.

1447
01:55:07,218 --> 01:55:07,539
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

1448
01:55:09,260 --> 01:55:09,880
[SPEAKER_15]: Vice is embarrassed.

1449
01:55:10,581 --> 01:55:11,441
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you, Madam President.

1450
01:55:11,501 --> 01:55:12,062
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you, chief.

1451
01:55:12,382 --> 01:55:15,244
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, just a couple of quick clarifying questions.

1452
01:55:15,484 --> 01:55:18,166
[SPEAKER_03]: One on the facilities.

1453
01:55:18,707 --> 01:55:18,767
[SPEAKER_03]: Um,

1454
01:55:19,390 --> 01:55:22,914
[SPEAKER_03]: So you said the feasibility for the fire headquarters is about 45% done?

1455
01:55:23,475 --> 01:55:28,260
[SPEAKER_00]: That's what I understand from the architectural studio that we hired.

1456
01:55:29,461 --> 01:55:34,467
[SPEAKER_03]: Given that, what would be the timeline for feasibility and design to finish?

1457
01:55:34,907 --> 01:55:36,970
[SPEAKER_03]: Is that about six months to a year?

1458
01:55:37,896 --> 01:55:41,018
[SPEAKER_00]: whatever, it all depends on what that study says.

1459
01:55:42,118 --> 01:55:47,060
[SPEAKER_00]: It may say several things, but whatever that does end up saying, then a decision will be made.

1460
01:55:47,080 --> 01:55:49,422
[SPEAKER_00]: All right, which direction are we going in?

1461
01:55:50,202 --> 01:55:56,405
[SPEAKER_00]: And then once that's made, that whole design process will continue, right?

1462
01:55:56,965 --> 01:56:02,208
[SPEAKER_00]: And we've already been working towards what we think we need based on

1463
01:56:03,418 --> 01:56:05,019
[SPEAKER_00]: the requirements of the fire department.

1464
01:56:05,279 --> 01:56:05,559
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay.

1465
01:56:05,660 --> 01:56:08,762
[SPEAKER_00]: And we look at 50 years, you know, it's going to be a 50 year building.

1466
01:56:08,782 --> 01:56:12,704
[SPEAKER_00]: So you have to kind of think ahead and say, okay, do we have room for expansion here?

1467
01:56:12,844 --> 01:56:22,531
[SPEAKER_00]: If they decide to expand and run an ambulance, or if they're going to run a heavy rescue, or if we're going to add another company, you know, to the headquarters, do you have the space?

1468
01:56:22,551 --> 01:56:24,653
[SPEAKER_00]: Do you have the room, the dorm rooms?

1469
01:56:24,673 --> 01:56:26,754
[SPEAKER_00]: Do you have the, you know, the capacity?

1470
01:56:27,414 --> 01:56:31,978
[SPEAKER_00]: So, you know, we're trying to be forward thinking, but at the same time conservative.

1471
01:56:31,998 --> 01:56:32,458
[SPEAKER_00]: So we're not,

1472
01:56:32,956 --> 01:56:34,477
[SPEAKER_00]: spending too much of the city's money.

1473
01:56:34,517 --> 01:56:39,700
[SPEAKER_00]: We wanna get what we need and not go overly elaborate, right?

1474
01:56:40,040 --> 01:56:42,462
[SPEAKER_00]: But yet still have the room to expand if we need it.

1475
01:56:43,182 --> 01:56:53,328
[SPEAKER_00]: So once that is figured out by the architects, then we can, basically you're gonna tabulate that how many square feet and that will equate to a number.

1476
01:56:53,408 --> 01:56:57,070
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we're gonna have to go to the city and find the money, just like the high school.

1477
01:56:57,730 --> 01:56:59,632
[SPEAKER_00]: There has to be a process, how we're gonna fund it.

1478
01:57:00,472 --> 01:57:03,274
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think at that point, it'll be like, all right, take a breath.

1479
01:57:03,394 --> 01:57:04,154
[SPEAKER_00]: Let's figure this out.

1480
01:57:05,055 --> 01:57:05,755
[SPEAKER_00]: And then they fund it.

1481
01:57:05,875 --> 01:57:07,036
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we'll have a timeline.

1482
01:57:07,076 --> 01:57:17,522
[SPEAKER_00]: I think if we funded it, when I talked to the architects, they're saying probably from that point on, probably four years it'll be built for the ribbon cutting.

1483
01:57:17,902 --> 01:57:22,465
[SPEAKER_00]: That's the estimate, depending on how long it takes to fund it.

1484
01:57:22,665 --> 01:57:25,407
[SPEAKER_03]: And that's from when we have the funding decided?

1485
01:57:25,427 --> 01:57:28,089
[SPEAKER_00]: From when we have the funding to when we actually ribbon cut.

1486
01:57:29,001 --> 01:57:30,282
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's rough.

1487
01:57:30,342 --> 01:57:31,604
[SPEAKER_00]: That's a very rough estimate.

1488
01:57:31,804 --> 01:57:39,072
[SPEAKER_00]: And it all depends on how long it takes to get, you know, if it has to go on the ballot or something like that and delay it, you know, so.

1489
01:57:40,453 --> 01:57:53,063
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, we just were working with them very closely to try and get that square footage down, and I'm trying to get them to kind of complete that feasibility study so we can share that with the city makes them this high level decisions.

1490
01:57:53,303 --> 01:57:53,524
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1491
01:57:54,124 --> 01:58:03,472
[SPEAKER_03]: And then we'll move on is the is the, and again I understand if you can't quite answer but you know, by this time next year do we think we'll have the study and done and the number or.

1492
01:58:04,503 --> 01:58:06,224
[SPEAKER_00]: I think we'll have a study done pretty quick.

1493
01:58:06,284 --> 01:58:07,325
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, they owe us that.

1494
01:58:07,365 --> 01:58:09,126
[SPEAKER_00]: I've been kind of pushing for that, you know?

1495
01:58:10,046 --> 01:58:15,169
[SPEAKER_00]: And then the number, once that study is done and the decisions are made, I think it'll be pretty quick.

1496
01:58:15,189 --> 01:58:20,312
[SPEAKER_00]: We'll have a number to come back to the council and say, hey, you know, we're gonna need X amount of dollars for this.

1497
01:58:21,533 --> 01:58:21,773
[SPEAKER_03]: So.

1498
01:58:24,014 --> 01:58:24,314
[SPEAKER_03]: Got it.

1499
01:58:25,235 --> 01:58:29,917
[SPEAKER_03]: Definitely understand that it's a process, but also, you know, I think we all feel the urgency around it too.

1500
01:58:29,977 --> 01:58:30,818
[SPEAKER_03]: And just to clarify this,

1501
01:58:31,429 --> 01:58:35,132
[SPEAKER_03]: we're looking at the site of the existing HQ plus the former police headquarters.

1502
01:58:35,292 --> 01:58:41,257
[SPEAKER_00]: There's also within that, you know, square footage, you're also looking at how you're gonna heat it, cool it.

1503
01:58:41,618 --> 01:58:41,778
[SPEAKER_03]: Right.

1504
01:58:41,798 --> 01:58:42,999
[SPEAKER_00]: And we're looking at efficiency.

1505
01:58:43,099 --> 01:58:44,920
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, the city has to make some decisions there.

1506
01:58:44,940 --> 01:58:52,587
[SPEAKER_00]: How efficient do you want, you know, cause obviously there's different levels of efficiency, you know, there's lead gold, I believe is the best, right.

1507
01:58:52,627 --> 01:58:54,529
[SPEAKER_00]: But that comes at a much greater cost.

1508
01:58:54,769 --> 01:58:59,333
[SPEAKER_00]: Cause you're putting in all electric, you know, solar,

1509
01:58:59,873 --> 01:59:07,241
[SPEAKER_00]: Maybe geothermal, you know, that one would have the highest cost and then there's sort of like a two and a three, you know, version of that.

1510
01:59:07,522 --> 01:59:12,727
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, so that those are again all decisions that the city has to make once we get there.

1511
01:59:12,747 --> 01:59:18,333
[SPEAKER_00]: And then the other problem we run into is the fire service is extremely, we use a lot of energy.

1512
01:59:18,914 --> 01:59:35,899
[SPEAKER_00]: So it's extremely hard to accomplish legal, although it has, I'm told now it has been done, but at what cost, right, like what's the maintenance cost going to be afterwards on all this high tech stuff because that's what we're doing we're talking about putting in solar geothermal high tech.

1513
01:59:37,159 --> 01:59:51,015
[SPEAKER_00]: radiant heating, you know, something that needs to have high level maintenance that you don't normally see in a regular fossil fuel or something that's less, maybe like heat pumps, things like that.

1514
01:59:51,035 --> 01:59:51,075
[SPEAKER_00]: So

1515
01:59:52,935 --> 01:59:53,936
[SPEAKER_00]: Those are decisions.

1516
01:59:54,076 --> 01:59:59,559
[SPEAKER_00]: Those are something that we look at the grants that are out there and we look at the cost and we say, okay, is it possible?

1517
01:59:59,579 --> 02:00:04,142
[SPEAKER_00]: How big is the building that determines how big, how many tons of cooling and heating we're gonna do?

1518
02:00:04,623 --> 02:00:11,247
[SPEAKER_00]: And then based on the, whatever incentives that are out there, the city can make that decision.

1519
02:00:12,127 --> 02:00:14,629
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we try to go for whatever that decision is.

1520
02:00:14,669 --> 02:00:15,930
[SPEAKER_00]: That's what we strive for.

1521
02:00:16,910 --> 02:00:18,171
[SPEAKER_03]: Got it.

1522
02:00:18,191 --> 02:00:21,914
[SPEAKER_03]: Last question is this question I asked to Tim earlier, you know,

1523
02:00:24,343 --> 02:00:31,296
[SPEAKER_03]: just, you know, what are some metrics that you think about on a daily basis or on an annual basis, you know, that allow you to say, you know, measure your success.

1524
02:00:31,376 --> 02:00:36,005
[SPEAKER_03]: So, you know, this was a good day, or we've made some real progress this year.

1525
02:00:38,175 --> 02:00:46,203
[SPEAKER_03]: those kind of things and respecting that I think obviously we know the first one is that no one's injured and everyone comes home.

1526
02:00:46,243 --> 02:00:47,604
[SPEAKER_00]: That's the most important.

1527
02:00:47,644 --> 02:00:48,845
[SPEAKER_00]: That's how I measure success.

1528
02:00:48,905 --> 02:00:50,406
[SPEAKER_00]: We all go home at the end of the shift, right?

1529
02:00:50,426 --> 02:00:50,587
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

1530
02:00:50,887 --> 02:00:51,507
[SPEAKER_00]: That's the goal.

1531
02:00:51,567 --> 02:00:52,889
[SPEAKER_00]: Safety, number one.

1532
02:00:52,969 --> 02:00:55,231
[SPEAKER_00]: Not only our safety but the residents.

1533
02:00:55,351 --> 02:00:55,811
[SPEAKER_00]: Exactly.

1534
02:00:56,312 --> 02:00:59,034
[SPEAKER_00]: And so I constantly, we obviously

1535
02:01:00,908 --> 02:01:02,831
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, um, document all of that.

1536
02:01:02,871 --> 02:01:04,353
[SPEAKER_00]: And we look at it all the time, right?

1537
02:01:04,393 --> 02:01:11,783
[SPEAKER_00]: We have this system we use called interest reporting, national fire incident reporting system, and all of our data is logged into that.

1538
02:01:12,544 --> 02:01:17,170
[SPEAKER_00]: And on top of that, um, you know, I constantly look at, um,

1539
02:01:18,892 --> 02:01:21,274
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, the amount of injury hours, right?

1540
02:01:21,314 --> 02:01:31,660
[SPEAKER_00]: Like, so every year, um, I've only been here 18 months, but every so often I look at, all right, per fiscal year, how many hours of injury did we pay out?

1541
02:01:31,860 --> 02:01:32,120
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

1542
02:01:32,801 --> 02:01:35,022
[SPEAKER_00]: And I'd like to see that number going down.

1543
02:01:35,062 --> 02:01:39,425
[SPEAKER_00]: But the reality of the situation is, is that as the department ages, as we get older,

1544
02:01:39,915 --> 02:01:41,376
[SPEAKER_00]: injury rate goes up, right?

1545
02:01:42,116 --> 02:01:51,600
[SPEAKER_00]: And, you know, we try to get new firefighters so that, you know, the average age goes down, the injury goes down, but then it's also a function of the amount of calls.

1546
02:01:51,660 --> 02:01:55,022
[SPEAKER_00]: So we've seen an increase in calls in the last three years.

1547
02:01:55,062 --> 02:01:59,784
[SPEAKER_00]: So we went from, you know, say somewhere around 11,000 and we're almost at, I think last year we were at 12,289.

1548
02:01:59,884 --> 02:02:03,165
[SPEAKER_00]: This year we're on point to go over 13.

1549
02:02:09,235 --> 02:02:17,358
[SPEAKER_00]: when you see an increase in call volume and you're getting more fires and more calls, the incidence of injury should go up.

1550
02:02:17,638 --> 02:02:24,220
[SPEAKER_00]: And when I look at injury hours, it stayed steady from the last three times I looked at it.

1551
02:02:24,300 --> 02:02:27,781
[SPEAKER_00]: So in the last three years, it's been 8,000 hours every year.

1552
02:02:28,142 --> 02:02:31,843
[SPEAKER_00]: That's the amount of injury hours if you add everybody up that was hurt, okay?

1553
02:02:32,423 --> 02:02:35,885
[SPEAKER_00]: So it's, so it's kind of staying the same where the call volume went up.

1554
02:02:35,945 --> 02:02:36,665
[SPEAKER_00]: It's staying the same.

1555
02:02:36,705 --> 02:02:46,091
[SPEAKER_00]: So it, it, it doesn't look like it's, it seems like it's static, but with the amount of call volume, it's actually, I think when I look at that, I say, okay, you know, that's good.

1556
02:02:46,271 --> 02:02:52,034
[SPEAKER_00]: The other thing I have done since I took over is I prioritize training, training, training, training, right?

1557
02:02:52,554 --> 02:02:55,576
[SPEAKER_00]: So you do your training, you do your knowledge, skills, and abilities.

1558
02:02:55,776 --> 02:02:57,777
[SPEAKER_00]: You evaluate after you do this training.

1559
02:02:57,837 --> 02:02:58,097
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay.

1560
02:02:58,137 --> 02:02:59,158
[SPEAKER_00]: What could we have done better?

1561
02:03:00,230 --> 02:03:08,494
[SPEAKER_00]: And then, um, that the effect of that is supposed to be a decrease in injuries, decrease in accidents and mistakes in general.

1562
02:03:08,534 --> 02:03:08,774
[SPEAKER_00]: Right?

1563
02:03:09,574 --> 02:03:13,075
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's what I've done since I took over and we continue to do that.

1564
02:03:13,115 --> 02:03:16,737
[SPEAKER_00]: That's one of the budgets, the line items in there that I asked for an increase in because

1565
02:03:17,912 --> 02:03:29,341
[SPEAKER_00]: know, if you look at what happened when I took over, we lost, you know, Gilberto retired, he had 23 years experience, I come in, I'm at 18 months, I need training, I left my position, I wore five hats when I was a deputy.

1566
02:03:29,861 --> 02:03:33,484
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay, so I had to rebuild that underneath me, but they don't have the skill level of me.

1567
02:03:34,144 --> 02:03:35,886
[SPEAKER_00]: So I'm constantly training them.

1568
02:03:36,426 --> 02:03:39,028
[SPEAKER_00]: And then as you promote a captain and a lieutenant,

1569
02:03:39,752 --> 02:03:40,713
[SPEAKER_00]: You lose your driver.

1570
02:03:40,833 --> 02:03:44,877
[SPEAKER_00]: So the drivers that are driving the apparatus, once they get promoted, they can't drive anymore.

1571
02:03:45,378 --> 02:03:51,043
[SPEAKER_00]: So now you've got new guys driving the apparatus and they need apparatus driver training.

1572
02:03:51,103 --> 02:03:54,627
[SPEAKER_00]: So we brought in training for that and it just.

1573
02:03:55,435 --> 02:04:03,805
[SPEAKER_00]: The more retirements we see, I lost a high-level deputy that retired early, and he was my IT guy, right?

1574
02:04:03,825 --> 02:04:09,912
[SPEAKER_00]: So now I'm leaning on Jim, and hopefully this new guy, I can lean on him when he gets all set up.

1575
02:04:11,313 --> 02:04:12,654
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm embracing technology.

1576
02:04:12,714 --> 02:04:18,739
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm bringing in, I was talking to the water department about doing a flow model for all the hydrants, right?

1577
02:04:18,799 --> 02:04:23,783
[SPEAKER_00]: And then color coding the hydrants so that we pull up to a hydrant, the color on the hydrant means something.

1578
02:04:24,004 --> 02:04:25,305
[SPEAKER_00]: Currently they're all the same color.

1579
02:04:26,105 --> 02:04:33,912
[SPEAKER_00]: And, you know, so like they have a whole NFPA color standard, but that's going to take time and money to go and do the flow models.

1580
02:04:34,632 --> 02:04:36,133
[SPEAKER_00]: But what I've done with,

1581
02:04:37,094 --> 02:04:39,757
[SPEAKER_00]: Tim was, we sat down with the water department.

1582
02:04:39,777 --> 02:04:44,401
[SPEAKER_00]: We said, okay, as this model is made and as you guys get the data, share it with us.

1583
02:04:45,221 --> 02:04:46,843
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we'll have that data.

1584
02:04:47,724 --> 02:04:48,404
[SPEAKER_00]: It's on maps.

1585
02:04:48,544 --> 02:04:50,186
[SPEAKER_00]: We'll know what size water main is there.

1586
02:04:50,286 --> 02:04:53,549
[SPEAKER_00]: Currently right now, we have, you know, very little idea of what we're hooking up to.

1587
02:04:53,569 --> 02:04:55,671
[SPEAKER_00]: We just hook up to a height and hopefully it's okay, right?

1588
02:04:56,371 --> 02:04:59,754
[SPEAKER_00]: So once we hook up to it, we know, but by that time it's too late.

1589
02:04:59,814 --> 02:05:02,637
[SPEAKER_00]: So it'd be nice to be able to, as we're coming into the scene, okay,

1590
02:05:03,117 --> 02:05:04,158
[SPEAKER_00]: This is a six inch main.

1591
02:05:04,198 --> 02:05:04,879
[SPEAKER_00]: This is an eight inch.

1592
02:05:04,939 --> 02:05:05,939
[SPEAKER_00]: This one's a 16.

1593
02:05:06,620 --> 02:05:08,482
[SPEAKER_00]: I know where we're going to get the most water from now.

1594
02:05:08,582 --> 02:05:10,503
[SPEAKER_00]: And we're going to put that on the tablets and the trucks.

1595
02:05:10,543 --> 02:05:16,248
[SPEAKER_00]: That's another thing that will be good for the firefighters.

1596
02:05:16,268 --> 02:05:18,770
[SPEAKER_00]: They can actually look at the screen and see where the water mains are.

1597
02:05:18,810 --> 02:05:20,432
[SPEAKER_00]: But that all comes at a cost.

1598
02:05:20,452 --> 02:05:21,312
[SPEAKER_00]: You have to buy an app.

1599
02:05:22,213 --> 02:05:28,779
[SPEAKER_00]: And you have to basically buy the licenses for each computer so that you can load it on there.

1600
02:05:29,883 --> 02:05:32,184
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think eventually we'll get there.

1601
02:05:32,264 --> 02:05:38,945
[SPEAKER_00]: And then the goal is to have the water department increase, you guys were talking about what more staffing you could do in the DPW.

1602
02:05:40,406 --> 02:05:45,207
[SPEAKER_00]: I have an answer for that is increase the amount of water mean that you change on a yearly basis.

1603
02:05:45,247 --> 02:05:51,328
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you're changing a quarter of a mile a year right now, based on the modeling, once we get back, we should increase that amount.

1604
02:05:51,408 --> 02:05:53,028
[SPEAKER_00]: It should be maybe four miles a year.

1605
02:05:53,249 --> 02:05:55,089
[SPEAKER_00]: And I don't know what that cost would be.

1606
02:05:56,149 --> 02:05:58,930
[SPEAKER_00]: It might translate to doing it in-house and hiring more staff.

1607
02:05:59,680 --> 02:06:02,544
[SPEAKER_00]: And then you could replace more means when we find the problem.

1608
02:06:02,924 --> 02:06:03,144
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

1609
02:06:03,785 --> 02:06:05,568
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's kind of where I'm at.

1610
02:06:06,429 --> 02:06:07,650
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, no, that's helpful.

1611
02:06:07,710 --> 02:06:10,253
[SPEAKER_03]: That's I've had some conversations with Tim and Dan.

1612
02:06:12,413 --> 02:06:18,295
[SPEAKER_03]: about that issue with the water mains and we can see obviously how that really goes right into the work that you do.

1613
02:06:18,375 --> 02:06:19,976
[SPEAKER_00]: I do also look at response time.

1614
02:06:20,356 --> 02:06:20,576
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah.

1615
02:06:20,776 --> 02:06:28,919
[SPEAKER_00]: I get a daily report every day by email from Armstrong, exactly how long it takes them to get on scene when they get the call.

1616
02:06:29,479 --> 02:06:36,541
[SPEAKER_00]: If it's an ALS unit, a BLS unit, and then I get graphs and charts each day, like it shows me if something's in red, I know something went awry.

1617
02:06:36,901 --> 02:06:41,063
[SPEAKER_00]: For example, say there's three medicals come in all at the same time.

1618
02:06:41,103 --> 02:06:42,003
[SPEAKER_00]: It's very common, right?

1619
02:06:42,599 --> 02:06:46,701
[SPEAKER_00]: So A1 goes to the first cardiac one, and then they send a BLS and a BLS.

1620
02:06:46,741 --> 02:06:51,803
[SPEAKER_00]: And now the third one's coming from Arlington, or it's coming from wherever it's coming from, right?

1621
02:06:52,243 --> 02:06:54,364
[SPEAKER_00]: That may take longer to get there, right?

1622
02:06:54,424 --> 02:06:56,224
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's the beauty of having a fight department.

1623
02:06:56,244 --> 02:07:01,747
[SPEAKER_00]: The fight department gets there in under three, and we stabilize the patient, and then we wait for that.

1624
02:07:01,767 --> 02:07:04,528
[SPEAKER_00]: It affords that ambulance time to get there.

1625
02:07:04,848 --> 02:07:09,030
[SPEAKER_00]: So as long as we're meeting that standard with who's responding there and we're stabilizing,

1626
02:07:10,533 --> 02:07:21,464
[SPEAKER_00]: And sometimes what happens, what's been happening with with Armstrong is and all these ambulance companies for that matter, same thing we're having, the staff is leaving, moving quicker than they can replace.

1627
02:07:22,144 --> 02:07:24,366
[SPEAKER_00]: So they've done some things, they've hired some more staff.

1628
02:07:25,187 --> 02:07:31,994
[SPEAKER_00]: And I've also when we did the contract this year, I met with them and I asked for a third ambulance to be in the city.

1629
02:07:33,495 --> 02:07:40,597
[SPEAKER_00]: So currently we have two ambulances and during the hours from eight in the morning to eight at night, that's where I saw the peak volume.

1630
02:07:41,037 --> 02:07:43,577
[SPEAKER_00]: So you talk about efficiency, that's where we need a third one.

1631
02:07:44,037 --> 02:07:56,740
[SPEAKER_00]: So what we did was we brought another ambulance in and the two medics that are in the medic car now, if they need a transport, they can go back and get that ambulance and become a third transport unit in those cases where like

1632
02:07:57,659 --> 02:08:00,521
[SPEAKER_00]: we run into a situation where we're waiting a long time for an ambulance.

1633
02:08:00,661 --> 02:08:03,802
[SPEAKER_00]: And since I've done that, I've seen a lot less problems.

1634
02:08:03,822 --> 02:08:07,004
[SPEAKER_00]: We still have problems every now and then, like every now and then it's just weird.

1635
02:08:07,024 --> 02:08:15,128
[SPEAKER_00]: Like you'll get seven medicals will come in, you know, for example, in the town next door, like Malden, Everett, and then we'll have seven.

1636
02:08:15,148 --> 02:08:17,670
[SPEAKER_00]: There's no way the system can handle that.

1637
02:08:17,810 --> 02:08:19,631
[SPEAKER_00]: It just, it ends up, somebody's going to be waiting.

1638
02:08:20,251 --> 02:08:24,173
[SPEAKER_00]: So what we try to do is, and what I told Armstrong is they have fleet eyes.

1639
02:08:24,193 --> 02:08:25,454
[SPEAKER_00]: They know where all their trucks are.

1640
02:08:25,714 --> 02:08:26,014
[SPEAKER_00]: Okay.

1641
02:08:26,875 --> 02:08:26,995
[SPEAKER_00]: And

1642
02:08:27,879 --> 02:08:35,365
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, they have to kind of sort of triage the ambulances and say, okay, if this, because they also do our EMD, which is emergency medical dispatch.

1643
02:08:36,346 --> 02:08:40,749
[SPEAKER_00]: And they know something's cardiac or it's ALS, right?

1644
02:08:41,049 --> 02:08:46,914
[SPEAKER_00]: So prioritize that ambulance, move that one over first and go to the ALS call.

1645
02:08:47,214 --> 02:08:49,596
[SPEAKER_00]: The BLS call can be stabilized while we're waiting.

1646
02:08:50,225 --> 02:08:58,109
[SPEAKER_00]: And so it goes against the contract a little bit because they're regionalizing without doing it.

1647
02:08:58,649 --> 02:09:01,770
[SPEAKER_00]: But what it does is it increased the efficiency.

1648
02:09:03,371 --> 02:09:08,473
[SPEAKER_00]: And it's only during those times when the calls are at such a peak that it's overwhelmed everybody.

1649
02:09:10,614 --> 02:09:13,215
[SPEAKER_00]: And it's been working out better.

1650
02:09:13,235 --> 02:09:15,396
[SPEAKER_00]: They're working on getting more staff constantly.

1651
02:09:16,017 --> 02:09:17,517
[SPEAKER_00]: I mean, that's definitely helping a little bit.

1652
02:09:19,935 --> 02:09:23,997
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, those are the kinds of things I look at, you know, as chief, it's like, okay.

1653
02:09:24,657 --> 02:09:33,422
[SPEAKER_00]: And if there is a problem, if I detect a problem, sometimes my staff will come to me, hey, it took like too long to get to this call or something happened where the ambulance was late.

1654
02:09:33,962 --> 02:09:36,824
[SPEAKER_00]: And then I make a phone call, I talk to them and say, okay, what happened here?

1655
02:09:37,364 --> 02:09:38,805
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we look into it, right?

1656
02:09:38,825 --> 02:09:44,167
[SPEAKER_00]: There's a million things that could have happened that as the fire chief, I have that,

1657
02:09:45,932 --> 02:09:50,334
[SPEAKER_00]: on my shoulders to make sure that I investigate those so that we make sure that it won't happen again.

1658
02:09:51,115 --> 02:09:56,978
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's what I've been doing since I took over and I stay in touch with them whenever I need to investigate something.

1659
02:09:57,985 --> 02:09:59,506
[SPEAKER_00]: pull the tapes, whatever, I do that stuff.

1660
02:10:00,147 --> 02:10:00,768
[SPEAKER_03]: Very helpful.

1661
02:10:01,588 --> 02:10:03,090
[SPEAKER_03]: Um, really quick question.

1662
02:10:03,110 --> 02:10:08,815
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you think regionalizing EMS would be helpful given that it's already kind of happening?

1663
02:10:09,155 --> 02:10:12,458
[SPEAKER_00]: I think if we have a contract with them, we'll go against the contract.

1664
02:10:12,518 --> 02:10:14,200
[SPEAKER_00]: If they did, it would violate it.

1665
02:10:14,861 --> 02:10:18,904
[SPEAKER_00]: So, uh, I think there, um, you know,

1666
02:10:20,547 --> 02:10:28,856
[SPEAKER_00]: I think they're doing it without regionalizing right now, because if they have an emergency, they need to get ALS there and with that with fleet eyes, and they have the capability to do it.

1667
02:10:30,398 --> 02:10:31,720
[SPEAKER_00]: They're the best ones to do it.

1668
02:10:31,740 --> 02:10:32,601
[SPEAKER_00]: You know what I mean?

1669
02:10:32,641 --> 02:10:39,509
[SPEAKER_00]: Like, because they know where the trucks are, they're looking at a map saying this trucks, you know, the closest trucks send that one to Medford, right?

1670
02:10:40,109 --> 02:10:43,192
[SPEAKER_00]: So it speeds, and it might not even be an Armstrong ambulance.

1671
02:10:43,372 --> 02:10:45,033
[SPEAKER_00]: It could be a Cambridge ambulance.

1672
02:10:45,093 --> 02:10:47,796
[SPEAKER_00]: It could be, you know, a Fallon.

1673
02:10:47,836 --> 02:10:49,577
[SPEAKER_00]: It could be all, it could be anyone.

1674
02:10:49,617 --> 02:10:50,878
[SPEAKER_00]: They know where everyone is.

1675
02:10:51,899 --> 02:10:52,139
[SPEAKER_00]: So.

1676
02:10:52,780 --> 02:10:53,240
[SPEAKER_03]: Interesting.

1677
02:10:53,840 --> 02:10:54,101
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah.

1678
02:10:54,481 --> 02:11:02,508
[SPEAKER_00]: So, I mean, I think if we were going to do that, you know, or they were going to do that, it would violate the contract and then there'd be a problem.

1679
02:11:02,548 --> 02:11:02,708
[SPEAKER_00]: Right.

1680
02:11:02,728 --> 02:11:04,069
[SPEAKER_00]: All right.

1681
02:11:04,149 --> 02:11:04,569
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

1682
02:11:05,870 --> 02:11:06,931
[SPEAKER_14]: Councilor Kerrio.

1683
02:11:06,971 --> 02:11:07,392
[SPEAKER_20]: Thank you.

1684
02:11:07,452 --> 02:11:08,492
[SPEAKER_20]: Chief, just a couple of questions.

1685
02:11:09,963 --> 02:11:14,764
[SPEAKER_20]: You brought up the fact that you've got an abundance of medicals now.

1686
02:11:15,224 --> 02:11:17,285
[SPEAKER_20]: The community's getting older.

1687
02:11:17,305 --> 02:11:20,465
[SPEAKER_20]: I see other cities have medical trucks.

1688
02:11:20,485 --> 02:11:23,346
[SPEAKER_20]: I think we used to have one years ago.

1689
02:11:24,766 --> 02:11:25,746
[SPEAKER_20]: You mean on the fire department?

1690
02:11:26,006 --> 02:11:26,226
[SPEAKER_20]: Yes.

1691
02:11:27,207 --> 02:11:33,368
[SPEAKER_20]: Is there talk of maybe getting a medical truck to take the burden off you sending out the big truck?

1692
02:11:34,758 --> 02:11:35,299
[SPEAKER_20]: all the time.

1693
02:11:36,020 --> 02:11:39,383
[SPEAKER_00]: So, you know, I did look, I've had looked at that.

1694
02:11:39,984 --> 02:11:42,546
[SPEAKER_00]: Other cities like Woburn, they run their own ambulance.

1695
02:11:42,826 --> 02:11:57,401
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, I'm not saying running an ambulance, but you know, I have a medical, just a medical truck, you know, versus sending out a, you know, a big bumper or, you know, like I say, and I see them on the highway, the medical truck will be following the ambulance.

1696
02:11:58,324 --> 02:11:59,744
[SPEAKER_00]: Are you talking about a medic unit?

1697
02:12:00,745 --> 02:12:02,205
[SPEAKER_00]: Like an SUV?

1698
02:12:02,925 --> 02:12:04,345
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, yeah.

1699
02:12:04,505 --> 02:12:05,746
[SPEAKER_00]: We have that in the city now.

1700
02:12:05,846 --> 02:12:06,546
[SPEAKER_00]: We do have that now?

1701
02:12:06,686 --> 02:12:18,748
[SPEAKER_00]: So what we've done with them, what I did with Armstrong was those two medics, or whoever's in that medic unit, a lot of times it's quicker and easier to get the medic to that call.

1702
02:12:18,788 --> 02:12:20,509
[SPEAKER_00]: So they operate like that normally.

1703
02:12:20,829 --> 02:12:25,950
[SPEAKER_00]: In times where, between eight and eight, where things could get sort of dicey, we get a lot of call volume,

1704
02:12:27,078 --> 02:12:28,979
[SPEAKER_00]: They don't, they don't have the capability to transport.

1705
02:12:29,779 --> 02:12:30,539
[SPEAKER_00]: So now you're tying up.

1706
02:12:30,579 --> 02:12:31,700
[SPEAKER_00]: Now think about what you just said, right?

1707
02:12:31,720 --> 02:12:33,080
[SPEAKER_00]: We've got a medic in the back of the ambulance.

1708
02:12:33,100 --> 02:12:35,361
[SPEAKER_00]: Cause you want the, it's like bringing the doctor to you, right?

1709
02:12:35,761 --> 02:12:36,401
[SPEAKER_00]: He's in the back.

1710
02:12:36,441 --> 02:12:38,462
[SPEAKER_00]: Someone's driving his, his SUV.

1711
02:12:38,482 --> 02:12:42,724
[SPEAKER_00]: So you're tying up the medic and you, the ambulance has to go.

1712
02:12:42,744 --> 02:12:48,266
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's part of the problem too, that I didn't want to get into, but because we don't have a hospital anymore, right.

1713
02:12:48,686 --> 02:12:51,867
[SPEAKER_00]: Everyone's either going to Winchester, they're going to Mass General, they're going out of the city.

1714
02:12:52,634 --> 02:12:53,995
[SPEAKER_00]: And a lot of times it's mass transit.

1715
02:12:54,055 --> 02:12:58,178
[SPEAKER_00]: So, but even if they go to Winchester or Melrose or wherever they go, right?

1716
02:12:59,839 --> 02:13:01,840
[SPEAKER_00]: It takes time to turn that ambulance around.

1717
02:13:02,040 --> 02:13:08,244
[SPEAKER_00]: So we also sent letters to the hospitals too, because what was happening was they were using those medics like doctors.

1718
02:13:08,284 --> 02:13:14,828
[SPEAKER_00]: They were kind of like triaging the patient saying, okay, don't turn those over to us till we can get a doctor for it, right?

1719
02:13:14,928 --> 02:13:20,952
[SPEAKER_00]: So they were holding them at the hospital and it was tying up resources, making it almost impossible to get them back

1720
02:13:21,338 --> 02:13:21,939
[SPEAKER_00]: in a timely manner.

1721
02:13:21,959 --> 02:13:22,660
[SPEAKER_00]: It would take hours.

1722
02:13:23,882 --> 02:13:36,642
[SPEAKER_00]: So we wrote a letter to them and basically they had to hire some more staff within the hospital to be able to care for these patients and turn the ambulances around quicker because it was having the side effect of people not getting an ambulance for

1723
02:13:37,397 --> 02:13:39,757
[SPEAKER_00]: you know, six, eight, 10 minutes, and that's dangerous.

1724
02:13:40,138 --> 02:13:43,278
[SPEAKER_00]: So, um, since we, that was another thing we did.

1725
02:13:43,298 --> 02:13:49,639
[SPEAKER_00]: I just, you know, you just brought it back to my memory that, that by doing that, it's, it turned it around, turned them around quicker.

1726
02:13:50,199 --> 02:13:56,401
[SPEAKER_00]: But in the past, when we had the Lawrence, right, the ambulance were all here, even if they weren't, were at the hospital, they could clear them.

1727
02:13:56,441 --> 02:13:57,221
[SPEAKER_00]: They're in Medford.

1728
02:13:57,581 --> 02:14:01,202
[SPEAKER_00]: Now they're all either in Boston, Winchester, Melrose, wherever they are.

1729
02:14:01,222 --> 02:14:03,162
[SPEAKER_00]: So that time to go from A to B,

1730
02:14:03,860 --> 02:14:05,020
[SPEAKER_00]: It takes longer to get them back.

1731
02:14:05,060 --> 02:14:08,261
[SPEAKER_00]: So that, I think, is another side effect of losing the hospital.

1732
02:14:08,482 --> 02:14:10,502
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, you're right.

1733
02:14:11,563 --> 02:14:12,703
[SPEAKER_20]: So last question.

1734
02:14:13,523 --> 02:14:17,845
[SPEAKER_20]: So the city is looking to grow and expand.

1735
02:14:18,525 --> 02:14:23,687
[SPEAKER_20]: And one of the areas they're looking at is Route 16, Riverside Avenue area.

1736
02:14:24,447 --> 02:14:26,348
[SPEAKER_20]: There's going to be some building there up in the Fellsway.

1737
02:14:28,108 --> 02:14:32,730
[SPEAKER_20]: Are we going to need in the next four or five years to maybe

1738
02:14:34,027 --> 02:14:51,827
[SPEAKER_00]: uh increased staff and maybe another truck or two here or there as you know i think you hit a uh you hit on a subject that um the the city is growing in leaps and bounds right um i saw an article online it was a the 15th fastest growing city in the nation

1739
02:14:52,376 --> 02:14:56,101
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's so it was the fire department.

1740
02:14:56,261 --> 02:14:57,062
[SPEAKER_00]: The fire department.

1741
02:14:57,102 --> 02:14:59,305
[SPEAKER_00]: So to answer your question, I would love to expand.

1742
02:14:59,325 --> 02:15:02,129
[SPEAKER_00]: I'd love to have another station down at station landing somewhere.

1743
02:15:02,169 --> 02:15:09,979
[SPEAKER_00]: I'd love to have maybe put engine three in service or maybe take the two houses and combine them into a three bay station or something, you know, in the future.

1744
02:15:11,283 --> 02:15:16,727
[SPEAKER_00]: But all of that comes at a great cost, you'd have to increase minimum manning and that 14 million will go way up.

1745
02:15:17,068 --> 02:15:25,334
[SPEAKER_20]: And that's something that the city has to... But is that in your part of the capital plan, looking to grow the department as the city grows?

1746
02:15:25,374 --> 02:15:27,696
[SPEAKER_00]: It isn't yet, but I can certainly look into it.

1747
02:15:27,756 --> 02:15:34,181
[SPEAKER_00]: And we can sort of as a wish list, put it in there and see if we can... You're going to get bigger buildings, newer buildings.

1748
02:15:36,743 --> 02:15:49,973
[SPEAKER_00]: more people would be coming in and obviously attacks I mean that I thought about that when we when we were looking at headquarters I when Gilberti was chief I sort of mentioned that to him about that might have been a way to sort of

1749
02:15:50,997 --> 02:15:52,638
[SPEAKER_00]: pay for a temporary headquarters, right?

1750
02:15:52,658 --> 02:15:55,718
[SPEAKER_00]: You take and build a new station, say down a station landing, right?

1751
02:15:56,299 --> 02:16:03,501
[SPEAKER_00]: And then what you do is you put all the headquarters people out in the, once you get that built, you have enough room for the whole department to be on the peripheral.

1752
02:16:04,021 --> 02:16:05,761
[SPEAKER_00]: And that gives you an empty building to rebuild.

1753
02:16:06,302 --> 02:16:14,124
[SPEAKER_00]: And then as we go through, like you were talking about replacing stations, I mean, I'm dreaming right now, but it would be as we replace them, right?

1754
02:16:14,724 --> 02:16:16,805
[SPEAKER_00]: Then they would come to headquarters and we replace this one.

1755
02:16:16,845 --> 02:16:20,446
[SPEAKER_00]: And like, if you wanted to add another station somewhere, that's the perfect,

1756
02:16:21,159 --> 02:16:25,041
[SPEAKER_00]: sort of scenario instead of you build a headquarters, right?

1757
02:16:25,141 --> 02:16:27,522
[SPEAKER_00]: And we're going to build a temporary building at what cost?

1758
02:16:27,602 --> 02:16:29,683
[SPEAKER_00]: I'm looking very hard at Cambridge right now.

1759
02:16:29,723 --> 02:16:34,105
[SPEAKER_00]: They have a, um, I believe it's a four bay station they bought.

1760
02:16:34,765 --> 02:16:36,906
[SPEAKER_00]: That's a temporary station for millions of dollars.

1761
02:16:36,986 --> 02:16:39,587
[SPEAKER_00]: It just comes down from Canada and they put it up on this site.

1762
02:16:39,607 --> 02:16:40,848
[SPEAKER_00]: They have a site plan for it.

1763
02:16:41,708 --> 02:16:46,250
[SPEAKER_00]: And it's, it's just a temporary building while they build the new building.

1764
02:16:46,488 --> 02:16:46,708
[SPEAKER_00]: Right?

1765
02:16:47,409 --> 02:16:52,671
[SPEAKER_00]: But the better, again, I don't know the exact numbers, but I was talking to the architects about it.

1766
02:16:52,691 --> 02:17:01,096
[SPEAKER_00]: I gave them the contacts so we could kind of look into that and see what they paid for that, see how much it costs, see what the plan, the long-term plan is for that.

1767
02:17:01,376 --> 02:17:12,983
[SPEAKER_00]: Like in some ways it might be better if you were gonna have that plan and say, okay, we're gonna expand out into say station land area, landing area, or like maybe in another part of Medford.

1768
02:17:13,816 --> 02:17:15,357
[SPEAKER_00]: to build that station, a permanent one.

1769
02:17:15,777 --> 02:17:20,719
[SPEAKER_00]: And then when you're ready to do your other renovations or replacements, you have a place to go.

1770
02:17:21,819 --> 02:17:25,660
[SPEAKER_00]: And you look at the expansion, I'm looking at the expansion now as chief.

1771
02:17:25,740 --> 02:17:27,561
[SPEAKER_00]: It's like, I see all these developments, right?

1772
02:17:28,501 --> 02:17:37,685
[SPEAKER_00]: Maybe you pull some linkage money in and say, okay, if you're gonna build this big of a project, you gotta add on a fire station or put it within the development.

1773
02:17:40,046 --> 02:17:40,426
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you.

1774
02:17:40,626 --> 02:17:40,986
[SPEAKER_00]: You're welcome.

1775
02:17:42,082 --> 02:17:44,403
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, any other questions from the council?

1776
02:17:46,964 --> 02:17:48,424
[SPEAKER_15]: Members of the public who wish to speak?

1777
02:17:49,645 --> 02:17:51,065
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you, Chief.

1778
02:17:51,285 --> 02:17:55,667
[SPEAKER_15]: I think we'll open up to any, I know folks have been sitting here, Mr. Buckley's been sitting here, so.

1779
02:17:57,388 --> 02:17:58,508
[SPEAKER_07]: Happy to go ahead.

1780
02:17:58,568 --> 02:18:02,529
[SPEAKER_07]: Walter Buckley, 340 Salem Street, Meffitt, also a Meffitt firefighter.

1781
02:18:03,270 --> 02:18:08,872
[SPEAKER_07]: We just had a couple of concerns while looking at the budget, starting off with public safety supplies.

1782
02:18:10,578 --> 02:18:16,441
[SPEAKER_07]: If you look at last year's budget and this year's budget, it used to be $90,000 and it's going down to $55,000.

1783
02:18:17,081 --> 02:18:18,321
[SPEAKER_07]: I believe to this day, we've spent $92,000.

1784
02:18:27,195 --> 02:18:30,357
[SPEAKER_07]: This item pays for all fire operation related equipment.

1785
02:18:31,537 --> 02:18:38,701
[SPEAKER_07]: And obviously the firefighters feel that $55,000 is just not enough, as again, we've already spent $92,000 this year.

1786
02:18:38,881 --> 02:18:43,444
[SPEAKER_07]: We're pulling money from other line items to make up that cost.

1787
02:18:44,784 --> 02:18:49,147
[SPEAKER_07]: Also, usually in that item is turnout gear.

1788
02:18:50,307 --> 02:18:54,530
[SPEAKER_07]: Turnout gear, currently 29 members only have one set of gear.

1789
02:18:55,733 --> 02:18:59,696
[SPEAKER_07]: because of an expired set or they were never issued a second set.

1790
02:19:00,356 --> 02:19:03,699
[SPEAKER_07]: By the end of fiscal year 24, 47 more will expire.

1791
02:19:04,379 --> 02:19:08,802
[SPEAKER_07]: That's a total of 75 sets, which is equal to $400,000.

1792
02:19:11,324 --> 02:19:17,368
[SPEAKER_07]: Obviously going from $90,000 to $55,000, they're not taking into consideration that turnout care.

1793
02:19:18,289 --> 02:19:22,252
[SPEAKER_07]: I don't know if they put that in a different line item, but we can't find it anywhere.

1794
02:19:24,133 --> 02:19:26,795
[SPEAKER_07]: The next one is, you guys were talking about the manning.

1795
02:19:27,375 --> 02:19:31,738
[SPEAKER_07]: So in fiscal year 21, we had 125 members.

1796
02:19:32,598 --> 02:19:35,180
[SPEAKER_07]: Fiscal year 22, we had 123 members.

1797
02:19:36,160 --> 02:19:45,546
[SPEAKER_07]: And I don't know what they were talking about, the two members being cut, but the way we look at the budget today, fiscal year 24 gives us 120 members.

1798
02:19:46,587 --> 02:19:51,790
[SPEAKER_07]: That's another two members that we lost, that would equal to $148,000, that's two members.

1799
02:19:55,235 --> 02:20:00,678
[SPEAKER_07]: Yeah, so looking back, 1989 we had 170 members and we had 6,200 runs.

1800
02:20:00,698 --> 02:20:01,418
[SPEAKER_07]: 2022 we have 105 members, the 12,190 runs.

1801
02:20:01,438 --> 02:20:07,001
[SPEAKER_07]: So the calls are going up, they're almost doubling and we're going down, that takes,

1802
02:20:20,243 --> 02:20:22,065
[SPEAKER_07]: Firefighters, they have to work overtime.

1803
02:20:22,806 --> 02:20:24,788
[SPEAKER_07]: Physically, mentally, we're getting worn out.

1804
02:20:27,811 --> 02:20:32,336
[SPEAKER_07]: Firefighters are getting promoted to lieutenant, captain, and deputy, and it's not getting backfilled.

1805
02:20:32,516 --> 02:20:36,400
[SPEAKER_07]: As you talked about earlier, it takes about 18 months to get somebody here.

1806
02:20:36,860 --> 02:20:37,881
[SPEAKER_07]: That's if you did that today.

1807
02:20:38,202 --> 02:20:39,904
[SPEAKER_07]: There's no plan of hiring anybody today.

1808
02:20:40,764 --> 02:20:42,326
[SPEAKER_07]: So by next year, we're under 100 guys.

1809
02:20:46,034 --> 02:20:49,756
[SPEAKER_07]: It's not feasible, especially on us, on the members.

1810
02:20:50,316 --> 02:21:01,640
[SPEAKER_07]: It makes us, the morale's down in the city, and working more overtime, it's just putting stress on us, putting stress on our families.

1811
02:21:04,041 --> 02:21:06,322
[SPEAKER_07]: The last thing we wanted to talk about was the training line.

1812
02:21:06,342 --> 02:21:08,743
[SPEAKER_07]: It is getting a bump from 12,000 to 25,000.

1813
02:21:11,655 --> 02:21:16,256
[SPEAKER_07]: But with that, we're spending around $10,000 to have tiller training for new members.

1814
02:21:17,397 --> 02:21:19,237
[SPEAKER_07]: So that cuts that down to $15,000.

1815
02:21:19,497 --> 02:21:26,279
[SPEAKER_07]: Then we'll spend another $10,000 to do pump simulator training, which we do every couple of years.

1816
02:21:27,680 --> 02:21:31,081
[SPEAKER_07]: So now we're gonna have $20,000 already spent.

1817
02:21:31,921 --> 02:21:34,542
[SPEAKER_07]: The rest of the year, we have $5,000 for a training line.

1818
02:21:35,842 --> 02:21:37,823
[SPEAKER_07]: You can't train a member

1819
02:21:38,570 --> 02:21:42,291
[SPEAKER_07]: You can't train a department with 100 members, 110 members with $5,000.

1820
02:21:43,551 --> 02:21:45,632
[SPEAKER_07]: That's no training at all.

1821
02:21:46,572 --> 02:21:53,494
[SPEAKER_07]: We're hoping that someone knocks down a house and we get to go in there and cut holes in the roof and do stuff like that.

1822
02:21:54,775 --> 02:21:58,196
[SPEAKER_07]: But to actually train guys, we're not getting any classes coming in.

1823
02:21:58,736 --> 02:22:01,156
[SPEAKER_07]: Armstrong hasn't provided classes with us for a while.

1824
02:22:03,937 --> 02:22:06,118
[SPEAKER_07]: And I heard you talking about the

1825
02:22:08,607 --> 02:22:11,449
[SPEAKER_07]: We don't personally have a medical chaser car.

1826
02:22:12,009 --> 02:22:12,730
[SPEAKER_07]: That's Armstrong.

1827
02:22:13,531 --> 02:22:18,695
[SPEAKER_07]: We would love a rescue or an ambulance like that that would provide income to the city.

1828
02:22:18,735 --> 02:22:21,577
[SPEAKER_07]: And I believe Lieutenant Jones will be talking about that when I leave.

1829
02:22:21,637 --> 02:22:27,341
[SPEAKER_07]: But those are most of our biggest fears in this budget.

1830
02:22:28,242 --> 02:22:35,128
[SPEAKER_07]: The lack of public safety supplies money, the lack of staffing and the training.

1831
02:22:37,644 --> 02:22:38,664
[SPEAKER_07]: Any questions I can ask?

1832
02:22:41,105 --> 02:22:43,866
[SPEAKER_16]: Councilor Kerrio.

1833
02:22:44,426 --> 02:22:47,167
[SPEAKER_07]: What number do you think the public safety should be?

1834
02:22:47,867 --> 02:22:54,169
[SPEAKER_07]: Well, again, if we already spent $92,000 this year, we're only getting $55,000 next year.

1835
02:22:54,689 --> 02:22:56,929
[SPEAKER_20]: So it should at least be at least level funded.

1836
02:22:57,750 --> 02:22:57,990
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

1837
02:22:58,010 --> 02:22:58,350
[SPEAKER_20]: At least.

1838
02:22:59,170 --> 02:22:59,550
[SPEAKER_20]: At least.

1839
02:23:01,311 --> 02:23:06,032
[SPEAKER_20]: Now, I see underneath it there the public safety uniforms.

1840
02:23:06,881 --> 02:23:07,061
[SPEAKER_20]: Yep.

1841
02:23:07,382 --> 02:23:13,267
[SPEAKER_20]: Went from, it's going up to a little bit of a, there's a bump there.

1842
02:23:13,287 --> 02:23:17,952
[SPEAKER_20]: 110 now?

1843
02:23:18,032 --> 02:23:18,152
[SPEAKER_20]: Or 104,000?

1844
02:23:18,653 --> 02:23:22,637
[SPEAKER_20]: Are those like the irregular uniforms?

1845
02:23:27,195 --> 02:23:28,576
[SPEAKER_20]: It says public safety uniforms.

1846
02:23:28,836 --> 02:23:30,817
[SPEAKER_07]: That's the clothing, yeah, the regular uniforms.

1847
02:23:30,877 --> 02:23:33,018
[SPEAKER_07]: It has nothing to do with the bunker gear.

1848
02:23:33,799 --> 02:23:35,099
[SPEAKER_07]: The bunker gear is $5,000.

1849
02:23:35,139 --> 02:23:38,541
[SPEAKER_20]: That's not considered turnout gear.

1850
02:23:38,841 --> 02:23:39,001
[SPEAKER_20]: No.

1851
02:23:39,021 --> 02:23:39,902
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay.

1852
02:23:40,582 --> 02:23:45,405
[SPEAKER_20]: And I know, I remember we fought about turnout gear for a long time.

1853
02:23:45,645 --> 02:23:46,906
[SPEAKER_20]: Right, and we're afraid of that.

1854
02:23:47,066 --> 02:23:47,686
[SPEAKER_20]: It's not in there.

1855
02:23:47,986 --> 02:23:49,767
[SPEAKER_07]: So we're gonna have to come and fight for it again.

1856
02:23:50,007 --> 02:23:51,668
[SPEAKER_07]: There's no turnout gear at all here.

1857
02:23:51,908 --> 02:23:56,651
[SPEAKER_07]: And I believe the council and the administration talked about some kind of plan

1858
02:23:57,452 --> 02:24:00,695
[SPEAKER_07]: where they would rotate, they would know when these gears are expiring.

1859
02:24:00,755 --> 02:24:01,936
[SPEAKER_07]: We know they're expiring.

1860
02:24:01,956 --> 02:24:02,937
[SPEAKER_07]: They're expired right now.

1861
02:24:03,377 --> 02:24:04,878
[SPEAKER_07]: There's no plan to buy them.

1862
02:24:04,979 --> 02:24:06,500
[SPEAKER_07]: There's no money to buy them.

1863
02:24:06,520 --> 02:24:08,241
[SPEAKER_20]: So we need a plan for turnout, yeah.

1864
02:24:09,302 --> 02:24:10,964
[SPEAKER_00]: So I can answer some of that.

1865
02:24:12,845 --> 02:24:19,211
[SPEAKER_00]: This $90,000 that he's looking at, we did go over because of turnout gear.

1866
02:24:19,711 --> 02:24:26,157
[SPEAKER_00]: We had 12 members that came on that we bought turnout gear through that line item, OK?

1867
02:24:26,577 --> 02:24:28,659
[SPEAKER_00]: Because obviously, they come on the job.

1868
02:24:28,819 --> 02:24:30,781
[SPEAKER_00]: We had to rent gear for them to go in the academy.

1869
02:24:31,522 --> 02:24:35,825
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we have to repair, clean it, send it back.

1870
02:24:35,885 --> 02:24:38,107
[SPEAKER_00]: And then we got to buy them new gear when they arrive, OK?

1871
02:24:39,469 --> 02:24:43,175
[SPEAKER_00]: We couldn't fund a second set through that because it would have been way too much money.

1872
02:24:43,235 --> 02:24:47,862
[SPEAKER_00]: So I had the discussion with the staff and it is in the CIP, there is a plan.

1873
02:24:48,760 --> 02:24:51,381
[SPEAKER_00]: And it just hasn't been funded yet.

1874
02:24:51,922 --> 02:24:53,062
[SPEAKER_00]: So I know what I need.

1875
02:24:53,162 --> 02:24:54,583
[SPEAKER_00]: I've communicated that to them.

1876
02:24:55,263 --> 02:24:58,325
[SPEAKER_00]: And I just haven't got around to getting the funds yet.

1877
02:24:58,825 --> 02:25:02,206
[SPEAKER_00]: Is that eligible for funding under the OPA money?

1878
02:25:03,127 --> 02:25:04,187
[SPEAKER_00]: I don't know the mechanism.

1879
02:25:04,527 --> 02:25:07,129
[SPEAKER_00]: That's the issue, is where is that money coming from?

1880
02:25:07,169 --> 02:25:09,630
[SPEAKER_00]: Most likely some of it will come from OPA, I would imagine.

1881
02:25:10,428 --> 02:25:12,090
[SPEAKER_00]: And well, we have a free cash of $25 million.

1882
02:25:12,110 --> 02:25:14,211
[SPEAKER_20]: We have a free cash of $25 million.

1883
02:25:14,331 --> 02:25:17,914
[SPEAKER_00]: Like that big purchase, that $400,000 purchase, I was very well aware of that.

1884
02:25:17,934 --> 02:25:19,055
[SPEAKER_00]: I made the staff aware of it.

1885
02:25:19,115 --> 02:25:19,856
[SPEAKER_00]: It is in there.

1886
02:25:20,416 --> 02:25:25,921
[SPEAKER_00]: How they're going to ultimately fund it, that's a higher level decision that I don't have.

1887
02:25:26,221 --> 02:25:27,823
[SPEAKER_20]: Like I say, there's $25 million in free cash.

1888
02:25:28,403 --> 02:25:33,367
[SPEAKER_20]: And there's still OPA funds available that hopefully they're going to put a better use of it than going to.

1889
02:25:33,387 --> 02:25:38,511
[SPEAKER_00]: They just haven't communicated the decision down to me yet where the money's coming from and pulled the trigger on.

1890
02:25:39,272 --> 02:25:40,593
[SPEAKER_00]: when to actually make the purchase.

1891
02:25:40,633 --> 02:25:42,415
[SPEAKER_00]: But some of the gear is correct.

1892
02:25:42,435 --> 02:25:43,536
[SPEAKER_00]: Some of the gear is expired.

1893
02:25:43,876 --> 02:25:45,757
[SPEAKER_00]: There are members that don't have second sets.

1894
02:25:47,239 --> 02:25:47,999
[SPEAKER_20]: And you get 10 guys.

1895
02:25:48,039 --> 02:25:50,201
[SPEAKER_20]: You're going to have 10 guys coming on and have no sets.

1896
02:25:50,601 --> 02:25:52,843
[SPEAKER_20]: We don't have 10 guys.

1897
02:25:52,883 --> 02:25:55,486
[SPEAKER_00]: The plan is 10, but that won't be until the end.

1898
02:25:55,506 --> 02:25:57,327
[SPEAKER_00]: But it's a year away, year and a half away.

1899
02:25:57,347 --> 02:25:59,249
[SPEAKER_00]: So if you hire them today, they're going to hire them today.

1900
02:25:59,309 --> 02:26:01,851
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't know why we're not hiring people.

1901
02:26:05,239 --> 02:26:07,921
[SPEAKER_07]: Also, those new guys, we decided they have one set of gear.

1902
02:26:08,541 --> 02:26:12,724
[SPEAKER_07]: We've had four-line fighters, three-line fighters, they've all been to those fights.

1903
02:26:13,624 --> 02:26:15,065
[SPEAKER_07]: Now their gear has to go and get washed.

1904
02:26:15,245 --> 02:26:16,146
[SPEAKER_07]: What are they wearing?

1905
02:26:17,627 --> 02:26:19,388
[SPEAKER_07]: Someone else's gear that probably doesn't fit them.

1906
02:26:20,108 --> 02:26:21,449
[SPEAKER_07]: So it puts them in danger.

1907
02:26:22,210 --> 02:26:25,532
[SPEAKER_07]: It also puts the public in danger.

1908
02:26:25,592 --> 02:26:28,313
[SPEAKER_20]: And what's the cost of gear per man?

1909
02:26:28,514 --> 02:26:29,374
[SPEAKER_07]: About $5,000, head to toe.

1910
02:26:35,571 --> 02:26:38,092
[SPEAKER_20]: So you need 122, 123 sets, 122 turnout gears?

1911
02:26:38,112 --> 02:26:41,073
[SPEAKER_20]: That's you adding 10 guys that we're not hiring right now.

1912
02:26:41,093 --> 02:26:42,274
[SPEAKER_20]: No, okay.

1913
02:26:42,674 --> 02:26:43,875
[SPEAKER_07]: We only have 110 guys.

1914
02:26:43,975 --> 02:26:44,275
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay, yeah.

1915
02:26:44,335 --> 02:26:45,635
[SPEAKER_07]: So the issue with the gear is,

1916
02:26:54,183 --> 02:26:55,683
[SPEAKER_00]: it is a finite amount of life.

1917
02:26:55,763 --> 02:26:58,264
[SPEAKER_00]: Under NFPA, it's 10 years and done.

1918
02:26:58,944 --> 02:27:01,025
[SPEAKER_00]: Once it hits 10, it's no longer deployable.

1919
02:27:01,645 --> 02:27:03,005
[SPEAKER_00]: So we know those dates.

1920
02:27:03,585 --> 02:27:04,866
[SPEAKER_00]: We know when they're going to expire.

1921
02:27:05,486 --> 02:27:09,327
[SPEAKER_00]: But like everything since the pandemic, there's a lead time to get it, too.

1922
02:27:09,447 --> 02:27:17,749
[SPEAKER_00]: So my concern is that we need to get it funded sooner rather than later, only because some of it has expired.

1923
02:27:17,809 --> 02:27:22,650
[SPEAKER_00]: And it takes months to get it made, get fitted, get it made, and get it delivered.

1924
02:27:24,778 --> 02:27:30,179
[SPEAKER_20]: Okay, and my last question is, this council received a letter a few days ago.

1925
02:27:31,920 --> 02:27:36,881
[SPEAKER_20]: Does anyone, would you like to discuss that letter and its contents?

1926
02:27:38,301 --> 02:27:38,681
[SPEAKER_20]: If you could.

1927
02:27:38,761 --> 02:27:41,862
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't have a letter in front of me.

1928
02:27:41,902 --> 02:27:43,482
[SPEAKER_20]: I think you know what it says.

1929
02:27:43,682 --> 02:27:45,383
[SPEAKER_20]: It says what it says.

1930
02:27:46,463 --> 02:27:48,404
[SPEAKER_20]: Nothing has changed from when we got the letter?

1931
02:27:49,224 --> 02:27:49,664
[SPEAKER_20]: No.

1932
02:27:49,704 --> 02:27:51,344
[SPEAKER_20]: Contract negotiations have gone nowhere?

1933
02:27:51,364 --> 02:27:51,984
[SPEAKER_20]: No.

1934
02:27:52,945 --> 02:27:54,005
[SPEAKER_20]: And there's still,

1935
02:27:54,913 --> 02:27:57,936
[SPEAKER_15]: I think even though it feels like it was days ago, I think it was just yesterday we got it.

1936
02:27:58,036 --> 02:27:59,537
[SPEAKER_20]: Yesterday, okay.

1937
02:27:59,697 --> 02:28:04,401
[SPEAKER_20]: And there's still fire personnel that don't have insurance?

1938
02:28:05,157 --> 02:28:07,918
[SPEAKER_20]: They don't have insurance to this city, right?

1939
02:28:08,058 --> 02:28:10,979
[SPEAKER_07]: So they have VA insurance, so they can't go to their own doctor.

1940
02:28:10,999 --> 02:28:13,539
[SPEAKER_07]: They have to go to some guy at the VA that they don't know.

1941
02:28:13,639 --> 02:28:22,522
[SPEAKER_20]: I thought when we hired a new personnel person, the mayor got up here last week and said the insurance issues were all squared away.

1942
02:28:23,502 --> 02:28:25,002
[SPEAKER_20]: Contract negotiations were moving on.

1943
02:28:25,522 --> 02:28:28,923
[SPEAKER_20]: Again, they do not have insurance provided by this city.

1944
02:28:29,063 --> 02:28:31,184
[SPEAKER_20]: How many people don't have insurance?

1945
02:28:33,589 --> 02:28:34,930
[SPEAKER_20]: It's four.

1946
02:28:35,050 --> 02:28:37,392
[SPEAKER_20]: And how long have they been without insurance?

1947
02:28:40,235 --> 02:28:41,055
[SPEAKER_20]: Since they were hired.

1948
02:28:41,516 --> 02:28:44,218
[SPEAKER_20]: February of last year.

1949
02:28:44,679 --> 02:28:46,160
[SPEAKER_20]: Last year, so they still don't have insurance?

1950
02:28:46,821 --> 02:28:47,181
[SPEAKER_20]: Yep.

1951
02:28:48,362 --> 02:28:49,623
[SPEAKER_20]: I still don't have insurance.

1952
02:28:49,863 --> 02:28:50,284
[SPEAKER_20]: I don't either.

1953
02:28:51,227 --> 02:28:55,610
[SPEAKER_04]: They were told that they would have to wait until the open enrollment, which that period begins July 1st.

1954
02:28:56,311 --> 02:29:04,937
[SPEAKER_07]: They were also told that they might not possibly be eligible for it because they're not a new employee anymore, and they're not switching from any other insurance.

1955
02:29:05,757 --> 02:29:07,959
[SPEAKER_07]: So there's no life-changing event to jump on.

1956
02:29:08,199 --> 02:29:09,400
[SPEAKER_07]: So we don't know if they're getting it.

1957
02:29:09,460 --> 02:29:12,582
[SPEAKER_07]: We hope they're getting it.

1958
02:29:12,622 --> 02:29:16,745
[SPEAKER_20]: So I understand you need the life event to get on quicker.

1959
02:29:16,765 --> 02:29:18,646
[SPEAKER_20]: So these people were hired.

1960
02:29:19,602 --> 02:29:25,707
[SPEAKER_20]: And when you get hired in most jobs, there might be maybe a small waiting period to get the insurance.

1961
02:29:26,968 --> 02:29:27,588
[SPEAKER_20]: 60 days.

1962
02:29:28,029 --> 02:29:28,249
[SPEAKER_20]: 60 days.

1963
02:29:28,729 --> 02:29:32,492
[SPEAKER_20]: So these people have been on for more than 60 days, and they don't have insurance.

1964
02:29:32,512 --> 02:29:33,013
[SPEAKER_20]: Why is that?

1965
02:29:34,174 --> 02:29:35,295
[SPEAKER_20]: That's a question for the city.

1966
02:29:35,855 --> 02:29:36,436
[SPEAKER_20]: I can't help you.

1967
02:29:37,116 --> 02:29:38,737
[SPEAKER_20]: Madam Chief of Staff, could you answer that?

1968
