[SPEAKER_18]: And so Alicia provides wide scope and supportive services to residents.

2334
02:59:54,699 --> 02:59:55,560
[SPEAKER_18]: I think you all know that.

2335
02:59:56,803 --> 03:00:00,286
[SPEAKER_18]: She's working very hard with other city departments.

2336
03:00:00,746 --> 03:00:04,630
[SPEAKER_18]: She's helped with veterans, building departments, certainly the health department.

2337
03:00:04,670 --> 03:00:08,853
[SPEAKER_18]: She comes out on some of the more difficult cases that we went into with housing issues.

2338
03:00:11,035 --> 03:00:14,058
[SPEAKER_18]: She's really helped develop solutions for community issues.

2339
03:00:14,258 --> 03:00:15,259
[SPEAKER_18]: She works with the residents.

2340
03:00:15,279 --> 03:00:16,080
[SPEAKER_18]: She works with the agency.

2341
03:00:16,140 --> 03:00:21,024
[SPEAKER_18]: She does a lot of navigation work, trying to help people out with food, utilities, housing.

2342
03:00:21,064 --> 03:00:24,467
[SPEAKER_18]: We've had a couple of recent nice wins for people that we're very excited about.

2343
03:00:24,877 --> 03:00:33,742
[SPEAKER_18]: were able to alleviate a utility bill and get a woman's gas, $6,000 gas bill back, get her gas back on after a really long time.

2344
03:00:35,603 --> 03:00:47,129
[SPEAKER_18]: Housing, employment, other service navigation and case management for those with behavioral health needs, creating programming to ease access to local services.

2345
03:00:47,730 --> 03:00:51,812
[SPEAKER_18]: She leads a substance use recovery harm reduction program.

2346
03:00:53,105 --> 03:01:08,411
[SPEAKER_18]: she actually also just did a return to work job program for those in recovery as well and a lot of other community interventions the health equity team which again i think you are well aware of we have um

2347
03:01:09,758 --> 03:01:13,922
[SPEAKER_18]: The coordinator, who Sophie was here earlier, she's the one who's managing the liaisons.

2348
03:01:14,222 --> 03:01:17,845
[SPEAKER_18]: She is managing the city food and housing equity efforts.

2349
03:01:17,945 --> 03:01:20,027
[SPEAKER_18]: She's collaborating with the public health nurse now.

2350
03:01:20,427 --> 03:01:30,596
[SPEAKER_18]: We have a new public health nurse who just started this week, so we're very excited about that, to identify and implement strategies to address the chronic disease disparities and some health promotion ideas.

2351
03:01:31,917 --> 03:01:36,821
[SPEAKER_18]: She's also been securing some amazing programming, new programming around health equity.

2352
03:01:38,168 --> 03:01:43,930
[SPEAKER_18]: including establishing citizenship classes starting in September at the library.

2353
03:01:44,911 --> 03:01:50,413
[SPEAKER_18]: She has implemented a certification program for mass health application counselors.

2354
03:01:50,513 --> 03:01:57,316
[SPEAKER_18]: So our social worker and our liaisons are all going to be available to help people with their mass health applications.

2355
03:01:57,756 --> 03:01:59,937
[SPEAKER_18]: That's currently in progress or under training now.

2356
03:01:59,997 --> 03:02:03,979
[SPEAKER_18]: She secured a DTA kiosk, which is going to be at the library as well.

2357
03:02:05,362 --> 03:02:16,128
[SPEAKER_18]: She is trained in youth mental health first aid instruction, and she'll be offering those programs throughout the summer with the support of the language access team so they'll be in different languages as needed.

2358
03:02:16,869 --> 03:02:23,853
[SPEAKER_18]: And she is managing the EMR and the Food Justice Council work going on in collaboration with the YMCA.

2359
03:02:25,354 --> 03:02:27,755
[SPEAKER_18]: Our five community liaisons have been doing amazing work.

2360
03:02:27,795 --> 03:02:32,858
[SPEAKER_18]: We have Arabic, Brazilian, Portuguese, BIPOC, which is English speaking, Haitian Creole,

2361
03:02:33,390 --> 03:02:41,873
[SPEAKER_18]: and Spanish speaking liaisons working with our city cultural events.

2362
03:02:41,933 --> 03:02:48,375
[SPEAKER_18]: We've had two really great cultural events recently, the Arabic and the Haitian Heritage Days.

2363
03:02:49,816 --> 03:02:58,739
[SPEAKER_18]: Again, we already have one of our counselors, our liaisons certified in being able to help folks with mass health applications.

2364
03:02:58,779 --> 03:03:02,480
[SPEAKER_18]: So already 20 folks have been helped with that since March.

2365
03:03:04,012 --> 03:03:10,557
[SPEAKER_18]: Um, we have three or four of them certified as community health workers and two others working towards that.

2366
03:03:11,717 --> 03:03:15,300
[SPEAKER_18]: Uh, we've done a lot of outreach to culturally specific owned businesses.

2367
03:03:16,181 --> 03:03:25,447
[SPEAKER_18]: Um, and businesses have been reaching out to liaisons regarding issues around licensing or complaints or any other city related issues.

2368
03:03:26,260 --> 03:03:30,001
[SPEAKER_18]: We had a wonderful meeting last week with Congresswoman Clark's office.

2369
03:03:30,441 --> 03:03:41,984
[SPEAKER_18]: They were very interested in the work the liaisons are doing, particularly great discussion on immigration concerns and what the Congresswoman's office can do and what we can do to help them.

2370
03:03:43,544 --> 03:03:52,806
[SPEAKER_18]: At the end of the conversation, we did tell them that the liaisons' positions are all APA funded, and we know that that will be coming to an end on December of 24.

2371
03:03:52,926 --> 03:03:55,967
[SPEAKER_18]: And the response we got was

2372
03:03:56,758 --> 03:04:00,140
[SPEAKER_18]: send us a write up and we're going to see what we can do to help support them going forward.

2373
03:04:00,201 --> 03:04:08,046
[SPEAKER_18]: So a lot of great work is being recognized and I'm hopeful that we will be able to continue the work going forward.

2374
03:04:10,688 --> 03:04:20,315
[SPEAKER_18]: And then the last couple slides, the inspectional services side of the house is the next slide and the public health nursing.

2375
03:04:20,335 --> 03:04:23,297
[SPEAKER_18]: Again, we have a brand new public health nurse who's just started and

2376
03:04:23,813 --> 03:04:25,953
[SPEAKER_18]: So I think she's going to be wonderful.

2377
03:04:26,594 --> 03:04:31,715
[SPEAKER_18]: But this past year, with our previous public health nurse, we did administer over 1,700 vaccines.

2378
03:04:32,515 --> 03:04:42,597
[SPEAKER_18]: She did have weekly blood pressure screenings at both the Council on Aging and West Memphis Community Center, and the Farmers Market, and several other places throughout the community that she would visit.

2379
03:04:44,057 --> 03:04:51,819
[SPEAKER_18]: Responsible for all the infectious disease follow-up and contact tracing, you know, TB, COVID this year among MPOCs.

2380
03:04:53,401 --> 03:04:55,242
[SPEAKER_18]: as well as others who've got illnesses.

2381
03:04:56,783 --> 03:05:01,685
[SPEAKER_18]: The department put out over a thousand permits, those are permanent permits.

2382
03:05:02,105 --> 03:05:06,306
[SPEAKER_18]: There's also another couple of hundred temporary permits that the department put out this year.

2383
03:05:06,326 --> 03:05:17,751
[SPEAKER_18]: 25 pool inspections in addition to all the other inspections, because the 520 complaints that you see we received, those pretty much all generate an inspection or two as well.

2384
03:05:19,092 --> 03:05:19,712
[SPEAKER_18]: And in addition,

2385
03:05:20,325 --> 03:05:25,106
[SPEAKER_18]: We do 537 routine food inspections are required.

2386
03:05:26,047 --> 03:05:32,248
[SPEAKER_18]: And that doesn't include having to go back for re-inspections and temporary food inspections and farmer's markets and other events.

2387
03:05:32,328 --> 03:05:39,470
[SPEAKER_18]: So that's to make sure that there is the inspectional side of life that's extremely important and happens every day.

2388
03:05:39,630 --> 03:05:41,311
[SPEAKER_18]: And the inspectors are incredibly busy.

2389
03:05:41,811 --> 03:05:43,851
[SPEAKER_18]: I have a new inspector starting on Monday.

2390
03:05:43,871 --> 03:05:45,152
[SPEAKER_18]: So we're very happy about that.

2391
03:05:45,172 --> 03:05:46,752
[SPEAKER_18]: So we'll have a full staff back up again.

2392
03:05:47,791 --> 03:05:49,792
[SPEAKER_18]: And then the goals, I'll let you read them.

2393
03:05:49,832 --> 03:05:53,635
[SPEAKER_18]: I don't have to read them to you, but yeah.

2394
03:05:54,815 --> 03:05:55,255
[SPEAKER_18]: That's it.

2395
03:05:55,276 --> 03:05:56,716
[SPEAKER_18]: Any other questions?

2396
03:05:57,877 --> 03:05:58,177
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

2397
03:05:58,197 --> 03:05:59,198
[SPEAKER_15]: We'll go to Councilor Sang.

2398
03:05:59,877 --> 03:06:00,798
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you, President Morrell.

2399
03:06:01,098 --> 03:06:09,462
[SPEAKER_27]: I'm glad to hear that the social workers, you're finding a way to continue that pastor, which has done an amazing job.

2400
03:06:09,562 --> 03:06:14,245
[SPEAKER_27]: So I wanted to convey that I'm very happy about that.

2401
03:06:14,665 --> 03:06:26,692
[SPEAKER_27]: I think your department in general has done a great job, especially through a few very difficult years, and especially as our city, I think we've reset our expectations and our goals with,

2402
03:06:27,372 --> 03:06:29,714
[SPEAKER_27]: how we approach public health and what lenses we use.

2403
03:06:29,834 --> 03:06:34,398
[SPEAKER_27]: And so I think I have to commend you guys for that work.

2404
03:06:35,119 --> 03:06:40,964
[SPEAKER_27]: A lot of folks are rightfully very proud of our community liaisons program.

2405
03:06:41,224 --> 03:06:50,212
[SPEAKER_27]: A lot of different municipalities look at Medford and that program as a startling example, as a shining model.

2406
03:06:50,912 --> 03:06:53,494
[SPEAKER_27]: And I think there's some concern that

2407
03:06:54,455 --> 03:06:58,456
[SPEAKER_27]: we might not have the money for that next year when we face a big fiscal cliff.

2408
03:07:00,417 --> 03:07:05,179
[SPEAKER_27]: Have you received any assurances or are there any ways that we're going to keep that funded?

2409
03:07:05,479 --> 03:07:08,200
[SPEAKER_18]: Yeah, so actually the mayor has been

2410
03:07:08,848 --> 03:07:09,849
[SPEAKER_18]: Very committed to that.

2411
03:07:10,369 --> 03:07:13,592
[SPEAKER_18]: She does want to start actually doing that work this summer.

2412
03:07:14,213 --> 03:07:17,475
[SPEAKER_18]: We are to sit down and start looking at what the needs are in the budget.

2413
03:07:18,316 --> 03:07:28,344
[SPEAKER_18]: We're definitely, in the meantime, going to be not shy about reaching out to Congresswoman Clark's office or other funders because it is, I think, people are recognizing the value.

2414
03:07:29,767 --> 03:07:41,331
[SPEAKER_18]: I don't think finding additional funding is gonna be as difficult, but I do, the ultimate goal is to get it into the general fund, into the budget, operating budget, so that it's sustainable and going forward.

2415
03:07:41,812 --> 03:07:47,314
[SPEAKER_27]: Great, yeah, I mean, that's something that I think is something that should be in the general fund.

2416
03:07:47,354 --> 03:07:57,698
[SPEAKER_27]: I know Councilor Collins and I have been calling for that for a while, but we also understand that the budget is complex and things aren't always very flexible.

2417
03:07:59,189 --> 03:08:07,415
[SPEAKER_27]: I think the next question I wanted to ask, I mean, I think everyone's asked, you're anticipating questions already, but about rats and rodents.

2418
03:08:07,856 --> 03:08:13,780
[SPEAKER_27]: What is, I asked you this question last year, but I think for the sake of residents, it's good to re-ask it.

2419
03:08:14,160 --> 03:08:17,963
[SPEAKER_27]: What is our city currently doing on rats, on rodents?

2420
03:08:18,343 --> 03:08:20,145
[SPEAKER_27]: What is our plan going forward?

2421
03:08:20,705 --> 03:08:25,169
[SPEAKER_27]: And I think a new question would be, what are some other cities doing that we're not doing?

2422
03:08:25,330 --> 03:08:32,436
[SPEAKER_27]: So for example, I know Somerville's doing a bunch of things and different neighboring municipalities are trying out a bunch of techniques.

2423
03:08:32,977 --> 03:08:37,221
[SPEAKER_27]: Is there anything that you think is working and that we should maybe look at investing in?

2424
03:08:38,531 --> 03:08:40,772
[SPEAKER_18]: So we're trying to do a lot of education.

2425
03:08:40,912 --> 03:08:46,594
[SPEAKER_18]: Obviously, it was great that we passed the ordinance last year, the pest control ordinance.

2426
03:08:47,095 --> 03:08:48,515
[SPEAKER_18]: And we're following up on that.

2427
03:08:49,475 --> 03:08:56,498
[SPEAKER_18]: That is requiring food establishments, dumpsters, and haulers.

2428
03:08:56,818 --> 03:08:59,139
[SPEAKER_18]: People have to have an integrated pest management.

2429
03:08:59,279 --> 03:09:02,441
[SPEAKER_18]: And when we say that, some of these folks are like, they don't even know what it is.

2430
03:09:02,481 --> 03:09:05,482
[SPEAKER_18]: Some of the pest control companies themselves, they don't know what it is.

2431
03:09:05,856 --> 03:09:06,296
[SPEAKER_18]: what that is.

2432
03:09:06,676 --> 03:09:14,398
[SPEAKER_18]: So we've had to do a lot of education around that, but I think just making sure that they have those in place, um, is, is, is helping.

2433
03:09:14,458 --> 03:09:16,118
[SPEAKER_18]: I think we've, we've seen a difference.

2434
03:09:16,478 --> 03:09:19,559
[SPEAKER_18]: Um, we do have a contract with Yankee pest control.

2435
03:09:20,499 --> 03:09:25,760
[SPEAKER_18]: Um, we don't want to be, uh, just spreading rodenticide, uh, throughout the city.

2436
03:09:25,840 --> 03:09:29,921
[SPEAKER_18]: So what we are doing is again, besides by inspectors going out

2437
03:09:30,277 --> 03:09:36,186
[SPEAKER_18]: The pest control inspectors are going out as well, surveying the homes or the sites.

2438
03:09:36,847 --> 03:09:44,312
[SPEAKER_18]: and talking to folks about how they could better protect themselves from road infestations.

2439
03:09:44,993 --> 03:09:56,701
[SPEAKER_18]: But again, if they do see burrows on these properties, with our contract with Yankee, they will treat the burrows for free for the residents, depending on where the burrows are.

2440
03:09:56,741 --> 03:10:01,805
[SPEAKER_18]: Sometimes if they're too close to the home, because what they're doing is putting carbon monoxide dioxide.

2441
03:10:02,511 --> 03:10:03,672
[SPEAKER_18]: into the into the borough.

2442
03:10:03,692 --> 03:10:06,353
[SPEAKER_18]: So depending on how close they are foundations or whatever.

2443
03:10:06,993 --> 03:10:14,256
[SPEAKER_18]: But if they're under sheds, they're in their yards, under their fences, they will treat the boroughs twice, they'll go back a second time.

2444
03:10:14,296 --> 03:10:19,118
[SPEAKER_18]: And if it doesn't look like it worked the first time, we'll treat them again the second time again for free for the for the residents.

2445
03:10:19,559 --> 03:10:20,959
[SPEAKER_18]: So we're hoping to continue that.

2446
03:10:23,680 --> 03:10:26,982
[SPEAKER_18]: What what we've been looking at and what some of the other communities

2447
03:10:27,933 --> 03:10:29,894
[SPEAKER_18]: Yeah, mixed reviews on all of these things, right?

2448
03:10:29,974 --> 03:10:36,216
[SPEAKER_18]: But the shock boxes, Maldon, I've been talking with Maldon.

2449
03:10:36,276 --> 03:10:39,138
[SPEAKER_18]: They just implemented a shock box thing.

2450
03:10:39,278 --> 03:10:44,480
[SPEAKER_18]: It's a couple thousand dollars to $3,000, depending on the number of boxes you get.

2451
03:10:45,120 --> 03:10:48,201
[SPEAKER_18]: It's like $100 a box per month.

2452
03:10:48,801 --> 03:10:52,503
[SPEAKER_18]: They usually do 30, so it's like $3,000 a month that they're spending.

2453
03:10:55,695 --> 03:10:57,836
[SPEAKER_18]: They seem to be having some success.

2454
03:10:58,637 --> 03:11:00,978
[SPEAKER_18]: The thing with those boxes is they actually track.

2455
03:11:01,258 --> 03:11:05,581
[SPEAKER_18]: They have GIS on them, and they track when there's a hit.

2456
03:11:06,202 --> 03:11:09,343
[SPEAKER_18]: And they'll go out and empty the box and restock the box.

2457
03:11:09,383 --> 03:11:16,468
[SPEAKER_18]: But it's basically shocking the heart and stopping the heart of the rat.

2458
03:11:18,689 --> 03:11:20,570
[SPEAKER_18]: So we're looking at that as an option as well.

2459
03:11:22,206 --> 03:11:31,154
[SPEAKER_18]: But again, the rodenticide thing, especially like we had a lot of people calling about making sure that we weren't doing that, especially when we had a couple of deaths recently of the eagles.

2460
03:11:31,234 --> 03:11:36,278
[SPEAKER_18]: And so we want to be very, very conscious of that going forward.

2461
03:11:36,318 --> 03:11:41,183
[SPEAKER_18]: So it's just a lot of education, trying to get people to

2462
03:11:41,858 --> 03:11:57,269
[SPEAKER_18]: stop feeding the birds, and picking up their trash, and making sure that their barrels are maintained properly, and changing the barrels if they have holes in them, and really trying to get people to cooperate and take ownership as well.

2463
03:11:57,289 --> 03:12:01,111
[SPEAKER_18]: You want to be proactive, right, too.

2464
03:12:01,491 --> 03:12:03,073
[SPEAKER_18]: So that's really a lot of education.

2465
03:12:07,549 --> 03:12:16,575
[SPEAKER_18]: posted, I believe, that educational session we had with the owner of Yankee Pest Control a year or so ago.

2466
03:12:17,075 --> 03:12:20,637
[SPEAKER_18]: So that's back out there on the web, on our webpage.

2467
03:12:21,618 --> 03:12:25,340
[SPEAKER_18]: And we started an Instagram page this year too.

2468
03:12:25,420 --> 03:12:28,002
[SPEAKER_18]: So I didn't, my inspector did.

2469
03:12:28,062 --> 03:12:32,725
[SPEAKER_18]: But we do a lot of education through that as well, really trying to push the education.

2470
03:12:45,092 --> 03:12:46,934
[SPEAKER_27]: seek additional grants or additional funding.

2471
03:12:46,974 --> 03:12:53,180
[SPEAKER_18]: We have APA funding throughout the year to help us, would get us through with that.

2472
03:12:54,321 --> 03:12:57,463
[SPEAKER_18]: But we are really, see, I shouldn't say this.

2473
03:12:58,164 --> 03:13:02,388
[SPEAKER_18]: Complaints seem to have quieted down a little bit.

2474
03:13:02,888 --> 03:13:04,490
[SPEAKER_18]: So I think we're going in the right direction.

2475
03:13:05,140 --> 03:13:10,564
[SPEAKER_18]: Again, it's the time of the year that people are now going to be out later on their decks or whatever at night.

2476
03:13:11,464 --> 03:13:14,246
[SPEAKER_18]: So the complaints may go back up again.

2477
03:13:16,208 --> 03:13:16,488
[SPEAKER_03]: Thanks.

2478
03:13:21,191 --> 03:13:22,031
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you, Madam President.

2479
03:13:22,052 --> 03:13:22,952
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you, Director O'Connor.

2480
03:13:22,972 --> 03:13:24,013
[SPEAKER_03]: I just have two questions.

2481
03:13:24,213 --> 03:13:29,256
[SPEAKER_03]: One, I know that animal control is always pretty tight every year.

2482
03:13:29,276 --> 03:13:32,839
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not seeing any increases in this year's budget.

2483
03:13:33,399 --> 03:13:34,380
[SPEAKER_03]: Is there any plan in the

2484
03:13:35,170 --> 03:13:39,312
[SPEAKER_03]: next couple years to try to get some more resources down to help out with animal control?

2485
03:13:40,532 --> 03:13:40,932
[SPEAKER_18]: Yeah.

2486
03:13:41,852 --> 03:13:44,613
[SPEAKER_18]: A couple of sides to that, yeah.

2487
03:13:44,994 --> 03:14:02,440
[SPEAKER_18]: So the animal... I mean, it's really hard because animal control, it's not 24-7, and it's difficult when complaints come in on weekends and evenings.

2488
03:14:03,758 --> 03:14:11,263
[SPEAKER_18]: So, yeah, we have been looking at that, and I've had discussions with the police because, you know, they oftentimes end up dealing with some of these situations.

2489
03:14:12,183 --> 03:14:15,165
[SPEAKER_18]: So, we're talking and we're trying to brainstorm solutions.

2490
03:14:15,245 --> 03:14:24,070
[SPEAKER_18]: Again, like, those regional grants that I've talked about, we've even had discussions within those, like, can we get a regional person who would just be, like, an on-call?

2491
03:14:24,530 --> 03:14:25,951
[SPEAKER_18]: You know, will the grant cover that?

2492
03:14:25,991 --> 03:14:28,012
[SPEAKER_18]: So, we're seeking options that way.

2493
03:14:31,968 --> 03:14:40,791
[SPEAKER_18]: The health canine contracted services, that's really, that's a little deceiving because $26,000 of that 35 immediately goes to mosquito control.

2494
03:14:41,991 --> 03:14:48,633
[SPEAKER_18]: And the rest is left for basically, you know, kennel boarding and that type of thing when that happens.

2495
03:14:49,093 --> 03:14:59,857
[SPEAKER_18]: We lost our facility and land shut down abruptly that we would be boarding our animals, our dogs at if Patrick found a lost dog or a dangerous dog.

2496
03:15:01,219 --> 03:15:09,203
[SPEAKER_18]: So we've been scrambling, honestly, to try, and everyone's scrambling, because these facilities have just had few in between and had to come by.

2497
03:15:10,364 --> 03:15:15,087
[SPEAKER_18]: And MSPCA will not take animals anymore from cities.

2498
03:15:15,247 --> 03:15:18,809
[SPEAKER_18]: So if the police went there, they would take it from a resident.

2499
03:15:20,069 --> 03:15:22,891
[SPEAKER_18]: But they really are putting it back on the cities to do that.

2500
03:15:23,391 --> 03:15:30,195
[SPEAKER_18]: I mean, I even had a quick discussion, I hope you remember this, with Chief Friedman around the new

2501
03:15:31,217 --> 03:15:45,982
[SPEAKER_18]: the new fire station and potentially like finding a spot where we could just have the area that would be a place where we could have the dogs stay overnight until the owner is found or until we found another home for them.

2502
03:15:46,062 --> 03:15:55,105
[SPEAKER_18]: So that's, you know, we're going to pursue that as well because that would be a huge lift off of Pat's shoulders too if we had that.

2503
03:15:56,512 --> 03:16:07,361
