2859
03:46:07,012 --> 03:46:10,434
[SPEAKER_10]: I can say for both July and August, both months was about 7,000.

2860
03:46:10,494 --> 03:46:12,955
[SPEAKER_10]: July was 7,152 at a deficit, and August was 7,441 at a deficit.

2861
03:46:12,975 --> 03:46:14,476
[SPEAKER_10]: So we lost money on the rink over the summer?

2862
03:46:14,496 --> 03:46:15,676
[SPEAKER_10]: We did lose some money, yes.

2863
03:46:24,520 --> 03:46:26,065
[SPEAKER_20]: So why are we going to open it again this summer?

2864
03:46:26,246 --> 03:46:27,108
[SPEAKER_20]: Well, we're not opening.

2865
03:46:27,128 --> 03:46:28,031
[SPEAKER_20]: We're not going to open this summer.

2866
03:46:28,412 --> 03:46:28,593
[SPEAKER_10]: No.

2867
03:46:29,355 --> 03:46:29,455
OK.

2868
03:46:29,837 --> 03:46:29,977
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah.

2869
03:46:30,473 --> 03:46:32,374
[SPEAKER_10]: We're going to be, so it's closed right now.

2870
03:46:32,394 --> 03:46:35,516
[SPEAKER_10]: We're planning on opening on Labor Day, like we usually have.

2871
03:46:37,277 --> 03:46:39,678
[SPEAKER_10]: The cooling tower, especially, it just doesn't make sense.

2872
03:46:40,318 --> 03:46:49,023
[SPEAKER_10]: One of the biggest expenses this year was working with American Refrigeration, the company that services the compressors.

2873
03:46:49,523 --> 03:46:52,324
[SPEAKER_10]: As we said, that cooling tower needed to be replaced.

2874
03:46:52,825 --> 03:46:57,187
[SPEAKER_10]: With the cooling tower not working properly, the compressors are shutting off, and that costs

2875
03:46:57,770 --> 03:47:04,093
[SPEAKER_10]: near the end of April, sorry, the beginning of April, we had American refrigeration coming in almost every single day.

2876
03:47:04,554 --> 03:47:09,056
[SPEAKER_10]: And that's, again, one of the biggest push of why we were asking DCR for that replacement.

2877
03:47:09,757 --> 03:47:19,202
[SPEAKER_10]: And there is an announcement that for the state, they are giving us another $100,000 in the state budget to be dedicated for Lacanee Rink.

2878
03:47:19,802 --> 03:47:21,883
[SPEAKER_20]: Is it worth it to keep the rink open that extra month?

2879
03:47:22,884 --> 03:47:25,065
[SPEAKER_20]: Or is it better to shut it down at the end of March?

2880
03:47:26,790 --> 03:47:33,855
[SPEAKER_10]: So looking at the numbers, what we're looking at is at the end of April, I'd like to keep it open during April school vacation week.

2881
03:47:34,295 --> 03:47:38,618
[SPEAKER_10]: And so then I also talked with the contractor trying to keep it open at least for that school year.

2882
03:47:39,579 --> 03:47:43,942
[SPEAKER_10]: Once April vacation ends is when we would like to close it.

2883
03:47:44,662 --> 03:47:47,945
[SPEAKER_10]: As you know, with hockey, May, it's a dead season.

2884
03:47:47,965 --> 03:47:48,965
[SPEAKER_10]: There's not a lot of people.

2885
03:47:48,985 --> 03:47:51,467
[SPEAKER_10]: So overall, did the rink turn a profit?

2886
03:47:52,227 --> 03:47:55,630
[SPEAKER_10]: No, because of all the repairs that we had to spend on it.

2887
03:47:57,978 --> 03:48:00,319
[SPEAKER_20]: Um, so it was a stupid question.

2888
03:48:00,579 --> 03:48:16,583
[SPEAKER_10]: But can I also add, I do think, though, even if there is a loss in July and August, or if we even open up for August a little bit earlier, I do think once these repairs are done, we have the ability to make up that loss in the winter months.

2889
03:48:17,475 --> 03:48:23,076
[SPEAKER_20]: make sure that ring should be making money there because ice time is valuable throughout the state.

2890
03:48:23,397 --> 03:48:24,477
[SPEAKER_20]: There's hockey leagues everywhere.

2891
03:48:24,497 --> 03:48:30,698
[SPEAKER_20]: I think we should be a little more proactive and looking for more people to come in there and rent those hours all the time.

2892
03:48:30,718 --> 03:48:37,660
[SPEAKER_20]: Like I say, I was involved with that ring for many years and it should be working a lot more than it's working now.

2893
03:48:40,081 --> 03:48:40,441
[SPEAKER_20]: I know it's a,

2894
03:48:40,860 --> 03:48:42,261
[SPEAKER_20]: You know, you might think it's a crazy question.

2895
03:48:42,341 --> 03:48:44,323
[SPEAKER_20]: I'm sure I'm getting bombarded with all the time.

2896
03:48:44,343 --> 03:48:49,068
[SPEAKER_20]: What are we doing with the pickleball craze that's sweeping the city?

2897
03:48:49,949 --> 03:48:54,833
[SPEAKER_10]: I mean, everybody's, everybody's wants- And it's not just an issue in MedFed.

2898
03:48:54,893 --> 03:48:56,174
[SPEAKER_10]: I know it's an issue everywhere.

2899
03:48:56,214 --> 03:48:57,335
[SPEAKER_10]: They want to take over the world now.

2900
03:48:57,355 --> 03:48:58,837
[SPEAKER_10]: It's one of the fastest growing sports.

2901
03:48:59,217 --> 03:49:02,941
[SPEAKER_10]: I know you've had Tom and Peter up here saying that as well.

2902
03:49:03,627 --> 03:49:04,368
[SPEAKER_10]: It really is.

2903
03:49:05,028 --> 03:49:07,710
[SPEAKER_10]: So, every city in town is trying to match up with that.

2904
03:49:08,150 --> 03:49:15,155
[SPEAKER_10]: What I will say with method though, you know, talking with other recreation departments we do belong to Massachusetts Recreation Parks Association.

2905
03:49:15,615 --> 03:49:19,157
[SPEAKER_10]: This is a hot topic in the industry and it's something that we discuss all the time.

2906
03:49:21,048 --> 03:49:24,589
[SPEAKER_10]: Method does offer a lot of pickleball, a lot.

2907
03:49:25,229 --> 03:49:35,951
[SPEAKER_10]: And if you look at the comparison to the other cities and towns, we have people coming outside of other cities and towns coming to Method because- And that's an issue, I'm glad we started charging money now for these people.

2908
03:49:36,051 --> 03:49:37,371
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, yeah.

2909
03:49:37,451 --> 03:49:42,152
[SPEAKER_10]: So we do have Duggar Park, which is the main attraction, of course, that's where we get a lot of people coming in.

2910
03:49:42,292 --> 03:49:44,472
[SPEAKER_10]: We have five wide pickleball courts.

2911
03:49:45,432 --> 03:49:49,513
[SPEAKER_10]: We also have Hickey Park that is under construction right now, but once that's done,

2912
03:49:50,000 --> 03:49:52,121
[SPEAKER_10]: There's gonna be another two line pickleball courts.

2913
03:49:52,641 --> 03:49:56,803
[SPEAKER_10]: You have the recreation center that has two lined pickleball courts as well.

2914
03:49:56,823 --> 03:50:01,585
[SPEAKER_10]: There is not a lot of indoor gyms that have line pickleball courts and we have that as well.

2915
03:50:02,846 --> 03:50:05,287
[SPEAKER_10]: But we also what is exciting is car park.

2916
03:50:05,307 --> 03:50:10,769
[SPEAKER_10]: When car park goes under renovations, there's gonna be four dedicated pickleball courts.

2917
03:50:11,469 --> 03:50:13,510
[SPEAKER_10]: So there is a large demand.

2918
03:50:13,630 --> 03:50:15,831
[SPEAKER_10]: I think the city recognizes that there's a large demand.

2919
03:50:15,871 --> 03:50:17,412
[SPEAKER_10]: That's why you see the projects.

2920
03:50:17,955 --> 03:50:21,427
[SPEAKER_10]: Every time we're doing a tennis court over, we're adding the pickleball lines at it.

2921
03:50:22,008 --> 03:50:26,630
[SPEAKER_10]: why the next time we are doing a park renovation, we're trying to add those pickleball courts.

2922
03:50:26,970 --> 03:50:31,092
[SPEAKER_20]: Is there any consideration to bringing it into maybe at the high school?

2923
03:50:32,072 --> 03:50:40,296
[SPEAKER_20]: And that gym that went as, I know they have courts that roll out, so you don't even have to mark them, but I've seen them, they kind of roll out and you roll them back up.

2924
03:50:40,836 --> 03:50:45,918
[SPEAKER_20]: Is there any consideration of using, because I know other cities do it in their gymnasiums.

2925
03:50:46,698 --> 03:50:50,700
[SPEAKER_20]: They have a certain day where they charge by the hour, they rent them out to these groups.

2926
03:50:51,320 --> 03:50:52,660
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, we've seen that before too.

2927
03:50:52,700 --> 03:50:56,021
[SPEAKER_10]: You can even rent a car for like $20 an hour, things like that.

2928
03:50:56,261 --> 03:51:02,963
[SPEAKER_10]: And that's something I think we're looking at the Recreation Center right now because we do have it already Tuesday and Thursday morning.

2929
03:51:03,043 --> 03:51:04,423
[SPEAKER_10]: We have it Saturday mornings.

2930
03:51:05,324 --> 03:51:08,284
[SPEAKER_10]: We just started adding Wednesday night this summer.

2931
03:51:08,404 --> 03:51:18,787
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm actually when I was in the audience, I'm working with some of the staff right now working on schedule, but we're planning and also have a night activities down at the Rec Center for pickleball.

2932
03:51:19,347 --> 03:51:20,469
[SPEAKER_10]: So there is an opportunity.

2933
03:51:20,489 --> 03:51:25,114
[SPEAKER_10]: I didn't necessarily look at Method High School, but down at the Retz Center.

2934
03:51:25,314 --> 03:51:28,117
[SPEAKER_20]: Right now, I think we should strike now.

2935
03:51:28,217 --> 03:51:33,503
[SPEAKER_20]: I mean, that's a moneymaker for the department, right, at this particular moment.

2936
03:51:33,523 --> 03:51:34,884
[SPEAKER_20]: So I hope we strike.

2937
03:51:35,485 --> 03:51:36,845
[SPEAKER_20]: all that great crazy spot.

2938
03:51:37,105 --> 03:51:37,425
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely.

2939
03:51:37,445 --> 03:51:39,946
[SPEAKER_10]: And I've heard that from reading and some of the other departments.

2940
03:51:39,966 --> 03:51:41,606
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, that's actually one of the revenue.

2941
03:51:41,746 --> 03:51:42,207
[SPEAKER_20]: Yeah, exactly.

2942
03:51:42,227 --> 03:51:49,228
[SPEAKER_20]: But I played it a few other cities and they just, you know, they rented out privately, like two hour blocks.

2943
03:51:49,608 --> 03:51:49,808
[SPEAKER_20]: Right?

2944
03:51:51,229 --> 03:51:51,629
[SPEAKER_27]: Thank you.

2945
03:51:53,809 --> 03:51:54,549
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other questions?

2946
03:51:54,849 --> 03:51:57,090
[SPEAKER_27]: Oh, thank you so much.

2947
03:51:58,987 --> 03:52:04,812
[SPEAKER_27]: There's so much programming that you guys do, so hats off to you guys.

2948
03:52:05,512 --> 03:52:13,919
[SPEAKER_27]: I wanted to ask, there's some stuff in here about afterschool recreation programs.

2949
03:52:14,099 --> 03:52:27,169
[SPEAKER_27]: I know Councilor Scarpelli has been a big proponent of finding a way to reach out to city departments and see how we can work together to solve the lack of afterschool spots, especially for elementary and middle schoolers.

2950
03:52:29,201 --> 03:52:38,504
[SPEAKER_27]: I like, I think we all know that there isn't, there isn't the capacity right now to create a huge program or to create a program.

2951
03:52:38,564 --> 03:52:47,666
[SPEAKER_27]: But, um, I was curious as to your kind of like take on how, what would you need to set up a program?

2952
03:52:48,116 --> 03:52:48,956
[SPEAKER_10]: No, it's a great question.

2953
03:52:48,976 --> 03:52:57,359
[SPEAKER_10]: And it's something that has been discussed with myself and with the administration and with the school department about the after school program.

2954
03:52:57,799 --> 03:52:59,200
[SPEAKER_10]: And we've talked to residents as well.

2955
03:52:59,440 --> 03:53:03,521
[SPEAKER_10]: One of the biggest challenges, as we've said before, it's actually two challenges.

2956
03:53:04,121 --> 03:53:07,862
[SPEAKER_10]: One is to find the space, as most many people probably know the rec center.

2957
03:53:08,323 --> 03:53:08,963
[SPEAKER_10]: When we first

2958
03:53:09,623 --> 03:53:11,405
[SPEAKER_10]: moved into that location.

2959
03:53:11,425 --> 03:53:13,767
[SPEAKER_10]: I want to say it was five years ago was the first year.

2960
03:53:14,628 --> 03:53:17,391
[SPEAKER_10]: Um, you know, we weren't at the capacity to run an after school program.

2961
03:53:17,411 --> 03:53:20,294
[SPEAKER_10]: So the Y. M. C. A. Has that.

2962
03:53:21,034 --> 03:53:28,542
[SPEAKER_10]: Um, so it doesn't make sense for us as a rec department to push out the Y. M. C. A. Just to replace it with the rec department.

2963
03:53:29,202 --> 03:53:33,086
[SPEAKER_10]: The Y. Does a great job with it, and it would just be moving one place for the other.

2964
03:53:33,786 --> 03:53:35,686
[SPEAKER_10]: So location is going to be the number one issue.

2965
03:53:36,186 --> 03:53:40,967
[SPEAKER_10]: And as you probably know, the administration has released that they are working on the Hagner Center.

2966
03:53:41,487 --> 03:53:43,668
[SPEAKER_10]: I know that it's not something that's going to happen overnight.

2967
03:53:43,788 --> 03:53:45,208
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, we're looking at the future.

2968
03:53:45,248 --> 03:53:49,649
[SPEAKER_10]: But certainly that place can be used for after school program.

2969
03:53:49,689 --> 03:53:56,070
[SPEAKER_10]: And that's something that because we've had these discussions is our plan to have that space.

2970
03:53:56,530 --> 03:54:00,531
[SPEAKER_10]: We are also looking at the school department to see if there is any other alternatives.

2971
03:54:01,371 --> 03:54:01,571
[SPEAKER_10]: But

2972
03:54:02,355 --> 03:54:12,017
[SPEAKER_10]: certainly if we do have a space, as I was saying with the school department as well, we want to be cognizant that before we start a program, we want to be set up for success.

2973
03:54:12,717 --> 03:54:16,178
[SPEAKER_10]: And that really goes into making sure that we have adequate space.

2974
03:54:16,798 --> 03:54:28,501
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm sure that we can find a classroom, but if you imagine if you have a child that's been in school all day to just be moved over to another classroom, that that's going to get very difficult for our

2975
03:54:30,118 --> 03:54:31,939
[SPEAKER_10]: staff to be able to keep the kids engaged.

2976
03:54:31,999 --> 03:54:35,220
[SPEAKER_10]: So I do want to make sure that we have the adequate space.

2977
03:54:36,180 --> 03:54:41,101
[SPEAKER_10]: Um, and then we have the storage that we have a place that we can actually keep equipment and we can keep fun equipment.

2978
03:54:41,321 --> 03:54:46,543
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, if it's something that we have to transport every single day, you know, that bring comes a challenge as well, too.

2979
03:54:46,983 --> 03:54:53,725
[SPEAKER_10]: So we are looking at that as well for the school department to see if we can get something in for the Hager center actually comes into fruition.

2980
03:54:54,485 --> 03:55:04,472
[SPEAKER_10]: And the second one is staffing, you know, like anywhere else the school department certainly has a challenge trying to find staff to be able to run the actual program.

2981
03:55:04,912 --> 03:55:10,215
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't think the rec department is going to be any different we're going to be in that same looking for the same amount of people.

2982
03:55:11,533 --> 03:55:13,233
[SPEAKER_10]: I do have some kind of plans in place.

2983
03:55:13,333 --> 03:55:23,156
[SPEAKER_10]: I did share that with the administration about how we can try to get a full time, how we can work on that with a revolving account like we do right now with the rest of our programs.

2984
03:55:23,756 --> 03:55:29,918
[SPEAKER_10]: But certainly the first step is we're trying to find, is there a good location?

2985
03:55:30,258 --> 03:55:34,679
[SPEAKER_10]: And then the second part will be, how do we implement of getting the staff to be able to do that?

2986
03:55:48,501 --> 03:55:56,203
[SPEAKER_27]: But yeah, I think in the next, in the following few years, it's something that we'll have to really sit down and really hash out all the options.

2987
03:55:56,503 --> 03:56:01,284
[SPEAKER_10]: And it's certainly a need, and it's something that we would want to be a part of to help with that.

2988
03:56:02,464 --> 03:56:03,745
[SPEAKER_10]: One of our FY 24 goals,

2989
03:56:06,482 --> 03:56:13,666
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't know if you have a copy of it, but one of the things that we did say, at least for this year, is trying to do more after-school programming.

2990
03:56:13,806 --> 03:56:26,072
[SPEAKER_10]: Even if we do it right now, every single day from 3.15 to 4 o'clock, like we were saying, this is a really good test to see how many part-time staff we can get right after school to work for us.

2991
03:56:26,572 --> 03:56:33,596
[SPEAKER_10]: So we think even if we implement that this year, it's gonna give us a better idea on what those staffing challenges will be.

2992
03:56:34,879 --> 03:56:36,820
[SPEAKER_27]: With that program, I'm just curious.

2993
03:56:37,961 --> 03:56:44,086
[SPEAKER_27]: So the 315, what would we know what kids are doing between 2.30 and 3.15?

2994
03:56:45,147 --> 03:56:50,330
[SPEAKER_10]: I think we're looking at that, seeing when kids get out of school.

2995
03:56:50,771 --> 03:56:55,414
[SPEAKER_10]: So if we have a high school student going from high school down to help run the program.

2996
03:56:56,395 --> 03:56:58,296
[SPEAKER_10]: But it doesn't necessarily have to be 3.15.

2997
03:56:58,416 --> 03:56:59,677
[SPEAKER_10]: It could be earlier.

2998
03:57:00,018 --> 03:57:02,980
[SPEAKER_10]: But we're just throwing that number, that timeline.

2999
03:57:03,786 --> 03:57:06,667
[SPEAKER_10]: thinking that we were trying to get some high school kids to help out with that.

3000
03:57:07,047 --> 03:57:07,307
[SPEAKER_27]: Great.

3001
03:57:07,427 --> 03:57:15,310
[SPEAKER_27]: Yeah, no, it's good to hear that we're trying new options and experimenting and seeing if we can get any, you know, any fish to bite.

3002
03:57:15,391 --> 03:57:16,851
[SPEAKER_27]: So thank you.

3003
03:57:18,652 --> 03:57:21,713
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other questions for Weston Bears?

3004
03:57:23,214 --> 03:57:24,254
[SPEAKER_03]: Kevin, just one question.

3005
03:57:24,274 --> 03:57:26,695
[SPEAKER_03]: The travel allowance seems pretty down.

3006
03:57:27,299 --> 03:57:29,180
[SPEAKER_03]: This year is that going to be a problem?

3007
03:57:29,400 --> 03:57:29,960
[SPEAKER_10]: I think it was.

3008
03:57:30,060 --> 03:57:32,460
[SPEAKER_10]: It's just been transferred to a different line.

3009
03:57:32,480 --> 03:57:35,621
[SPEAKER_10]: I think when we were first talking about it.

3010
03:57:35,641 --> 03:57:40,923
[SPEAKER_16]: That was added because it was the French benefits.

3011
03:57:57,080 --> 03:57:59,041
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, for going down, you said?

3012
03:57:59,682 --> 03:58:03,305
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, it looks like it's $37,000 this year and $8,000 next year.

3013
03:58:03,705 --> 03:58:05,586
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a 78% decline.

3014
03:58:05,606 --> 03:58:07,388
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, because of stipends.

3015
03:58:07,468 --> 03:58:10,850
[SPEAKER_10]: You see a large increase on the stipends.

3016
03:58:10,970 --> 03:58:11,270
[SPEAKER_17]: OK.

3017
03:58:11,431 --> 03:58:20,858
[SPEAKER_10]: I think in the past, because last year was the first year we were actually in the contract with the Teamsters, I think the way it was placed originally

3018
03:58:21,718 --> 03:58:28,224
[SPEAKER_10]: just didn't make sense, so the travel should be what the travel amount is.

3019
03:58:28,244 --> 03:58:30,286
[SPEAKER_03]: It was just something that was in a line that shouldn't have been there.

3020
03:58:30,306 --> 03:58:32,408
[SPEAKER_10]: Yeah, and then keeping the stipend separated.

3021
03:58:32,689 --> 03:58:33,009
[SPEAKER_03]: Got it.

3022
03:58:33,129 --> 03:58:33,349
[SPEAKER_03]: Great.

3023
03:58:33,529 --> 03:58:33,930
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

3024
03:58:33,950 --> 03:58:34,590
[SPEAKER_03]: You're welcome.

3025
03:58:34,610 --> 03:58:37,273
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other questions or discussion for recreation?

3026
03:58:40,438 --> 03:58:41,479
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing none.

3027
03:58:41,659 --> 03:58:41,979
[SPEAKER_15]: Thank you.

3028
