3231
04:13:31,545 --> 04:13:36,707
[SPEAKER_19]: If you've over-budgeted your health insurance by millions of dollars, that's going to fall to free cash.

3232
04:13:36,767 --> 04:13:37,488
[SPEAKER_19]: That's a turn back.

3233
04:13:38,902 --> 04:13:40,523
[SPEAKER_19]: when we're looking at our budget.

3234
04:13:40,724 --> 04:13:42,365
[SPEAKER_20]: So what you're saying is?

3235
04:13:43,927 --> 04:13:49,752
[SPEAKER_19]: Rationally looking at the last few years, that should be what we're expected to pay out.

3236
04:13:52,734 --> 04:13:53,755
[SPEAKER_20]: OK.

3237
04:13:53,875 --> 04:13:55,457
[SPEAKER_20]: If we can go back to the pension thing again.

3238
04:13:56,718 --> 04:13:58,740
[SPEAKER_20]: What year did you say the pension was going to be funded by?

3239
04:14:00,261 --> 04:14:00,942
[SPEAKER_20]: I believe it's 2032.

3240
04:14:03,832 --> 04:14:04,312
Thank you.

3241
04:14:04,773 --> 04:14:08,835
[SPEAKER_03]: There's a chart on page 44 that shows how much.

3242
04:14:08,855 --> 04:14:21,362
[SPEAKER_20]: I've been sitting on this council for the last 12 years, and that year keeps changing every year, every year.

3243
04:14:21,382 --> 04:14:24,844
[SPEAKER_20]: It probably changes every two years.

3244
04:14:25,065 --> 04:14:32,209
[SPEAKER_19]: It's an actuarial computation done every two years.

3245
04:14:33,235 --> 04:14:35,856
[SPEAKER_19]: So the next one will be done in January 1st, 2024.

3246
04:14:35,897 --> 04:14:41,820
[SPEAKER_20]: Is that taking the downturn in the market this year?

3247
04:14:42,620 --> 04:14:44,261
[SPEAKER_20]: That will include the downturn in the market.

3248
04:14:44,401 --> 04:14:46,763
[SPEAKER_20]: But is the downturn in the market included in these numbers?

3249
04:14:47,483 --> 04:14:48,203
[SPEAKER_20]: Not yet, no.

3250
04:14:48,684 --> 04:14:49,784
[SPEAKER_20]: So when will we see that?

3251
04:14:50,845 --> 04:14:51,465
[SPEAKER_19]: January 1st, 2024.

3252
04:14:51,745 --> 04:14:58,289
[SPEAKER_19]: That's when the next report comes out, and then that will determine what we're doing.

3253
04:14:58,309 --> 04:15:01,411
[SPEAKER_19]: There are various different scenarios based on

3254
04:15:02,752 --> 04:15:05,134
[SPEAKER_19]: how much we fund now, how much we fund later.

3255
04:15:05,154 --> 04:15:09,237
[SPEAKER_19]: There's also room in there if we want to.

3256
04:15:09,257 --> 04:15:11,098
[SPEAKER_19]: There's four more people retiring every day.

3257
04:15:11,238 --> 04:15:12,999
[SPEAKER_19]: Yes, there are.

3258
04:15:13,019 --> 04:15:24,887
[SPEAKER_19]: But there are different ways to actually, for instance, you could spread the,

3259
04:15:27,512 --> 04:15:35,075
[SPEAKER_19]: because we have till 2037 to fund this fully, we could spread it over more years, lessening the impact to the city.

3260
04:15:35,855 --> 04:15:37,996
[SPEAKER_19]: We could pay it quicker if we wanted to.

3261
04:15:40,557 --> 04:15:50,141
[SPEAKER_19]: The report will come out with what the actuary thinks are the best, his best estimates.

3262
04:15:50,381 --> 04:15:51,701
[SPEAKER_19]: And usually there's,

3263
04:15:54,644 --> 04:15:57,366
[SPEAKER_19]: there will be three or four different scenarios how to fund it.

3264
04:15:57,426 --> 04:16:05,030
[SPEAKER_19]: And then we will discuss that with the mayor and make a determination about what we think is best for the city to fund this.

3265
04:16:06,431 --> 04:16:09,913
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other questions for the council?

3266
04:16:10,314 --> 04:16:14,876
[SPEAKER_03]: Just if you could tell the retirement board to invest in Nvidia stock like three weeks ago.

3267
04:16:16,837 --> 04:16:17,178
[SPEAKER_19]: Well, yes.

3268
04:16:21,038 --> 04:16:24,041
[SPEAKER_19]: or, you know, go back 10 years and get some Bitcoin.

3269
04:16:24,061 --> 04:16:24,921
[SPEAKER_19]: That would be great.

3270
04:16:25,001 --> 04:16:25,302
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes.

3271
04:16:25,522 --> 04:16:31,326
[SPEAKER_03]: I was thinking like minimal time travel on the budget that we have, you know, 10 years we can't afford, maybe three weeks.

3272
04:16:31,967 --> 04:16:32,587
[SPEAKER_19]: Maybe three weeks.

3273
04:16:32,668 --> 04:16:34,489
[SPEAKER_19]: All right, well, I'll work on that.

3274
04:16:34,649 --> 04:16:35,330
[SPEAKER_19]: Thanks, Bob.

3275
04:16:35,970 --> 04:16:37,231
[SPEAKER_15]: Any other questions?

3276
04:16:39,153 --> 04:16:41,395
[SPEAKER_15]: Seeing none, I'll bring you Director Dickinson.

3277
04:16:41,415 --> 04:16:42,255
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

3278
04:16:42,656 --> 04:16:43,616
[SPEAKER_03]: Motion to adjourn.

3279
04:16:44,097 --> 04:16:47,360
[SPEAKER_15]: On the motion of Vice Mayor to adjourn, seconded by Councilor Seng.

3280
04:16:47,400 --> 04:16:48,781
[SPEAKER_15]: Mr. Clerk, please call the roll.

3281
04:17:06,614 --> 04:17:10,927
[SPEAKER_15]: Yes, five in the affirmative, negative two absent, meeting is adjourned.

3282
04:17:12,371 --> 04:17:13,033
[SPEAKER_15]: See everyone next.

